{In this lecture, I will introduce you to the main ideas in the exchange
structure in Ruy Lopez.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {This is the
most direct move. White's plan is straightforward, just to exchange all the
pieces and to win the pawn endgame. I always like to play this position for
Black because the bishop pair fully compensates for the slightly ruined
structure.} dxc6 5. d4 {This move doesn't have a good reputation. It is much
more flexible to start with 5.0-0 and to wait for Black's responce} exd4 6.
Qxd4 (6. Nxd4 c5 7. Ne2 Qxd1+ {and Black is already better, because White's
king is awkwardly placed in the centre}) 6... Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 (7... Bd7 8. Nc3
O-O-O 9. Be3 g6 $5 10. O-O-O Bg7 11. Nde2 Ne7 12. Bd4 f6 $1 {This is a common
idea. Black's keep his bishop pair. The dark-squared bishop is passive now but
has a lot of perspectives on the future.} (12... Bxd4 $5 {is also possible,
and Black should be fine after:} 13. Nxd4 c5 14. Nde2 f5) 13. Kb1 b6 $1 {
[%cal Rc6c5]} 14. f3 c5 15. Bf2 Be6 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 17. Rd1 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 Kd7 (
18... h6) 19. Ne3 f5 $1 {This is a very typical pawn break, after the exchange
of the "f" and "e" pawns Black's bishops become more active.} 20. exf5 Nxf5 21.
Nxf5 Bxf5 {Black has the bishop pair, but his structure is damaged. White
should hold this endgame but needs to defend precisely. I will leave the rest
of the game to enjoy Jussupow's brilliant technique.} 22. Be1 Be6 23. Ng3 h5
24. h4 Be5 25. Nf1 b5 26. Ne3 Kd6 27. c3 c4 28. Kc2 c5 29. a3 Kc6 30. Bf2 a5
31. Be1 Bf4 32. Nf1 Bf5+ 33. Kd1 Bd3 34. Nd2 Kd5 35. Bf2 b4 36. Ke1 Be5 37. Ne4
Bxe4 38. fxe4+ Kxe4 39. Kd2 bxa3 40. bxa3 a4 41. Be1 Kf4 42. Ke2 Kg4 43. Ke3
Bg3 44. Bxg3 Kxg3 45. Ke4 Kxg2 {0-1 (45) Slobodjan,R (2522)-Jussupow,A (2633)
Altenkirchen 2001}) 8. f4 {This move looks active but weakens White's
structure.} f6 9. Be3 Ne7 10. Nd2 Ng6 11. g3 c5 12. N4f3 $6 {The knight is
very passive on f3.} b6 13. O-O Bb7 $15 {This is Black's dream in such
positions. Black has two powerful bishops and an object to attack (e4-pawn).
The plan is to finish the development and find the right moment to open the
game. The obvious pawn break is g7-g5.} 14. Rfe1 O-O-O 15. Bf2 Rhe8 16. Re2 Rd7
17. Rae1 Rde7 {The first part of White's plan is to tiе all White's pieces}
18. h4 {we should remember that any pawn move creates a weakness. This time
the weakness is the square g4.} h5 19. c4 a5 20. a4 Kd7 21. Kf1 Bc6 22. b3 Kc8
23. Re3 Bd7 24. Kg2 c6 25. Nb1 Bc7 26. Nc3 Nh8 $3 {Nice maneuver. The knight
is heading to g4.} 27. Rd3 Nf7 28. Red1 Bg4 29. R1d2 Nh6 30. Bg1 Bb8 31. Bf2
Be6 32. Rd1 Bf7 33. Bg1 Bg6 34. Nd2 Nf7 35. Re1 Bh7 36. Kf3 Nh6 37. Bf2 Ng4 38.
Bg1 g5 $1 {Finally, Black is ready to open the game.} 39. Re2 gxf4 40. gxf4 Rg8
$1 41. Re1 Reg7 42. Ne2 f5 43. exf5 (43. e5 $2 Bxe5 $1 44. fxe5 Nxe5+ $19)
43... Bxf5 44. Ne4 Bxe4+ 45. Kxe4 Re8+ 46. Kf3 Rf7 47. Rdd1 Ref8 48. Rf1 Bxf4
49. Nxf4 Rxf4+ 50. Kg2 Rxf1 51. Rxf1 Rxf1 52. Kxf1 Nh6 53. Ke2 Nf5 54. Bf2 Nd4+
{Transposing to a winning pawn endgame.} 55. Kd3 Nxb3 $19 {the rest is simple}
56. Be3 Kd7 57. Kc3 Nd4 58. Bxd4 cxd4+ 59. Kxd4 Kd6 60. Kd3 Ke5 61. Ke3 c5 0-1

