1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O (5. Nc3 {There are many
games with this move, but in my opinion, it didn't pose any serious problems
and Black gets a good play with natural moves. There are many possible plans
for Black. As always in the exchange structure, understanding the ideas means
more than concrete moves.} f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 {this doesn't change
much} c5 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1 Be6 10. Bf4 O-O-O 11. Ne3 Ne7 12. h4 Nc6 {
0-1 (69) Zubarev,A (2444)-Ivanisevic,I (2606) Chess.com INT 2021}) 7... Qxd4 8.
Nxd4 Bd7 9. Be3 O-O-O 10. O-O-O c5 11. Nde2 Re8 12. Bf4 Ne7 13. h4 Ng6 14. Bg3
h5 15. Nf4 Ne5 16. Rhe1 c4 17. Ncd5 Bc6 18. f3 Bd6 {0-1 (72) Stojanovski,D 
(2405)-Georgiev,V (2576)/Skopje FRM 2007}) (5. d4 {This move, as we already
know, is inaccurate and a small mistake} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 {
let's remind you of the plan once again. Black wants to play Bd7, 0-0-0,
followed by Rde8, Bb4, and f5 in an appropriate moment.} 8. Nc3 O-O-O 9. Be3
Re8 10. O-O-O Bb4 11. Nde2 f5 $17 {The bishops are just too powerful} 12. exf5
Bxf5 13. a3 Bd6 14. Bf4 Bc5 15. Bg3 Nf6 16. f3 Nd5 17. Nd4 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Bxa3+
19. Kb1 Bd7 20. Rhe1 Bd6 {0-1 Saket,K (1972)-Iuldachev,S (2520)/Gurgon IND
2009/The Week in Chess 742}) 5... Qf6 {This is my favorite way to meet the
exchange variation. Black is preparing Bd7 (or Bg4 in some cases) followed by
0-0-0.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 {This move can't pose any serious problems. Now
Black just exchange queens and enjoy the endgame, which we saw in the previous
game. White is with a tempo up, but this didn't change the evaluation of the
position. Black has at least equal chances, in my opinion, is even slightly
better.} (7. Bg5 {This is probably the most serious test. White is getting
tempo before taking on "d4"} Qd6 8. Nxd4 (8. Qxd4 Qxd4 $1 9. Nxd4 Bd7 {the
same endgame over and over again. I put a lot of model games in the commentary,
which you can study. I played this position a hundred times and find with some
slight differences.} 10. Nc3 (10. Nd2 f6 11. Be3 O-O-O 12. f4 Nh6 13. h3 Bb4
14. c3 Bd6 15. Rae1 Rhe8 16. Kh1 c5 17. N4b3 b6 $17 {0-1 (40) Denny,K (2334)
-Mihalcisin,A (2512)/Calvia ESP 2004}) 10... f6 (10... Ne7 11. Rad1 O-O-O 12.
Rd2 f6 13. Be3 Ng6 14. Rfd1 Bb4 15. Nde2 Ne5 16. b3 Rde8 $15 {1/2-1/2 Vysochin,
S (2520)-Fedorchuk,S (2603)/Warsaw POL 2008/The Week in Chess 737}) 11. Be3
O-O-O 12. Rad1 g6 13. Rd3 Nh6 14. Bxh6 Bxh6 15. Rfd1 Rhe8 16. Nde2 b5 $15 {
1/2-1/2 (58) Solak,D (2630)-Atalik,S (2592)/Kocaeli TUR 2008/The Week in Chess
712}) 8... Bd7 9. Nc3 Ne7 $5 (9... Be7 $5) 10. Qd2 {[%cal Rd2e3] again the
idea is to keep the queens on the board, so Black hurry up and exchange the
queens} (10. Be3 {White is threatening to play Qd2 followed by Rd1, so Black
is in a hurry to exchange queens} c5 $1 11. Nde2 Qxd1 12. Raxd1 b6 13. Nf4
O-O-O 14. Nfd5 Ng6 $11 {[%cal Rh7h5,Rd7e6,Rf8d6,Rc8b7] 0-1 (47) Tan,M (2321)
-Negi,P (2597)/Hoogeveen NED 2008/The Week in Chess 729}) (10. Nb3 Qxd1 11.
Raxd1 Ng6 $1 12. Be3 b6 $1 {not allowing White to exchange pieces} 13. f4 O-O-O
14. a3 f6 15. Nd4 Bd6 16. g3 h5 $15 {1/2-1/2 (42) Volokitin,A (2671)-Caruana,F
(2646)/Wijk aan Zee NED 2009/The Week in Chess 741}) 10... c5 $1 11. Nb3 Qxd2
12. Bxd2 b6 13. a4 O-O-O 14. Be3 a5 15. Bf4 f6 16. Rfd1 g5 17. Bg3 Bg7 $17 {
0-1 (29) Iuldachev,S (2520)-Sethuraman,S (2415)/New Delhi IND 2009/The Week in
Chess 741}) (7. Nxd4 {It is better to include Bg5, now Black can just proceed
with his plan and the queen on f6 is very well placed} Bd7 8. c3 O-O-O 9. Nd2
c5 10. Nc2 Ne7 11. Qf3 Qg6 12. Nc4 Qe6 13. Qe2 f5 14. e5 {when White's pawn is
already on e5, Black has an excellent play. The e5-pawn is weak and we have
the d5-square at our disposal.} h6 $17 {0-1 (31) Haznedaroglu,K (2498)
-Sasikiran,K (2653)/Bursa TUR 2010}) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Nc3 (9. Be3 O-O-O
10. Nd2 Ne7 11. Nc4 b6 12. Rfd1 c5 13. Nb3 Be6 14. Rxd8+ Kxd8 15. Rd1+ Kc8 16.
Ne5 f6 17. Nf3 Nc6 18. c3 a5 $19 {and the higher rated player converts his
advantage to a win later on 0-1 (37) Straarup,E (1998)-Ovsejevitsch,S (2582)/
Esbjerg DEN 2008}) 9... O-O-O 10. Be3 Re8 11. Rfd1 Bb4 12. Nde2 f5 13. Bd4 Nf6
{The triumph of Black's strategy} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 $17 15. f3 fxe4 16. Nxe4 f5 17.
N4g3 h5 18. Nf4 h4 19. Nge2 h3 20. g3 Bc5+ 21. Nd4 Bd6 22. Kf2 Rhg8 23. Nde2 a5
24. a4 Rg7 25. Nxh3 Rh7 26. Neg1 Bc5+ 27. Kf1 Bxg1 28. Nxg1 Rxh2 29. Rac1 c5
30. b3 c4 31. Re1 Rxe1+ 32. Kxe1 cxb3 33. cxb3 Rb2 34. Rc3 Be6 35. Ne2 Bxb3 36.
Nd4 Bxa4 37. Nxf5 b5 38. g4 b4 39. Rc5 b3 40. Nd6+ Kd7 41. Nc4 Ra2 42. Rxa5 Bc6
43. Ne5+ Kc8 {0-1 Marholev,D (2423)-Radulski,J (2592)/Kyustendil BUL 2010/The
Week in Chess 806} *

[Event "St Petersburg International Final"]
[Site "St Petersburg"]
[Date "1914.05.18"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Lasker"]
[Black "Capablanca"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev, GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "83"]
[EventDate "1914.05.10"]
[EventRounds "10"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]

{Lasker's choice to play 5.d4 against a great endgame expert like Capablanca
may seem strange, and it would hardly make sense without a concrete idea in
mind: To play f2-f4 and later f4-f5. The idea was probably borrowed from
Alekhine, who utilized it successfully in the same tournament. But this is how
chess was developing in the first half of the 20th century. Now, let's take a
look at this memorable game. No story about Lasker's chess career is complete
without it. The young Cuban genius, Capablanca, was playing easily and
convincingly in this tournament, probably the strongest ever held until that
time. Lasker, as usual, began quite slowly and, with just four rounds to go,
he was trailing a full point behind Capablanca, whom he was desperately trying
to catch. His last chance to fight for tournament victory was to beat the
leader. (G. Kasparov)} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {(!) A very
surprising choice. The Exchange Variation of the Ruy Lopez was a dangerous
weapon in Lasker's hands. But nobody in the audience and amongst the
participants believed that this quiet opening would work against Capablanca,
whose excellent technique was already widely recognised. With the charming
self-confidence of youth, Jose Raoul unfortunately shared this misconception
and did not recognise Lasker's real intentions. (Garry Kasparov). This is only
partially true, as the real surprise is not 4.Bxc6 but 5.d4. More concretely,
the novel idea was the treatment of the endgame with a quick f2-f4.} dxc6 5. d4
{If we count only serious games - world championships and international
tournaments, Lasker played like this only five times in his chess career. From
these five games he lost one, in 1894 against Steinitz, and won 3 - against
Tarrasch (game 5) and two times against Janowski. Invariably he played f2-f3
and in all those games he got either worse or equal endgames. The reason he
chooses the line one more time and also at such a decisive moment was exactly
the idea that he learned from his game against Alekhine: The quick f2-f4-f5.
This approach - to take the other players' ideas from the same tournaments and
immediately adopt them against the next opponents, was used by many strong
players - one of them who mastered this at a very high level is the great
Anand.} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd6 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. O-O $1 {This move passed
unnoticed by Garry Kasparov in his comment. Castling short in this position
might have been a revolutionary approach at this time. Usually White's king
stayed in the centre or castled long. The idea of this move probably came to
Lasker because in his game against Alekhine, White had trouble defending the
g2 pawn, so Lasker now defends it immediately.} O-O 10. f4 $1 {This move marks
the start of a plan which was completely new at this time - 1914. Instead of
fighting for the d-file and looking for exchanges, White immediately advances
his pawn majority. This is definitely the more demanding and risky plan, but
the main point is that it was still unknown and also the defence against it
was very difficult to find, even for the greatest endgame expert of his time.
This was actually the main reason for his uncertainty and instability with
which he played the rest of the game. Who dares wins! By adopting this new
approach, Lasker gave the world an unforgettable masterpiece, which now, more
than 100 years later, is still an example of the realisation of space
advantage in the endgame.} Re8 ({Of course for us, players from the 21st
century, it looks obvious to find the blockading idea} 10... f5 11. e5 Bc5 12.
Be3 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 b6 {, when despite the passed pawn only Black can be better.}
) 11. Nb3 {Removing the hanging knight and taking the c5-square under control
- exactly what Alekhine did in his game.} f6 {Of course only Black can be
better here according to modern endgame understanding.} (11... Ng6 {is also
good.}) 12. f5 $1 {Under the classical rules of the Steinitz positional school,
this move has to be damned. White gets a weak pawn on e4, Black a stronghold
on e5, with a devaluation of White's pawn advantage on the kingside - too many
negative points for just one move. But Lasker's eagle eye had seen much
further. (G.K) This move is a strong psychological weapon. Black's pieces are
severely restricted - the knight on e7 has no future and the Bc8 needs to find
a better diagonal. But its abovementioned disadvantages are also quite real.
You may play hundreds of games even against much weaker opponents and possibly
never make the plan work which Lasker convincingly realised in this game. But
Capablanca was under psychological pressure to find a concrete response. Being
under pressure, even strong players make such errors - they just lose their
confidence and start exaggerating their opponents' ideas, adopting passive
approaches and committing unbelievable positional mistakes, which under normal
circumstances they would never do. To embarrass the opponent by creating a
psychologically unpleasant situation became a trademark for many world
champions and strong players like Tal, Kortschnoj, Kasparov Kramnik, and
Topalov.} b6 {And here} 13. Bf4 Bb7 $2 {This was the first error, which passed
the advantage to White. There was no need to create a weakness on d6. After
the obvious} (13... Bxf4 $1 14. Rxf4 c5 $1 15. Rd1 Bb7 16. Rf2 Rad8 17. Rfd2 (
17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Rd2 Rxd2 19. Nxd2 Nc6) {or} 17... Rxd2 18. Rxd2 Nc6 19. Rd7
Rc8 {, and after Ne5 Black is fine. This plan was later recommended by
Capablanca.}) 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nd4 Rad8 $2 {Capablanca doesn't take White's
plan serious. The knight on e6 will be a bone in his throat, so 15...Bc8 was
obligatory. (GK) But here to play Bc8 is somewhat inhuman.} 16. Ne6 Rd7 17.
Rad1 Nc8 18. Rf2 b5 19. Rfd2 Rde7 20. b4 $1 {This was the only move to defend
against Black's plan to release the pressure by b5-b4, Nb6 and d6-d5.} Kf7 21.
a3 Ba8 $2 (21... Rxe6 22. fxe6+ Rxe6 {would have given him the best fighting
chances.}) 22. Kf2 Ra7 23. g4 $1 {After installing the knight on e6, White is
trying to create a weakness on the kingside in order to activate his rooks} h6
24. Rd3 a5 $2 25. h4 axb4 26. axb4 Rae7 27. Kf3 Rg8 28. Kf4 g6 29. Rg3 (29. g5
hxg5+ 30. hxg5 $18) 29... g5+ {It's too late for good advice.} (29... gxf5 {
doesn't offer any relief:} 30. exf5 d5 31. g5 $1 hxg5+ 32. hxg5 fxg5+ 33. Nxg5+
Kf8 34. f6 Ra7 35. Ke5 $1) 30. Kf3 Nb6 {A desperate try.} 31. hxg5 hxg5 32. Rh3
$1 {Lasker continues to execute his plan without any diversions.} (32. Rxd6 {
would have given Black some extra breathing time.} Nc4 33. Rd1 Rh8) 32... Rd7 (
32... Nc4 33. Ra1 {The combined invasion of the white rooks on the a- and
h-files demolished Black's defence.}) 33. Kg3 {The final preparation.} Ke8 34.
Rdh1 Bb7 35. e5 $1 $18 {It's amazing that with so many pieces Black wasn't
able to prevent this pawn from going ahead!} dxe5 36. Ne4 Nd5 37. N6c5 Bc8 38.
Nxd7 Bxd7 39. Rh7 Rf8 40. Ra1 Kd8 41. Ra8+ Bc8 42. Nc5 {Black resigned, and
the old chess wizard Lasker had become the winner of this historical contest.
The psychological effect of this brilliant victory was long-lasting. A shaken
Capablanca lost with White in the next round to Dr Tarrasch. And even seven
years later, in his world championship match against Lasker, he never played 3.
..a6 in the Ruy Lopez! (GK) It was really impressive to see Capablanca's
execution in this highly important game. And it was amazing to see the match
from 1921, when he won the title. Capablanca met the Ruy Lopez with the
Steinitz Defence 3...d6, which gave him completely passive positions, typical
for this line. But he successfully avoided the Exchange Variation and was
awarded for his stoicism with the championship title!} 1-0

[Event "FIDE World Cup"]
[Site "Tromso"]
[Date "2013.08.17"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Adhiban, B."]
[Black "Nakamura, Hi"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C68"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev, GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "84"]
[EventDate "2013.08.11"]
[EventRounds "7"]
[EventCountry "NOR"]

{This game was played at the 2013 Fide World Cup in Tromso. Black is one of
the favourites of the tournament while White is also a strong player, who will
soon become one of the best from India, right after Anand and Harikrishna. We
were teammates in Spanish team championships for more than five years and he
amazed me mostly by his aggressive, combinative style and his seemingly
infinite energy and fighting spirit. Here for some unknown reason he chose to
challenge Nakamura in the Exchange Spanish. Was that an inspired decision?
Let's take a look the game and judge for ourselves.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 f6 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1
Be6 10. Bf4 O-O-O {is the theoretical continuation.}) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9.
Be3 O-O-O 10. O-O-O {This position is completely harmless for Black, which was
proved in many games before.} Ne7 (10... Bb4 {will be met by} 11. Nde2 Ne7 12.
a3 Bd6 13. Bf4) ({The well-known equaliser is} 10... Bd6 {Spassky,B-Antoshin,V
Sochi 1966} 11. Nb3 Ne7 12. Nc5 Ng6 13. Nxd7 Rxd7 14. f3 Re8 (14... Nh4 $1 {
Putting some pressure on White's pawns.} 15. Rd2 g5 16. Rf2 Re8 17. g3 Ng6) 15.
g3 Ne5 16. Rhf1 Red8 {Even if White manages to trade the knight for the
light-squared bishop, all the endgames are easy to defend because of the
activity of all black pieces.}) 11. Nb3 b6 12. f4 {I analysed a very similar
position in the Endgame and Historical sections.} Ng6 13. a3 {With the idea to
avoid Bb4, which will expose the e4-pawn.} c5 $1 {Limiting the Nb3 and Be3 and
preparing Bc6 to pressure the weak pawn e4.} 14. Rhf1 Bd6 15. Nd2 Rhe8 16. Nc4
Bf8 $1 {Black completed his setup and it is now up to White to show his hand.}
17. f5 $5 {Inspired by Lasker's and Fischer's games, which however didn't
really prove that f4-f5 is that strong.} Nh8 $1 {You do not often see that
moving the knight into the corner is much stronger than centralising it. This
might be an idea for a further article - Centralisation vs Decentralisation.} (
17... Ne5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. Bf4 Ree8 20. g4 Bc6 21. Rxd8+ Kxd8 22. Re1 b5 {
also promises White no more than equality.}) 18. a4 {Trying to stop b5-b4,
which is vital for the survival of the central pawn e4.} Nf7 19. Bf4 b5 $1 20.
axb5 axb5 21. Nd2 Bc6 22. Rde1 Nd6 $1 ({It was already possible to win a pawn.
} 22... b4 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. exd5 Rxe1+ 25. Rxe1 Rxd5 26. Re8+ Rd8 27. Rxd8+
Kxd8 $17) 23. Bxd6 {A sad necessity.} Bxd6 24. g3 Be5 25. Nd1 {This equals
resignation, as such passive moves only postpone the inevitable. Black's
bishop pair is ruling over the board while White's knights and rooks create a
pitiful impression.} Kb7 26. Nf3 Bd6 27. Nf2 Ra8 $1 28. Kd2 Ra2 (28... Red8) (
28... b4) 29. Ra1 $1 {Grabbing the chance to trade a pair of rooks for the
price of one pawn.} Rxa1 30. Rxa1 Bxe4 31. Nxe4 Rxe4 32. Kd3 (32. Re1 Rxe1 33.
Kxe1 Kc6 34. Ke2 Kd5 35. Ke3 h5 $19 {should be easily winning.}) 32... Rb4 33.
Kc3 Kc6 34. Rd1 g5 $1 {Playing for second weakness - a typical tool in the
realisation of the advantage.} 35. fxg6 hxg6 36. b3 g5 $1 $19 37. Rf1 g4 38.
Nd2 Rd4 $3 {Immediate execution - such an idea is easy to miss, but not for a
player like Nakamura!} 39. Nb1 Be5 $1 {Creating a devastating threat.} 40. Rf5
Rd8+ 41. Rxe5 b4+ 42. Kb2 fxe5 {One more game in which f4-f5 didn't impress
too much.} 0-1

[Event "24th ECC"]
[Site "Kallithea GRE"]
[Date "2008.10.19"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Hracek, Z.."]
[Black "Svidler, P.."]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C85"]
[WhiteElo "2613"]
[BlackElo "2727"]
[Annotator "GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "33"]
[EventDate "2008.10.17"]
[EventType "team"]
[EventRounds "7"]
[EventCountry "GRE"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Bxc6 {This is so-called
Delayed Exchange variation. It is trendy nowadays. It seems that White loses a
tempo with Bb5-a4-c6, but on the other hand, Black plays Nf6 and Be7. Both
moves don't fit Black's strategy in this structure very well.} dxc6 {This is
the starting position and White is on a crossroad. The e4-pawn is hanging and
White has to do something about it. White has two main plans in this position.
The first one is to prepare and open the game by means of d4 and the other one
is to start a kingside play with f2-f4. The recent trend in similar structures
for White is to castle long and to start pushing his kingside pawns. Black
wants to maneuver his knight to e6 (via f8 or c5) and usually, he waits with
castling. Very often, Black's monarch feels more comfortable on the queenside.
The other maneuver which you should know is Nf6-d7-b8-c6. Some of the arising
positions are quite sharp.} 7. d3 {The most natural and flexible move. Now,
Bg4 is not that dangerous because Nbd2 will well meet it} (7. Qe1 {the idea of
this move is to avoid the nasty pin Bg4, but the move is a bit artificial. I
think Black can get a decent play by just proceeding with his plan} Nd7 8. b3
c5 {stopping d4} 9. Bb2 Bd6 10. Nc3 Nf8 11. Nd5 {I can't see the idea of this
movie. Now Black is just better with simple moves} Ng6 12. d3 Be6 13. Ne3 f6
14. c3 O-O 15. d4 {Black is fully developed and this break doesn't give White
any benefits.} cxd4 16. cxd4 Qe8 {0-1 (36) Horvath,T (2430)-Ragger,M (2530)/
Jenbach AUT 2008}) (7. Re1 {This natural move is not very good here. The rook
has nothing to do with the e-file. It is often better placed on "f1" because
it supports the f4-break.} Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 (8... Bh5 $5 {[%cal Rd8d6,Re8c8,
Rf6d7] This is more ambitious} 9. g4 $6 Nxg4 $1 10. hxg4 Bxg4 $44 {This is a
very typical sacrifice and Black should always consider it.}) 9. Qxf3 O-O 10.
d3 Nd7 11. b3 Nc5 12. Bb2 f6 13. Nd2 Ne6 {Both d4 and f4 are not working and
Black enjoys a nice game} 14. Qd1 Bc5 15. Nf3 Qd7 16. a4 Rad8 17. Ba3 Bxa3 $15
{1/2-1/2 (31) Ermenkov,E (2465)-Isaev,J  (2400)/Dresden GER 2008/The Week in
Chess 733}) (7. Nxe5 Nxe4 8. Qe2 Nd6 9. Re1 Nf5 10. c3 O-O 11. d4 c5 $15 {
Black is already better due to his bishop pair ½-½ (21) Kholmov,R-Robatsch,K/
Havana 1965/MCD/[K]}) (7. Qe2 c5 $5 (7... Bg4 $5) 8. d3 (8. Nxe5 Qd4 9. Nf3
Qxe4 10. Qxe4 Nxe4 11. d3 Nf6 12. Re1 h6 13. Bf4 Nd5 14. Be5 f6 15. Nc3 Nxc3
16. Bxc3 Kf7 $15 {0-1 Xie Jun-Nikolic,P/Monaco blind 1996 (33)}) 8... Nd7 9.
Nbd2 O-O 10. Nc4 Bd6 11. Nfd2 Nb8 {[%cal Rd7b8,Rb8c6,Rc6d4]} 12. f4 exf4 13. e5
$2 {Is a strategical mistake. As we know, this move is very often in Black's
favor.} (13. Nxd6 Qxd6 14. Nc4 Qd4+ 15. Kh1 Be6 $11) 13... Be7 14. Rxf4 Nc6 15.
Nf3 Be6 {Black won a nice game in 0-1 (30) Sutovsky,E (2565)-Adams,M (2685)
Tilburg 1996 CBM 056 [Wedberg,T]}) (7. Nc3 {Is also not very good. The c6-pawn
dominates the knight on c3 and also now Bg4 would be a very unpleasant pin} Bg4
8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 (9. d3 Nd7 10. Be3 f6) 9... Nxg4 $1 {This sacrifice works well
here.} 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. Kg2 f5 {The engine said that this is the killer move
here, all other natural moves also keep the initiative} (11... Qd6 12. Qe2 h5
$44) 12. exf5 (12. Qe1 $5 Bxf3+ 13. Kxf3 f4 $15 {[%cal Rg7g5,Rh7h5]}) 12... Qc8
$19) 7... Nd7 $1 (7... Qd6 $5 {is a tricky way to handle the position,
intending to play Be6 followed by 0-0-0, Nbd7 and an active play on the
queenside.} 8. Nbd2 ({The direkt} 8. d4 $2 {doesn't work} Bg4 $1 9. dxe5 Qxd1
10. Rxd1 Nxe4 $15) 8... Be6 9. b3 Nd7 10. Bb2 O-O-O $1 11. Re1 (11. a4 g5 $1
12. Ba3 c5 13. Nc4 Bxc4 14. dxc4 Qg6 15. Qe2 g4 $15) 11... g5 12. Nc4 Bxc4 13.
dxc4 Qe6 14. Qe2 g4 15. Nd2 h5 $17 {Black has a free attack 0-1 (49) Kabanov,N
(2510)-Kurnosov,I (2668)/Moscow RUS 2010}) 8. b3 (8. Nbd2 O-O 9. Nc4 f6 10. Nh4
Nc5 {This is the main line} (10... Re8 11. Nf5 Bf8 12. f4 g6 $6 {I don't like
to soften the structure on the kingside. In my opinion White is slightly
better here.} 13. Ng3 exf4 14. Bxf4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (19) Edouard,R (2531)
-Saravanan,V (2417)/Palma de Mallorca ESP 2008/The Week in Chess 736}) ({
the direct} 10... Nb6 {is also interesting} 11. Ne3 g6 12. Nf3 c5 {Black
starts counterplay in the centre} 13. a4 Be6 14. a5 Nc8 {[%cal Rc8d6]} 15. c3 {
after this move Black has good counterplay against the d3-pawn.} Nd6 16. Qc2
Nb5 17. Ra4 Qd7 18. Rd1 Rfd8 $15 {0-1 (47) Akshayraj, K (2399)-Koneru,H (2612)/
Kolkata IND 2008}) 11. Be3 (11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. exf5 Qd7 {With approximately
equal position ½-½ (35) Naroditsky,D (2621)-Firouzja,A  (2749) Chess.com INT
2021}) 11... Rf7 {remember this maneuver. Black's bishop is going to f8} 12.
Nf5 Bf8 13. Kh1 Be6 14. Nd2 Qd7 15. Ng3 b5 16. f4 exf4 17. Bxf4 a5 18. Be3 Nb7
19. Nf3 c5 20. Qe1 Re8 21. b3 c4 {Black is just in time with his counterplay
in the centre 0-1 (43) Kengis,E (2445)-Tseshkovsky,V  (2505)/Soviet Union 1984/
EXT 2000}) 8... O-O 9. Bb2 f6 10. Nbd2 Nc5 11. Nc4 Rf7 (11... Be6 12. Re1 $6 (
12. Ne3 $1) 12... Bxc4 $1 {White shouldn't allow this exhange, now Black is
just better.} 13. dxc4 (13. bxc4 Na4 {[%cal Rb7b5]}) 13... Qxd1 14. Raxd1 Rfd8
(14... Bd6 $15 {[%cal Rb7b5,Rc5e6]}) 15. Ba3 Kf7 16. Bxc5 Bxc5 $11 {Black
can't attack the e4-pawn with a minor piece and the game went to a draw after
a few moves. ½-½ (31) Petrov,M (2483)-Radulski,J (2578)/ Borovets BUL 2008})
12. Ne3 a5 13. a4 Ne6 14. Kh1 c5 15. Ng1 b6 16. Ne2 Bd6 17. Nc4 1/2-1/2

[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
[Site "Berlin"]
[Date "2018.03.12"]
[Round "3"]
[White "Aronian, L."]
[Black "Kramnik, V."]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C65"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev, GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "54"]
[EventDate "2018.03.10"]
[EventRounds "14"]
[EventCountry "GER"]
[EventCategory "22"]

1. e4 {Aronian already surprises with his first move!} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6
4. d3 Bc5 5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. O-O Qe7 {Black's idea, as described by Kramnik in
his annotations, is that if White delays h2-h3, Black also holds back with the
move Nf6-d7 and first develops his bishop. For example 7.Nbd2 Bg4 8.h3 Bh5 9.
Nc4 Nd7. In my opinion, this is an ideal setup for Black, in which he has
hardly any problems.} 7. h3 $6 {After this game it became common knowledge
that combining h2-h3 and 0-0 is suicidal. But the refutation is not that
obvious.} Rg8 $1 {Black wants to save a tempo on h7-h6.} 8. Kh1 Nh5 $5 (8... h6
9. Nbd2 g5 10. Nc4 g4 11. Nfxe5 h5 12. d4 Bd6 13. Re1 gxh3 {, and White is
still hanging on. The knight move is more ambitious.}) 9. c3 $6 {The most
natural, but an unfortunate reaction.} ({The engine recommends} 9. Nh2 {
, but after Black plays} g6 {and prepares to castle long, his position is just
perfect.}) (9. Nc3 g5 10. Nxe5 g4 11. d4 Bd6 12. g3 Bxe5 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. h4
Bd7 {The position is still more or less level, but playing it with Black is
considerably more pleasant: He will castle long and have the initiative while
White's king and light squares are weak.}) 9... g5 10. Nxe5 ({After} 10. d4 {
the right move is} exd4 $1 (10... g4 $5 11. hxg4 Bxg4 12. dxc5 Qf6) 11. cxd4
Bb6 12. Nh2 Nf6 13. e5 Nd5 {It is clear that White has lost the opening duel.})
10... g4 11. d4 {This is obviously the only move.} (11. hxg4 $4 Qh4+ 12. Kg1
Ng3) 11... Bd6 12. g3 Bxe5 ({Best was to complete development with} 12... Be6
$1 {, and if} 13. hxg4 $2 Bxe5 {, White will soon be mated. Otherwise Black
plays 0-0-0 and obtains a powerful attack in return for the pawn.}) 13. dxe5
Qxe5 14. Qd4 $1 {The most logical continuation.} (14. Kh2) (14. h4 Be6 {
The threat is to capture on g3 when} 15. Kh2 {can at least be met with} Qxe4 {
, winning a pawn.}) 14... Qe7 $5 ({It was possible to enter an endgame with an
extra pawn, but Kramnik is playing for more.} 14... Qxd4 15. cxd4 gxh3 16. Kh2
Be6) 15. h4 c5 $1 {The idea behind this move is to transfer the bishop to c6,
castle and then start the attack with f7-f5. The knight does not look best
placed on h5, but in the event of play on the light squares it will not be
possible for White to hold on to the pawn on e4, whilst the white king is very
weak.} 16. Qc4 $2 {The decisive mistake.} (16. Qd5 Nf6 {.}) (16. Qd3 Bd7 17. c4
O-O-O 18. Nc3 Rge8 19. Re1 Bc6 $40) 16... Be6 17. Qb5+ c6 18. Qa4 (18. Qe2 f5
19. Bg5 Rxg5 20. hxg5 f4 {does not help much either - it's only a slightly
better version of what happened in the game.}) ({The computer recommends} 18.
Qd3 Rd8 19. Qe3 (19. Qe2 f5) 19... Bc4 20. Rg1 (20. Re1 Rd3 21. Qh6 Qe5) 20...
Rg6 21. Qe1 Bd3 $19) 18... f5 $1 19. Bg5 (19. exf5 Nxg3+ $1 20. fxg3 Bd5+ 21.
Kg1 Qe2 22. Rf2 Qe1+ {with mate.}) 19... Rxg5 $1 {This move can hardly be
considered a sacrifice. .} 20. hxg5 f4 {White has no counterplay and will
simply be mated.} 21. Qd1 Rd8 {Of course 21...fxg3 also wins.} 22. Qc1 fxg3 23.
Na3 Rd3 $1 24. Rd1 Bd5 $1 (24... Rxd1+ 25. Qxd1 gxf2) 25. f3 (25. exd5 Qe4+ 26.
Kg1 gxf2+ $19) 25... gxf3 26. exd5 (26. Rxd3 Qxe4 $1 27. Re3 f2+ 28. Rxe4+
Bxe4#) 26... Qe2 $1 27. Re1 (27. Qc2 g2+ 28. Kh2 g1=Q+ 29. Kxg1 f2+ 30. Kh2 {
, and here the simplest is} Rh3+ $1 31. Kxh3 Qf3+ 32. Kh4 Qg3+ 33. Kxh5 Qh3# {
Again very beautiful.}) 27... g2+ {White resigned. This is the immortal (or
evergreen) game of the 21st century.} 0-1

[Event "9th London Classic 2017"]
[Site "London ENG"]
[Date "2017.12.06"]
[Round "5.1"]
[White "Caruana, F."]
[Black "Anand, V."]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C48"]
[Annotator "GM Aleksander Delchev, GM Petar G. Arnaudov"]
[PlyCount "77"]
[EventDate "2017.12.01"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "ENG"]
[EventCategory "22"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. Nc3 $5 {Nowadays it is not at all
easy to trouble the Berlin Defence. Having unsuccessfully tried all the
classical ways, now White is going back to long-forgotten lines by combining
the Spanish with the Four Knights. The main idea of 5.Nc3 is to wait for Black
to castle short and raise the tension on the kingside. Later on, White may
castle long, but there is also the option of leaving the king in the centre,
to ensure oneself against possible counterattacks on the queenside.} O-O {
Anand is going for the mainline. Of course Black can avoid the aforementioned
plan.} (5... a6 $5 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. Nxe5 Qd4 (7... Bxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Qd4+ 9. Be3
Qxe5 10. h3 O-O 11. Rf1 Rd8 12. Qf3) 8. Be3 Qxe5 9. d4 Qe7 10. dxc5 Nxe4 11.
Qd4 Bf5 12. O-O-O {Karjakin- Onischuk Baku 2015. Although Black is not lost,
he will not have an easy time defending his slightly worse opposite-coloured
bishop ending.}) (5... d6 6. Na4 $5 {gains the bishop pair, but I am doubtful
that this is sufficient for an advantage.} Bb6 7. Nxb6 axb6 8. c3 Bd7 9. Ba4
Ne7 $1 (9... O-O 10. Bc2 Ne7 11. Bg5 Ng6 12. h4 $1 {Short,N -Aronian,L
Reykjavik 2004}) 10. Bc2 Ng6 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O {, and Black didn't have any
problems in Carlsen,M -Anand,V London 2012}) 6. Bxc6 $1 dxc6 7. h3 ({One idea
worth analysing is} 7. Bg5 $5 {Bartel,M -Balogh,C Budapest 2014} h6 8. Bh4 Bg4
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Be7 11. g4 $1 Nd7 12. Bg3 Bh4 13. O-O-O $40 {This is
analysed in the theoretical section.}) (7. Be3 $5 {is also worthy of attention.
Look at the following performance by Carlsen at the recent online top event.}
Bd6 (7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 Re8 9. h3 {White would have all the play}) 8. Bg5 $1 Qe7
(8... Re8 9. h3 c5 10. Nd5 {Carlsen,M -Karjakin,S /Riadh 2017}) 9. h3 Re8 10.
g4 Qe6 11. Nh4 Nd7 12. Nf5 Nc5 13. h4 Bf8 14. h5 f6 15. Be3 Qf7 16. f4 exf4 17.
Bxf4 b5 18. Qf3 Ne6 19. Be3 Bb7 20. O-O-O b4 21. Na4 c5 22. h6 g6 23. Ng7 $1 {
, with a decisive attack for White in Carlsen,M -Grischuk,A chess24.com 2020})
7... Nd7 ({In a later game, Grischuk shows the right move order.} 7... Re8 {
Caruana,F -Grischuk,A Saint Louis 2017} 8. Ne2 (8. Be3 {Dominguez Perez,L -So,
W Saint Louis 2017} Bd6 9. Ne2 c5 10. Ng3) 8... Nd7 9. Be3 Bb4+ 10. c3 Bf8 11.
Qc2 c5 12. O-O-O Nb8 13. Ng3 Nc6 14. Kb1 f6 15. Nf5 Qd7 16. g4 Qf7 17. Rhg1 Be6
18. b3 Kh8 19. g5 a5 {, and it looks like Black's attack develops faster.}) 8.
Be3 Bd6 ({In case of} 8... Bxe3 9. fxe3 Re8 10. Qe2 $1 Nf8 11. Qf2 $1 {,
preparing Nh4-f5,} Ng6 12. O-O-O $1 b5 13. g4 a5 14. g5 a4 15. h4 b4 16. h5 Nf8
17. Nb1 Ra5 18. g6 $1 {, and White is the first to break open the kingside.}
fxg6 (18... hxg6 19. h6 $1) 19. hxg6 Nxg6 20. Rdg1) 9. Ne2 $1 Re8 10. g4 Nc5 (
10... Nf8 11. Ng3 Ne6 12. Nf5) 11. Ng3 Ne6 12. Nf5 c5 13. h4 {Both sides
succeeded in their middlegame plans - White provided an excellent square for
his knight, just in front of Black's king, while Black completed the manoeuvre
Nd7-c5-e6 and is ready to jump to d4.} a5 $1 {Preparing a4-a3 and employing
the queenside rook.} (13... Nd4 {will be met by} 14. c3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Be6 16.
c4 $1 {, and White has the ideal situation, as Black's counterattack cannot
reach his king, for instance} Bf8 17. Rd1 b5 18. h5 c6 19. h6 g6 20. Ng7 Qa5+
21. Kf1 Re7 22. Nh5 $1 Rb7 23. Nf6+ Kh8 24. Kg2 bxc4 25. dxc4 Rxb2 26. Rd7 $1
$18) 14. h5 $1 {Caruana is not in a hurry to castle, as his king feels safe in
the centre.} (14. a4 Nd4 15. Nd2 Bf8 16. h5) 14... Ra6 (14... a4 $1 {was more
precise.} 15. g5 Nd4 16. N3h4 $1 Bf8 17. g6 Ra6 18. Bxd4 cxd4 19. gxf7+ Kxf7
20. Qf3 Kg8 21. Rg1 Rb6 $132) 15. Qd2 ({It was better to start with
stabilising the position on the queenside by playing} 15. a4 $1 Bd7 (15... Nd4
16. Nd2 $1) 16. Rg1 (16. b3 Nf4 17. Rg1) 16... Nf4 17. Nd2 $1) 15... Nd4 $1 (
15... a4 16. O-O-O Nd4 17. N3h4 Be6 18. g5 Bxa2 19. g6 Bf8 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21.
Rdg1 {would be very difficult to evaluate, but one thing is clear - White's
attack was faster.}) 16. Rh3 {This looks ugly, but there is nothing better.} (
16. Bxd4 cxd4 17. Kf1 a4 18. Kg2 Rb6 19. b3 h6) (16. N3h4 Bxf5 17. gxf5 c4)
16... Bf8 17. O-O-O {White's king can become a target on the queenside, but
there was no other way to increase the attacking potential.} Be6 (17... b5 18.
Kb1 a4 19. Rdh1 b4 20. Bxd4 cxd4 21. g5) 18. Kb1 {The only way to protect the
pawn, as} (18. c4 a4 19. Rg1 b5 {would be quite bad for White.}) 18... f6 $1 ({
Avoiding} 18... Nxf3 19. Rxf3 c4 20. dxc4 Qxd2 21. Bxd2 Bxc4 {, with a more or
less equal endgame.}) 19. c3 Nxf3 (19... Qd7 20. cxd4 cxd4 21. Bxd4 exd4 22.
N3xd4 Bf7 23. Qc2) 20. Rxf3 c4 ({Here Black missed the best defence} 20... h6
$1 {, freezing the kingside, when the only way to continue the attack is to
sacrifice a piece.} 21. Rg3 Qd7 22. f4 exf4 23. Bxf4 Qf7 24. a3 b5 25. Bxh6 {
A desperate attempt, however rather incorrect.} gxh6 26. Nxh6+ Bxh6 27. Qxh6
Qg7 28. Qf4 Qg5) 21. Qc2 $1 {With this move Caruana takes over the initiative.}
(21. g5 Qxd3+ 22. Qxd3 cxd3 23. gxf6 gxf6 24. Rg3+ Kf7 25. Rxd3 {is only equal,
while}) ({, of course,} 21. dxc4 {loses on the spot after} Bxf5 22. Qxd8 (22.
gxf5 Rd6) 22... Bxe4+ 23. Kc1 Rxd8 24. Rxd8 Bxf3 25. Bc5 Rd6 $19) 21... cxd3
22. Rxd3 Qc8 23. g5 $1 {Caruana grabs his chance.} fxg5 (23... Qb8) 24. Bxg5
Bf7 (24... h6 25. Bc1 Bf7 26. Rg3 Kh7 27. Rd1 Qe6 28. b3 a4) 25. h6 $1 {
Now White is back in the game.} gxh6 {A sad moment for Black, as he is forced
to completely ruin his kingside.} (25... g6 26. Ne3 $1 {/\ Nd5-f6} c6 {is
refuted by} 27. Rxf7 Kxf7 28. Qb3+ Qe6 29. Qxb7+ $18) 26. Bc1 Qe6 27. b3 a4 (
27... b5 28. Ne3) 28. c4 axb3 29. axb3 Qc6 30. Rg3+ Kh8 31. Rd1 b5 {The
tension is very high, everything depends on who will be the first to create
mating threats.} 32. c5 $1 (32. Bb2 bxc4 33. Rd8 Ra5 $1) 32... b4 $2 {Having
protected everything, Anand loses his sense of danger. The idea of his last
move is to play Ra5 and take with the rook, defending on e5. But he runs into
a sudden refutation.} (32... Qxc5 $1 {practically forces a draw.} 33. Qxc5 Bxc5
34. Rd7 Bg6 35. Bxh6 Bf8 $11) 33. Bb2 $1 {It is all over now, Black's defence
collapses.} Bg6 {Blocking the g-file does not solve the problem.} ({
Unfortunately,} 33... Ra5 {meets a beautiful refutation:} 34. Rd8 $1 Qxc5 (
34... Rxc5 35. Bxe5+ $3 {Double pin!}) 35. Rxe8 Bxe8 36. f4 $1 Bg6 37. fxe5 Kg8
38. e6 Qxc2+ 39. Kxc2 Bd6 40. Rf3 Bxf5 41. exf5 $18) (33... Qxc5 34. Qxc5 Bxc5
35. Rd7 Bg6 36. f4 Bd6 37. fxe5 Bxe5 38. Bxe5+ Rxe5 39. Rd8+ Be8 40. Ng7 Rxe4
41. Rxe8+ Rxe8 42. Nxe8 Rg6 43. Rd3 c5 44. Nd6 $18) 34. Rd5 $1 Qb5 35. Rg1 $1
c6 36. Rxe5 Rxe5 37. Bxe5+ Kg8 38. Bd4 (38. Bb2 Kf7 39. Qd1) 38... Kf7 39. Nh4
$18 {Black's king is defenceless.} 1-0

