-241,-249,-250,-201,-212,-232,-245,-208,-281,-181,-218,-172,-168,-203,-226,
-226,-256,-205,-283,-348,-358,-370]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5
5. Bxc6 dxc6 6. h3 Nd7 {Black decides not to waste time and defend the pawn} 7.
Bg5 (7. Be3 $5 {was the choice of Magnus Carlsen in this position}) 7... f6 8.
Be3 Bxe3 9. fxe3 {I can't see what White achieves provoking f6. In my opinion,
this is just in Black's favour} Qe7 10. Nc3 (10. O-O {is very risky because
Black can consider an immediate} g5 $1 {when White's pawn is on h3, this move
is always a good idea.}) 10... b6 11. O-O Bb7 {Black decides to finish the
development first, before starting an active play on the queenside.} 12. Nh4 g6
$1 {of course, no one is going to allow White's knight to come on "f5"} 13. Qe1
{f5 was a serious threat} O-O-O 14. a3 Kb8 15. b4 {Hikaru starts some active
play against Black's king, but Black has nothing to worry about and
immediately counterattack.} c5 $1 16. Na4 Bc6 $5 17. Nb2 Rhg8 $1 {with the
idea f5} 18. Rd1 Rdf8 $1 19. c4 f5 20. b5 {After this move, Black's king is
safe, but otherwise, the b4-pawn is just hanging in many variations.} Bb7 $19 {
the game is practically over. Black has a free hand on the kingside and sooner
or later, this should bring him some benefits.} 21. exf5 gxf5 22. Rd2 Qg5 $5
23. e4 fxe4 24. Rxf8+ (24. dxe4 $2 Rxf1+ 25. Kxf1 Bxe4 $1 $19) 24... Nxf8 $1 {
Black activates the knight} 25. dxe4 Ne6 26. Nf3 Qh5 27. Kh2 Nd4 $19 {Black is
winning. Later both players commit many mistakes, but finally, Black scores
the full point.} 28. Qe3 Bc8 29. Ne1 Qg6 $1 30. Ned3 Re8 31. Nd1 Qg8 32. N3b2
Be6 $1 33. Qd3 Rd8 $1 34. Qc3 h5 35. Rf2 h4 36. a4 Qg6 $1 37. Qe3 Rg8 $1 38.
Kh1 Qh5 39. a5 Kc8 40. Qe1 Rg3 41. Qf1 Kd7 42. Nd3 Ke7 43. N1b2 Rg8 44. a6 Qg5
45. Qg1 c6 46. bxc6 Nxc6 47. Rf1 Qg3 48. Qf2 Qxf2 49. Nxf2 Rd8 50. Nfd1 Rd2 51.
Rf2 Rxf2 52. Nxf2 Na5 53. Kh2 Nxc4 54. Na4 Kd6 55. Nc3 Kc6 56. g3 hxg3+ 57.
Kxg3 b5 58. Nd3 b4 59. Na4 b3 60. h4 Bf7 61. Kg4 Bg6 62. Nc3 b2 63. Kf3 Kd6 64.
