{[%evp 0,129,14,14,23,23,19,19,27,2,-12,9,31,-2,5,8,13,-18,-8,-7,3,3,-11,-3,24,
-21,29,-10,25,25,48,41,42,-22,-7,-11,6,5,-4,-50,-35,-30,0,0,0,0,21,19,60,46,55,
51,58,54,48,57,56,39,81,69,71,94,60,86,80,90,116,39,48,57,123,86,136,136,139,
139,135,135,135,120,143,139,135,139,143,137,142,147,196,161,163,180,161,171,
169,170,178,169,166,161,168,167,189,181,207,187,204,213,237,235,236,237,237,
237,327,285,268,279,287,300,295,329,329,341,345,345,592,1252,1292,1312,1940,
2254]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6
8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 13. Nf1 Rfe8 {[%csl Ge8,
Ge4,Gf8,Ge7][%cal Gf8e8,Ge7f8,Ge8e4,Gf6e4,Gg7g6,Gf8g7] "The Yugoslav System,
popularized by Gligoric and Matanovic. The idea is to strengthen the position
and transfer the bishop to f8 while awaiting further developments. Black will
undertake specific counteraction only after White commits himself." (Fischer)}
14. Ne3 (14. b3 {cutting off the knight at a5 and not blocking the path of the
c1-bishop: if} g6 {, then} 15. Bg5 $1 {. This plan struck a serious blow at
the 'Yugoslav System'.}) 14... g6 15. dxe5 {"This positional approach bares
the hole on d5, so that White may gain access to it with his knight," writes
Fischer.} dxe5 16. Nh2 {[%csl Gf3,Gg4,Rf6,Ya5,Bd5][%cal Gd1f3,Gh2g4,Re3d5,
Gf6g4,Gh3g4,Gh1h8,Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Ge1h1]} Rad8 17. Qf3 Be6 {What happens next is
typical for the line:} 18. Nhg4 {A typical idea: after the exchange on g4 the
d5-square is weakened and attacking motifs on the h-file arise.} Nxg4 19. hxg4
(19. Nxg4 {[%csl Gg4] is harmless:} Bxg4 20. hxg4 c4 {[%csl Gc5,Gd3][%cal
Gc5d3,Ga5b7,Gb7c5]} 21. g3 Nb7 22. Kg2 Nc5 23. Rh1 f6 {with equality  
(Fischer-Matanovic, Portoroz Interzonal 1958).}) 19... Qc6 (19... Nc4 {[%csl
Ge3]} 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 {[%csl Gc2,Gc1] ," writes Fischer, evidently
relying on his two bishops. It is strange that he ignores} Nb6 $1 {[%csl Gd5]
[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8d8] followed by the doubling of rooks on the d-file, as
occurred in the games Gligoric-Reshevsky, Zürich Candidates 1953),
Smyslov-Gligoric (Zagreb 1955), Keres-Matanovic (Bled 1961) and many others,
where Black gained a draw without particular difficulty.}) 20. g5 $5 {
Fischer's novelty, which he introduced against Shocron in Mar del Plata (1959).
} Nc4 (20... Bxg5 {Bobby was intending} 21. Nd5 $1 Bxc1 22. Nf6+ {[%cal Gf6e8,
Gg8g7]} Kh8 $1 23. Raxc1 (23. Nxe8 Bg5 24. Nf6 Nc4 $1 {Black has good
compensation for the exchange}) 23... Rf8 24. Qg3 Qc7 $1 25. Qg5 Kg7 {, "and
now White can force a draw with} 26. Nh5+ {etc} (26. f4) (26. Re3 {." However,
after} h6 $1 {he is unable to achieve any more.})) 21. Ng4 {[%cal Ge6d5]} Bxg4
{Forced: the knight cannot be allowed to go to f6.} 22. Qxg4 f6 $2 {[%csl Rg8]
Unzicker makes an 'active' move, not sensing how dangerous it is to weaken the
light squares and the e5-pawn.} 23. gxf6 Bxf6 24. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4b5,Ga1a7,
Ga7h7,Gc2b3,Gb3g8]} Nb6 25. axb5 axb5 26. Be3 {"Because both flanks are fluid,
White, with his two bishops, is better able to penetrate and exploit the
'loose' pawns." To judge by this and Fischer's later comments, Black is
already doomed, although, as we will see, he had opportunities to put up a
tenacious resistance.} Ra8 27. Red1 Kh8 $6 {"If he swaps, White gains the
a-file; if he doesn't, White keeps the d-file." (Fischer). Hübner again
objects: "On h8 Black's king is often worse than on g8, because in the endgame
it needs more time to reach the centre; moreover, the danger to get mated in
the middlegame grows if White's bishop appears on h6.} 28. b3 Bg7 (28... Rxa1
29. Rxa1 Ra8 30. Rxa8+ Nxa8 {, though} 31. Qd1 $1 {followed by Qa1! forces an
invasion on the queenside." (Fischer). According to Hübner, there is nothing
terrible about this after} Nc7 $1 32. Qa1 (32. Bd3 $1 Kg7 33. Bf1 $1 {is
stronger, and Black has chronic problems}) 32... Be7 {.}) 29. Qh4 Bf6 30. Bg5
$1 {A concrete approach to the position that is typical of Fischer: he
exchanges his 'good' bishop for the opponent's 'bad' bishop, in order to
weaken still further the e5-pawn and the defences of the black king.} Bxg5 31.
Qxg5 {"Now White must penetrate on either the a- or d-file. Black's e-pawn has
clearly been exposed as a weakling. " (Fischer)} Rxa1 32. Rxa1 Nd7 33. Bd1 $1 {
A fine move,} Nf6 34. Ra7 Qd6 35. Be2 $1 {"Simply attacking a pawn. Curiously,
Black is in too much of a straitjacket to do much about it." (Fischer)} Re7 $2
{Simply giving up the b5-pawn.} 36. Rxe7 Qxe7 37. Bxb5 Kg7 38. Be2 {"The win
is still far from clear. White's major technical problem is creating a passed
pawn on the queenside while sheltering his king from a perpetual check."  
(Fischer)} Qc7 {With the threat of ...Nxe4.} 39. Qe3 Qa5 40. g3 {[%csl Gg2,Gf4]
[%cal Gg1g2,Gf6h5,Gh5f4]} Qa3 $6 41. Kg2 {[%cal Ga3b3,Gb3b1,Gb1e4]} Qa5 42. Qd3
Qb6 43. Qc4 {[%csl Gc4]} Qc6 44. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gc4e4]} Qb6 45. b4 {[%cal
Gf2f4]} cxb4 46. cxb4 {"Step one is completed: White has a passed b-pawn."  
(Fischer)} Ng4 47. Qc5 $1 {Forcing the exchange of queens,} Qxc5 48. bxc5 Kf7
49. f4 $1 {Playing for the creation of a second passed pawn.} Ke7 50. Kf3 Nf6
51. Bb5 Ke6 52. Bc4+ Ke7 53. c6 $1 Ne8 54. fxe5 $1 h6 55. Ke3 Nc7 56. Kd4 h5
57. Ke3 $1 g5 58. Be2 h4 59. gxh4 gxh4 60. Bc4 Ne8 61. Kf4 Kd8 62. Kg4 Kc7 63.
Bf7 Ng7 64. Kxh4 Kxc6 65. Kg5 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

