{[%evp 0,81,21,28,28,28,28,24,33,3,1,7,13,3,3,3,-3,0,18,-28,-10,-10,-12,-12,6,
-7,28,13,24,30,23,33,23,24,21,25,25,29,28,13,25,12,9,-12,-13,-15,-28,-3,-22,
-44,1,0,8,-28,-24,-33,-23,-36,-36,-21,29,24,-36,-93,-83,-32,-90,-125,-87,-130,
-96,-92,-92,-79,-104,-112,-58,-15,-35,6,6,0,85,70]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. d3 {A modest move which,
however prevents the Marshall Attack.} d6 9. c3 Na5 {Yesterday's loss was
certainly a painful blow for Vituigov, who missed a shot to play for a place
at the Candidates. Nevertheless, the Russian champion managed to bring himself
together and went fully mobilized in this final encounter.} 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2
Re8 12. h3 Bf8 13. Nf1 h6 14. d4 {White opens the center, despite the delay of
a tempo.} exd4 15. cxd4 cxd4 {[%csl Ge4,Gf6,Gc8,Ga5][%cal Gc8b7,Gb7e4,Gf6e4,
Ge8e4] The slightly comprimised pawn structure will be compensated by the
active black pieces.} 16. Ng3 Bb7 17. Nxd4 Nc4 (17... Qc7 18. Bf4 Nc4 19. Ndf5
Nxb2 20. Qc1 Nc4 21. Bxh6 gxh6 {Here Robson sacrificed a piece:} 22. Nxh6+ Bxh6
23. Qxh6 Re6 24. Nf5 Ne8 25. Qg5+ Kf8 26. Qh4 Rg6 {but his younger opponent
managed to defend, Robson,R (2669)-Burke,J (2554) Saint Louis 2021}) 18. b3 Ne5
19. Bb2 Rc8 20. Qd2 {[#]} Qb6 $146 {Active play, and a novely.} (20... Ng6 21.
Rad1 d5 22. Ndf5 Nxe4 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Qe3 Qc7 25. Bb1 Bc5 {Pfeffer,R (2155)
-Kiesekamp,M (2316) Berlin 2008}) 21. Ndf5 {[%cal Gf5h6,Gf5g7,Gf5d6,Gg1h1,
Gb6g1] Sjugirov wants to maneuver his knight to a better square, but this
costs him quite a lot of time.} (21. Kh1 $5 {to pay respect to the queen was a
better choice.}) 21... g6 22. Ne3 h5 $1 {[%csl Gh5,Ye3,Yg3,Bg6,Bh4,Re4][%cal
Gh6h5,Gb7e4,Gf6e4,Gg7g6,Gh5h4,Bg6f5] An important move in the battle for the
e4 square.} 23. Bd4 Qd8 24. f3 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Gd6d5] This modest move is
more or less forced. Sjugirov needs to overprotect his most important pawn.} (
24. f4 $2 h4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gd6e5]} 25. Ngf1 {[%cal Gf4e5]} Bxe4 $1 {And White
loses at least a pawn, as the line:} 26. fxe5 dxe5 27. Bc3 Qxd2 28. Bxd2 Bxc2 {
is not appealing at all.}) 24... h4 {Ten minutes on the clock indicate that
Vituigov might have been choosing between this aggression.} (24... d5 $5 {
Which is not bad at all after:} 25. exd5 Nxd5 (25... Bxd5 $5) 26. Nxd5 Bg7 $1 {
And White needs to give the piece back.}) 25. Ngf1 {The other retreats are
worse.} (25. Ne2 {blocks the white rook and:} d5 $1 {gains strenght.}) (25. Nh1
d5 $1) 25... Bh6 $1 {[%csl Gf4,Gg3,Gh2,Rf2,Re4][%cal Gh6f4,Gf6h5,Gd8g5,Rf2f3,
Rb7e4] Bringing the bishop first to control the dark squares.} (25... Nh5 $5
26. Rad1 Qg5 {with Black's pressure, but the move in the game is more powerful.
}) 26. Rad1 Bf4 27. Qf2 Nh5 28. Ng4 Qg5 {[%cal Gf7f5,Gd6d5] Black is in full
control. The breaks d6-d5 and f7-f5 are in the air, and there is more to add
to White's voes.} 29. b4 {[%cal Gc2b3] In order to bring his light-squared
bishop out.} (29. Be3 {Indeed, Black is significantly better thanks to:} Rc3)
29... Nxg4 $1 30. hxg4 Bg3 $1 {That forces the next capture.} 31. Nxg3 (31. Qe3
{would lose material for White in the forced line:} Qxe3+ 32. Rxe3 Rxc2 33.
gxh5 Bf2+ {[%cal Gf2e3]} (33... gxh5 $5 {looks appealing for Black too.}) 34.
Kh2 Bxe3) 31... hxg3 {[%cal Gg5h4,Gh4h2] The wedge on g3 acts as a piece in
Black's attack and the impression is that White would be mated at any moment.}
32. Qd2 Nf4 {Many people would simply resign to the frustration if they were
in White's shoes. But not Sjugirov, he finds strength and squeezes resources
to continue.} 33. Bb3 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gc2b3,Gc8c2]} (33. Be3 {[%csl Ge3]
[%cal Gd4e3] Which walks directly in the trap:} Qh4 34. Bxf4 Qh2+ 35. Kf1 Rxc2
$3 36. Qxc2 Qh1+ 37. Ke2 Qxg2+ 38. Kd3 Qxf3+ 39. Re3 Bxe4+ 40. Kd4 Qxe3+ {
and Black wins a bunch of pawns.}) 33... Qh6 {The human way! Good enough!} (
33... d5 $3 {That is not a major surprise, Black would not mind opening the
e-file and bringing on the last reserves. But observe now how's compy doing
the job:} 34. exd5 Rxe1+ 35. Qxe1 Qh6 $1 36. Qd2 Rc3 $3 {[%csl Gd4] with the
unstoppable threat of Rc3-d3!!} (36... Rc1 37. Be3 Rxd1+ 38. Bxd1 Bxd5 {
[%csl Gf4][%cal Ge3f4]})) 34. g5 $3 {The only way to fight on, is to create
problems! Amazing resource! Petrosian's thought about the one-pawn-square the
difference comes to mind when one follows this unbelievably complex,
marvellous game!} (34. Be3 {Falls short, for Black, can use the trick from the
line above:} Rc3 $3 {And it is all over:} 35. Qxc3 (35. Bxf4 Qh2+ 36. Kf1 Qh1+
37. Ke2 Qxg2#) 35... Qh2+ 36. Kf1 Qh1+ 37. Bg1 Qxg2#) (34. a3 Qh2+ 35. Kf1 Qh1+
36. Bg1 Nh3 $3 {Then when the bishop is defended:} 37. Qd4 (37. gxh3 Qxf3+)
37... Rc3 $3 {Yep, this guy again... And the players were obviously aware of
this resource!}) 34... Qh4 (34... Qh2+ 35. Kf1 Qh1+ 36. Bg1 Nh3 37. Qd4 Rc3 {
Only leads to a draw due to:} 38. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 39. Qf6+ {with a perpetual!}) (
34... Qxg5 35. Be3 Qh6 36. Bxf4 Qh2+ 37. Kf1 Qh1+ 38. Ke2 Qxg2+ 39. Kd3 Qxf3+
40. Qe3 Bxe4+ 41. Kd2 {would have seen the white king surviving!}) 35. Kf1 Rc3
$3 {Wow, this hapepned! And the rook is invincible, yes! And the Rc3-d3 threat
s deadly, right! And guess what, this is not the best!!!} (35... a5 $3 {When:}
36. a3 {Softens the position of the bishop and Black will now go for:} (36.
bxa5 b4 $1) 36... Rc3 $3 {and wins.} (36... a4 37. Ba2 Qxg5 38. Be3 Qh6 39.
Bxf4 Qh1+ 40. Ke2 Qxg2+ 41. Kd3 Qxf3+ 42. Qe3 Bxe4+ 43. Kd4 Qh5 $1 {mating the
king at the end.})) 36. Qxf4 $1 {Once that Sjugirov eliminates the impossible,
he decided that this must the truth! (Sherlock Bojkov)} Qxf4 37. Bxc3 Qxg5 {
And this obvious move actually lets White off the hook!} (37... a5 $3 {Main
idea is:} 38. bxa5 $2 (38. Bf6 {is better, but then Black would have taken the
other pawn:} axb4 {when:} 39. Ke2 {is no longer good due to:} Bxe4 $1 40. fxe4
Qxe4+ 41. Kd2 Qf4+ 42. Kd3 Qf5+ $1 {Now we see why the b4 pawn is needed!} 43.
Kd2 Qf2+ {and wins.}) 38... b4 39. Bxb4 Ba6+ 40. Kg1 Qh4) 38. Ke2 $3 {Suddenly,
the white king is out of danger and it is time for White's attack for a change.
} (38. Rxd6 Qh6 39. Bd4 Bc8 $1 {followed by Bc8-e6!}) 38... d5 {Give me more
open files!} 39. Rh1 {No, you give me more diagonals!} f6 40. Rh3 Bc6 {The
last move in the time control completely turns the tables.} (40... Rc8 41. Bb2
Rc4 $3 {at least getting rid of one of the monstrous bishops.}) 41. Rdh1 Kf7
42. Rh7+ Ke6 43. Rd1 {Now it is Sjugirov's moment to miss things.} (43. Bd2 $3
Qe5 44. Rc1 Ba8 45. Ra7 {and White's close to the win!}) 43... f5 $3 {Wow!
That's the only thing to say. WOW!} 44. Bd2 (44. exd5+ Kd6+ 45. Kf1 Bd7 {
with messy position.} (45... Qe3 $4 46. dxc6+ Kxc6 47. Bd5+ Kd6 48. Bb7+ Ke6
49. Re1 {when White wins.})) (44. exf5+ $4 {loses to:} Kd6+ 45. Kf1 Qe3 $1)
44... Qd8 {Who's going to blink first?} (44... f4 45. Rc1 {does not seem
appealing at all, albeit being objectively better.}) 45. Be3 (45. Rc1 $3 Ba8
46. Kd3 $3 {!!! I do not have enough exclams, sorry.} Kf6 47. e5+ $3 Rxe5 (
47... Ke6 48. Rcc7) 48. Rcc7 {would have led to decisive White attack.}) 45...
Kf6 {Now the king is relatively safe...} 46. Rc1 Qd6 47. Ra7 $5 {Sjugirov
rejects the draw and chases the full point!} (47. Bc5 Qe5 48. Be3 Qd6) 47...
fxe4 48. Bd4+ Kg5 (48... Kf5 $4 49. Rf7+) 49. f4+ $1 Kg4 $1 {Vituigov tries to
hide his king behind the pawn.} (49... Kxf4 50. Rf1+ Kg4 {There is the
fabulous ambush:} 51. Bd1 $3 {And that is good enough to interrupt any further
calculations. However, how to play after:} e3 $3 {It seems like that with the
best play the players will reach approximately equal endgame (?? Seriously??)
with:} 52. Raf7 Bd7 53. R1f6 Qxb4 54. Rf4+ Kg5 55. Bf6+ Kxf4 56. Bc3+ Bf5 57.
Bxb4 d4 58. Bc2 {Yep, believe it or not!}) 50. Rf7 $2 {Now White is losing
again!} (50. Rxa6 $1 Rc8 51. Rc5 $1 Qd7 52. Ke3 {Although Black is still on
top thanks to:} g5 $1) 50... e3 $1 {A very imporatnt resource!} 51. Bd1 $1 {
The ambush again!} Kh5 $2 {Did I say Black was losing again? No, I meant Black
is losing again...} (51... Qe6 $3 52. Ke1+ e2) 52. Rh7+ $2 (52. Kf3 $3 e2 (
52... Kh6 53. Bc2 $1) (52... g5 53. Bc2 $1) 53. Rh7#) 52... Kg4 {Now the
evaluation switch turns on and off a few times again.} 53. Rf7 Kh5 $2 54. Rh7+
$2 Kg4 55. Bxe3 d4 {Missing the last chance to win.} (55... Kf5 $3 56. Bc2+ Kf6
$1 {would have brought his Majesty into safety.}) 56. Kf1+ Kf5 {And after a
bunch of forcing moves:} 57. Rxc6 $3 Qxc6 58. Rf7+ Ke6 59. Bb3+ {Sjugirov
first regained the queen.} Qc4+ 60. Bxc4+ bxc4 {And then forced a draw rook
endgame with:} 61. Rc7 dxe3 62. Rxc4 Kd5 63. Rc5+ Kd4 64. Ke2 Rf8 65. Kf3 Re8
66. Ke2 Rf8 67. Kf3 Re8 {If one ever asks you why do you play chess-just show
them this game!} 1/2-1/2

[Event "Norway Chess 2021"]
