{[#]} 18... Re7 {A very useful move which aims to double the rooks on either
open or half-open file.} 19. c4 (19. f3 {for the time being as he would weaken
his king.}) 19... d4 $1 {Karjakin cramps further the white pieces.} (19... f5
$5 {at once was good as well.}) 20. Bd2 f5 21. axb6 axb6 22. f3 {At the end of
the day White was forced to defend with this move.} (22. c5 b5 {"Desperately
weakens my light squares, just f7-f5 and then the black knight lands on d5,
and just toast!"  (Carlsen)}) 22... Rf7 {Black wants to force the opening of
the f-file.} (22... f4 23. Be1 Rf7) 23. Rf1 {White cannot afford to leave the
first rank unprotected.} (23. Ra3 Qf6 24. Rba1 fxe4 25. fxe4 Qf2+ 26. Kh1 Qf1+
27. Rxf1 Rxf1#) 23... Kh7 24. exf5 Bxf5 25. Be1 (25. Nc1 $5 {To try and
transfer the knight to e4 via the e2-g3-e4 route was a better idea.}) 25... Qg5
26. Rd1 {According to Carlsen, a sad necessity.} (26. Bg3 Qe3+ 27. Qf2 Bxd3 (
27... Rd8 $1) 28. Nxd4 Qxf2+ 29. Rxf2 Rc8 30. Nc2 Bxc4 31. Ne3 {"I am still
holding on. I am a pawn down, but I should be able to hold the draw." (Carlsen)
}) 26... h5 (26... Ra8 27. Bd2 {when Black holds all the trumps.}) 27. Bd2 Qh4
$1 {A somewhat puzzling choice for the world champion. But as we shall see
Karjakin's choice was a very good one.} (27... Qf6 {Due to the f3-f4 advance,
either immediately, or after:} 28. Rde1 Ra8 29. f4) 28. Rde1 Ra8 {A tricky
move that lures the white rook away from home.} 29. Ra1 Raf8 $1 (29... Rfa7 {
White planned:} 30. Rxa7 Rxa7 31. Nc1) 30. Ra6 {And Carlsen embraces the
provocation, hoping to cause crisis rather than waiting patiently.} (30. Rae1 {
in hindsight was objectively better.}) 30... e4 {This is what White expected
and wanted to provoke.} (30... Bh3 $3 {Was tremendously strong! The two lines
that Carlsen suggested after the game could have been refuted spectacularly.
Once runs:} 31. Rf2 (31. Be1 {To which Carlsen quoted:} Qg5 (31... Rxf3 $3 32.
gxf3 Rxf3 33. Qg2 Qg4 $3 {and Black wins!}) 32. Qd2 {with a chance to defend.})
(31. Qd1 {Also does not bring White relief due to:} Bxg2 $1 32. Kxg2 Rxf3 33.
Rxf3 Qg4+ 34. Kf2 Nh4 35. Rxf8 Qxd1 36. Ra7 Qxb3 37. Rff7 Nf5 38. Rxf5 Qxd3 39.
Rxh5+ Kg8 40. Rxe5 Qxd2+ {and Black should be winning again.}) 31... Bxg2 32.
Rxg2 Nf4 $1 {With the threat of Nf4-h3+! promises Black huge attack, as:} 33.
Bxf4 Qe1#) 31. Nxd4 $1 (31. fxe4 Bh3 $3 32. Rxf7 Rxf7 {and the mating threats
force major material losses for White.}) 31... exf3 32. Nxf3 Bh3 33. Rf2 $1 {
A very cool move! "I have seen that this does not lose." (Carlsen)} Rxf3 34.
gxf3 Rf5 {Black starts to lose the thread.} (34... Ne5 35. d4+ Bf5 36. Qc3 Nd3
37. Rg2 {"It seems like I am protecting everything and that the knight is
poorly placed on d3." (Carlsen)}) (34... Bg4 $1 35. Bg5 Qxg5 36. fxg4 Qxg4+ 37.
Kh1 Rxf2 38. Qxf2 Qd1+) 35. d4 Qxd4 36. Ra3 {"I am kind of consolidated."  
(Carlsen) The problem was that White was down to a few minutes on the clock.}
Rf7 37. Re3 (37. Qd3 $1 Qh4 38. Qe4) 37... Bf5 38. Qc3 Qd8 39. Re1 Rd7 40. Qe3
Rd4 {Now things would be so much easier for White!} (40... Re7 {"I was going
to repeat once:"} 41. Qc3 {"And then, who knows..." (Carlsen)}) 41. Qg5 {
"I could not take away the queens quicker. I can never lose." (Carlsen)} Qxg5+
42. Bxg5 Rxc4 43. Rb2 b5 (43... Nf4 44. Bxf4 Rxf4 45. Kf2 h4 {Then the world
champion quoted Botvinnik who said that a bishop defended by a pawn is as
strong as rook and suggested that Black should hold this.}) 44. Kf2 c5 {
The frustrated Karjakin quickly loses the game.} (44... h4 $5 {was possibly
still the move.}) 45. bxc5 Rxc5 46. Rc1 $1 Rd5 47. Rd2 $1 {Once that the rooks
are traded it is over according to the world champion.} Rxd2+ 48. Bxd2 Ne5 (
48... Nf8 49. Rc7 Nd7 50. Rb7 {when Carlsen quoted one of the games between
Kasparov and Karpov where the former managed to win identical endgame.}) 49.
Rc7 b4 50. Rb7 Be6 {A blunder, but there was no way out anyway.} 51. Re7 Nd3+
52. Ke3 Bc4 53. Kd4 {1-0 Black resigns.} ({Bb5} 53. Rb7 {Bc6 Rb6}) 1-0

