{[#]} 13. d5 c4 14. Bc2 Nc5 15. Nf1 Re8 (15... Qc7 16. Ng3 Rfb8 17. Nf5 Bf8 18.
Qe2 Bc8 19. g4 Bd7) 16. Ng3 g6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ge7f8,Gf8g7]} 17. Be3 Qc7 {
Both players did the mandatory moves. Black did better though and equalized
comfortably.} 18. Nd2 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf2f4]} (18. Nh2 h5 19. Nf3 Reb8 20. Qe2
Bc8 21. Ra2 Bd7 22. axb5 axb5 23. Rea1 Rxa2 24. Rxa2 Qc8 25. Qd1 {1/2-1/2 (25)
Matlakov,M (2487)-Khruschiov,A (2498) St Petersburg 2009}) 18... Bf8 19. Qe2
Nfd7 $1 {Pogonina is consistently looking for a play on the queenside.} 20. f3
$146 {The actual novelty. All of this has been seen in a total of eleven games
and White always continued with} (20. Ra3 {[%cal Ge1a1] with the idea of
doubling the rooks before opening the a-file. Black can now force her opponent
to make a decision with the move} Nb6 {and after} 21. axb5 axb5 {will be
followed by liquidation of the rooks along the a-file and possible draw} 22.
Rea1 Rxa3 23. Rxa3 Ra8 (23... Bc8 {is more fightful} 24. Qd1 Bd7 25. Qa1 Nba4 {
Fleischanderl,F (2496)-Mrkvicka,J (2469) ICCF email 2002})) 20... Nb6 21. a5 {
Muzychuk closes the queenside and wants to concentrate on the other wing where
she is stronger by definition. The problem with this approach is that the pawn
on a5 might be vulnerable later.} Nbd7 22. Nh1 $1 {White needs the g pawn for
the attack. The other advance fails tactically} (22. f4 $2 exf4 23. Bxf4 Bxd5)
22... Be7 23. g4 Qd8 $1 {[%cal Ge7g5] Good understanding of the position.
Pogonina fights for the dark squares.} 24. Qf2 Bh4 $6 {Somewhat too
sophisticated to my taste.} (24... Bg5 {at once in order to swap off the
bishops was very comfortable for Black. After} 25. Ng3 Bf4 {is well followed
by Qd8-h4.} (25... Bxe3 26. Rxe3 Qh4) (25... Qf6)) 25. Ng3 Rc8 26. Kg2 {
[%csl Gg4,Gh3][%cal Gf3f4] White's game is easier as she basically has an only
plan- to carry out the f3-f4 advance.} Nf8 {'?'} (26... Qe7 27. f4 exf4 28.
Bxf4 Nd3 29. Bxd3 cxd3) 27. Rf1 Bg5 28. f4 exf4 29. Bxf4 {[%csl Gf4,Gg5,Gg3,
Gf8,Ge5][%cal Gc5e5] with the disappearance of the pawn pair some important
things happened: 1) The f file is now opened for the white pieces and White
can exert pressure on it. 2) The d4 square is available for the white knights.
3) The e5 square is a wonderful outpost for the black knights. 4) The typical
knight sacrifice Ng3-f5 gained popularity thanks to the extra space that White
has. All in all the transformations are favourable for White and Muzychuk's
game is much easier. Further, she got an attacking position, her most beloved
thing. Did you know that people already name her Miss Tactics in Sochi?} Rc7 {
[%csl Gf7][%cal Gc7f7] Overprotects f7.} (29... Bxf4 30. Qxf4 Rc7 (30... Re7
31. h4) 31. Rf2 {[%csl Gh5,Gf5][%cal Ga1f1,Gf4h6,Gg3h5,Gg3f5,Gg5f5] followed
by Ra1-f1 and Qf4-h6.} (31. Qh6 $5)) 30. Bxg5 Qxg5 31. Nf3 Qe7 (31... Qf4 32.
Qd4 Nfd7 {as none of the discovered attacks is particularly dangerous. But who
can really play with a queen that exposed?}) 32. Nd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg3f5,
Gd4f5]} Qe5 {Pogonina decided to move away from the dangerous Ng3(d4)-f5
threat. However, the precise calculation of the line '?!'} (32... Nfd7 $5 {
(to bring the knight to e5)} 33. Ngf5 gxf5 34. Nxf5 Qf6 35. Nh6+ {reveals that
Black is not forced to get checkmated after} (35. Nxd6 Qxf2+ 36. Rxf2 Re5)
35... Qxh6 $2 (35... Kg7 $1 36. Qxf6+ Nxf6 37. Nf5+ Kf8 38. Nxd6 Nfxe4 {
and if anyone is better here it is definitely not White!}) 36. Qxf7+ Kh8 37.
Qxe8+) (32... Ncd7 {the sacrifice seem to lead to a very powerful attack after}
33. Ngf5 gxf5 34. Nxf5 Qf6 35. Qd2 $3 Kh8 36. Nh6 Qe7 37. Rxf7 (37. Nxf7+ Kg8
38. Nh6+) 37... Qd8 {with a nice choice-} 38. Nf5 (38. Qf4) (38. Raf1)) 33. h4
h6 {This weakening might be a bit too much although it is not easy at all to
sit and wait while your opponent is improving the position. At this stage of
the game both the players had very little time left.} 34. Qd2 Bc8 {Black
hardly has any good defence.} (34... Kh7 35. h5 $1 {[%csl Gf5,Gf6,Gf7,Gf8] is
devastating.}) (34... Kg7 $2 {loses on the spot after} 35. Ngf5+ $1 gxf5 36.
Rxf5 $1 Qe7 37. Rh5 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Ga1f1,Gd4f5]}) (34... Qg7 {is the lesser
evil which will be similar to the game continuation after} 35. Qf4) 35. Nc6 (
35. Qxh6 Bxg4 36. Rf4 Bc8 37. h5 {with strong attack.}) 35... Qg7 36. Qf4 {
'+/-'} Rd7 37. Rf2 Bb7 38. Nd4 Re5 39. Nf3 Re8 40. g5 h5 41. Nd4 {The time
trouble is over and Muzychuk continues to mount pressure.} Qe5 42. Qd2 Rc7 43.
Raf1 Ree7 44. Rf6 {The queen is in danger, the threat being Nd4-f3 to trap it.}
Red7 45. R6f4 b4 {Pogonina decided that the moment for the counterplay had
come, but Muzychuk's position is rock solid. '?'} 46. Nf3 (46. cxb4 Nd3 {
[%csl Gd3,Gd4][%cal Gc7c1,Ge5d4] was Black's idea, although the complications
should nevertheless favor White after} 47. Nge2 Nxf4+ 48. Qxf4 $1 Qxf4 49. Rxf4
Rd8 50. Ba4 $1 {with the intention to shoot the knight on its way to e5.})
46... Qg7 (46... bxc3 47. Nxe5 cxd2 48. Nxd7 Nfxd7 49. Rxf7) 47. cxb4 Nd3 48.
Rf6 {Muzychuk sacrifices the exchange to keep the situation under control, but
there was no need of doing this.} (48. Bxd3 cxd3 49. Ne1 $1 Rc4 50. Nxd3 Rdc7
51. Qe3 $18) 48... Nh7 49. Nd4 Nxf6 50. gxf6 Qf8 51. Ba4 {The culmination of
the game.} (51. Bxd3 cxd3 52. Qxd3 {although the black rooks will start
working now on the c file.}) (51. Nxh5 $1 {with the possible line} gxh5 52.
Bxd3 cxd3 53. Rf5 {and wins.}) 51... Ne5 $2 {Now it is all over. White will
have it all-the mating attack and the material advantage.} (51... Rd8 52. Nxh5
$1 Rb8 53. Ng3 {although I doubt that this is survivable.}) 52. Bxd7 Rxd7 53.
Nf3 (53. Nxh5 {at once works as well} gxh5 54. Qg5+ Ng6 55. Qxh5 {followed by
Qh5-g4 and h4-h5 but there is no need to sacrifice a piece in this match
situation.}) 53... Ng4 54. Nxh5 $1 {Muzychuk finally made it to her opponent's
king.} gxh5 55. Qg5+ Kh8 56. Qxh5+ Nh6 (56... Qh6 57. Qxg4) 57. Kh2 Qg8 58. Rg1
{Mariya Muzychuk is just a point away from the title!} 1-0

