{[%evp 0,75,28,22,42,13,33,17,24,2,0,-1,27,-18,11,3,16,-24,-20,-6,-12,-10,-7,
-7,28,24,55,54,56,59,79,57,62,51,67,51,57,82,88,79,80,61,70,77,95,96,96,94,95,
106,117,94,101,83,89,92,119,117,114,134,205,173,213,219,237,241,266,178,246,
238,352,189,294,349,375,348,411,396]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6
5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5
{In his young days Kasparov was following the practical approach of an early
central closure, intending his favourite kingside attack. However, the future
world champion knew well enough that Black may suffer from some additional
problems.} c4 $6 13. b4 $1 {"My opponent was surprised by this set-up, which I
prepared on my own for this game, having noted Black's problems with his 'bad'
queen's knight" (G.K.)} cxb3 (13... Nb7 14. a4 {is also depressing for Black.})
14. axb3 {"At first sight, Donchenko has achieved quite a good position: White
has a backward pawn on the c-file. However, he has a clear plan for mobilising
his forces - Bd2, Bd3, Na3 and so on, and if ...Nb7, then b3-b4, preventing ...
Nc5 and threatening a possible c3-c4. Gradually Black begins to suffocate due
to the congestion of his pieces and lack of space." (G.K.)} Bd7 (14... Nb7 {
is no better:} 15. b4 $1 Nd7 16. Be3 Nb6 17. Na3 Bd7 {(Kayumov-Dydyshko,
Moscow 1979)} 18. Qe2 $1 Na4 $6 (18... Rfc8 19. Rec1) 19. c4 {with an enduring
advantage.}) 15. Bd2 {White has various ways of a queenside expansion, many
manoeuvres help him improve his queenside position.} Rfc8 (15... Nb7 16. b4 $1
{[%csl Rb7][%cal Rb4a5,Rb4c5]} a5 17. Bd3 Rfb8 18. Na3 Nd8 19. Qe2 {[%csl Rb5]
[%cal Rd3b5,Ra3b5] , Kasparov-Crisofari, Bastia simul' 2008.}) 16. Bd3 {(3)} (
16. Na3 $5 {was slightly more accurate.}) 16... Be8 17. Bf1 (17. Be3 $5 {
[%cal Ge1e2,Ge2a2,Yf3d2] with the ideas of Re2-a2(c2) and Nfd2.}) 17... Nb7 $6
{Here the knight's prospects are very obscure.} (17... Bd8 $5 18. Na3 Qe7 {
"(b7) with the typical idea ...Bb6, defending according to the principle
'stand and wait'. Donchenko clearly underestimated the dangers of the
impending squeeze." (G.K.)}) 18. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Ya6,Gb4,Yb5,Rc5][%cal Rb4a5,
Rb4c5] A key move in White's plan that locks the knight and fixes the
opponent's weakness(es) on the queenside.} Nd7 19. Na3 Nb6 20. Be3 Bd8 21. Rc1
$1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gc3c4]} Nc4 $6 {Black no longer knows what to do.} 22. Bxc4 $1
{"I was very proud of this unexpected exchange of bishop for a knight. Black's
replies are forced." (G.K.)} bxc4 23. Nd2 Bb5 24. Ra1 {[%csl Rb7] "With the
unavoidable exchange on b5 and the seizure of the a-file. And the knight on b7
is still dead - White effectively has an extra piece. The conversion of the
advantage, beginning from the 18th move, makes this game a textbook example." 
(G.K.)} h6 25. Nxb5 axb5 26. Nf1 Bg5 27. Re2 $1 Bxe3 28. Nxe3 Qd8 29. Rea2 Rab8
30. Ra7 Rc7 31. R1a6 Rd7 32. Qa1 Kh7 33. g3 g6 34. Rc6 h5 35. h4 g5 $6 36. Qd1
Kg6 37. Nf5 Qf6 38. Qd2 1-0

