{[%evp 0,58,28,20,20,21,20,28,36,-10,2,5,18,0,10,10,16,-17,-16,-7,-7,-7,-7,-7,
24,-18,-9,-3,36,-2,37,44,42,25,67,40,57,46,58,50,70,46,21,24,63,73,74,51,51,98,
124,26,23,-24,-24,-97,-100,-99,-119,-340,-408]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6
4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4
Qc7 12. Nbd2 cxd4 {If Black wants to solve the problem of his queenside knight,
this might be a good idea.} 13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Nb3 a5 15. Be3 a4 16. Nbd2 Bd7 17.
Rc1 Qb7 18. Qe2 Rfe8 19. Bd3 Rab8 20. dxe5 Nxe5 {Diagram [#] In this
theoretical position Sam decided to surprise me:} 21. Bb1 (21. Nxe5 dxe5 22.
Bc5 {is the main course of the events instead.}) 21... Bc6 {After a brief
check I decided to hit the centre. This leads to a very interesting tactical
skirmish:} 22. Nd4 $5 Bxe4 23. Nxe4 Nxe4 24. Nc6 $1 {Diagram [#]} Ng5 $1 {
The only way.} (24... Nxc6 $2 {loses the horse on the pin after:} 25. Bxe4 Rec8
(25... d5 26. Bxd5 Nd4 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Bxd4 Bb4 29. Qh5+) 26. Qf3 Ne5 27.
Bxb7 Nxf3+ 28. Bxf3 $18) 25. Nxe7+ (25. Nxb8 Ngf3+ {that White can go for the
tricky-} 26. Kh1 $5 (26. gxf3 Nxf3+ 27. Kf1 {leads to a draw-} Nh2+ (27... Nd4
{but there is a simple refutation-} 28. Qg4 Qh1+ 29. Qg1 Qxh3+ 30. Qg2 $18) 28.
Kg1 Nf3+) 26... Nxe1 {Diagram [#] I saw that far, the computer a bit further-}
27. Nc6 {the same motif again. It's funny how people (or it is probably just
me) tend to miss recurring tactical themes in a single game.} Nxc6 28. Be4 {
True, this time the resource-} d5 {works-} 29. Bxd5 Nd3 30. Qxd3 Nb4 31. Qxh7+
$5 (31. Bxb7 Nxd3 32. Rc7 Nxb2 {and Black should survive.}) 31... Kxh7 32. Bxb7
Nxa2) 25... Qxe7 26. f4 $6 (26. Qh5 {Better was: Although also interesting is:}
h6 (26... Ngf3+ 27. gxf3 g6 28. Qh6 Nxf3+ 29. Kg2 (29. Kh1 Qb7) 29... Nxe1+ (
29... Qf6 $2 30. Red1 Nh4+ 31. Kh2 $18) 30. Rxe1 $13) 27. f4 Nc4 (27... Ngf3+
28. gxf3 g6 29. Qxh6 Nxf3+ 30. Kf1 Nxe1 31. Rxe1 $16) 28. Bf2 Ne6 29. Qf5 {
Still, in this line White keeps strong pressure for the sacrificed pawn.})
26... Nc4 27. Rxc4 $2 {Diagram [#] One mistake and the game is thrown away.
White could go for an endgame:} (27. fxg5 Qxe3+ 28. Qxe3 Rxe3 29. Rxe3 Nxe3 30.
Kf2 Nc4 31. b3 axb3 32. axb3 Na5 33. b4 Nc4 34. Be4 $17 {The good bishop
compensates a bit the lost pawn.}) 27... Nxh3+ 28. gxh3 (28. Kh2 Qh4) 28...
bxc4 29. Qg4 Rxb2 {Diagram [#] The bishops will not have the time to show
their potential. White resigned.} 0-1

