{[%csl Ra3] [#] As I have already pointed out, if White does not handle the
situation precisely, Black can take the initiative either on the queenside or
on the kingside. For example, when White has played a2-a3 or a2-a4 (with the
pawn being on b2), the move ...c5-c4 is usually a very good reaction. Black's
usual plan in such positions is to put a knight on c5 and prepare the advance .
..b5-b4. As a rule, there is plenty of counterplay on the queenside.}  *

