{The following example is White's dream scenario that every Ruy Lopez player
should keep in mind. The position arose in the old game Tseshkovsky - Henri,
1969. Before going for his kingside play, White closes the queenside.} 14. a4
$1 {This typical move works extremely well when Black's rooks are not
connected. Now, the bishop will be forced into a passive position.} Bb7 {
[%csl Rb7,Rd5][%cal Rb7d5] The bishop is now biting on granite.} 15. c4 $1 {
This move is an important part of White's strategy. Black is forced to close
the queenside by means of ...b5-b4.} b4 16. Nf1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf1g3] Since the
queenside is closed, White has a free hand on the other wing. In Ruy Lopez
type of structures, there are two ways of developing the kingside initiative -
White prepares either g2-g4 or f2-f4. In this concrete example, g2-g4 followed
by Ng3 is easier to achieve.} Nbd7 17. g4 $1 Rfb8 18. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5,Gg1h1,
Ge1g1,Gg4g5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] The attacking scheme in such positions is quite
simple. White is going to play Nf5 followed by Kh1 and Rg1. After that, he can
already start advancing the kingside pawns.} g6 $6 {Even though Black's
position is already difficult, the advance ...g7-g6 only helps White. The
g6-pawn can be used as a hook.} 19. b3 Bf8 20. Kh1 ({Even more straightforward
would have been} 20. g5 Ne8 21. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] with h4-h5 to follow.}) 20...
Bg7 21. Rg1 Kh8 22. Be3 Ng8 23. g5 $1 {An important move. White gains more
space on the kingside and fixes the g6-pawn. Now, Black should reckon with the
advance h3-h4-h5.} f6 {Making White's task easier but it's already difficult
to give Black advice.} 24. h4 Nf8 25. h5 {The attack is crushing.} fxg5 26.
Nxg5 Bc8 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Nf5 $18 *

