{Now, we shall deal with another popular idea for White - the f2-f4 advance.
When should we go for the f2-f4 pawn break? Sometimes, in the structure c4, d5,
e4 against c5, d6, e5, Black is the first to start active actions on the
queenside. This could be done by means of a7-a6 followed by b7-b5. Usually, a
number of Black's pieces are engaged in the preparation of the b7-b5 pawn
advance. For example, Black could prepare it by means of moves like Rab8,
Na6-c7, Bd7 and only after that a7-a6 followed by b7-b5. This is a very
typical scenario in openings like Classical Benoni and Ruy Lopez. In most of
the cases, in order to prepare the b7-b5 advance, loses control over the
centre (e5-square). That is the reason why White could consider going for
active play on the kingside. In such situations, by playing f2-f4, White tries
to make use of the fact that Black's control over the e5-square is not
sufficient. This is very often the case in openings like Ruy Lopez where
White's minor pieces are mostly concentrated on the kingside. Let's take a
look at one typical example: The diagram position arose in the game Zhigalko,
S - Deepan, C played in 2015. It is obvious that we have a Ruy Lopez type of
position. It is easy to spot that two black minor pieces and a rook are
engaged in the preparation of the b7-b5 advance. On the other hand, White is
ready to execute the f2-f4 pawn break. This advance is quite logical since
Black doesn't have good control over the e5-square and white pieces are ready
for an active play on the kingside. Zhigalko played} 23. f4 $1 {At this point,
I would like to make an important point. Under ideal circumstances, Black
would like to meet f2-f4 by means of exf4 followed by Ne5. Since black knights
do not control the e5-square, this idea is impossible here. That is why in
such kinds of structures, Black prefers to have a knight on d7. In such a case,
we are going to play f2-f4 only if we could challenge the e5-knight later (for
example with a move like Nf3). In this position, White has two sensible plans:
1) play fxe5 after Nf3 2) go for f4-f5 after Rf1} Qc8 24. Rf1 {The rook
definitely belongs to the f-file. It becomes clear that Zhigalko is planning
to follow up with the f4-f5 advance. Later on, White could bring new forces
into the attack by playing Ng4.} f6 {Sooner or later, Black must go for this
move. By playing f7-f6, he not only protects the centre but prevents White
from playing f4-f5-f6.} 25. f5 {We have a typical position with a space
advantage. As we could see, White's pawn structure restricts Black's minor
pieces. Furthermore, Black has problems establishing  coordination between his
major pieces. In my previous article, I pointed out that when we have a space
advantage, we enjoy better communication lines. That is why in such kinds of
positions, we could easily play on both wings. For example, in this concrete
situation, besides his active actions on the kingside, White could go for a
queenside play by means of b3-b4 advance.} bxc4 {The desire to open a file on
the queenside and simplify the position is quite natural. Nevertheless, it is
obvious that only White could make use of the open b-file. As a rule, when
there are is only one open file, this file is usually taken by the side which
has the space advantage. This principle could be explained by better
communication lines.} ({In any case, Black should reckon with the idea 26.
b3-b4 with the idea to meet 26...cxb4 by means of 27. c4-c5 destroying Black's
position. How to do it without giving White a free hand on the queenside? A
logical idea that comes to my mind is} 25... b4 {[%cal Ga6a5,Ga5a4] intending
to follow with a5-a4. This plan, however, has some serious drawbacks. First of
all, by playing b5-b4, Black releases the tension on the queenside and White
could concentrate all his pieces on the kingside. The idea a5-a4 seems to be
too slow. Instead of directly starting active play on the kingside, White
could apply the prophylactic thinking by playing} 26. a4 $1 {After closing the
queenside, White could bring all his pieces on the kingside. We could create
the following plan: 1) double the rooks on the f-file 2) evacuate the king to
the queenside (a2 is a perfect square) 3) open the kingside by means of moves
like Ng4 followed by h4-h5.  Given the fact that Black has no space, he
couldn't easily bring his pieces to the kingside. Also, it is difficult to
create a fortress since White has a number of pawn contacts and piece
sacrifices.} ({The computer advocates the straightforward} 26. Rf3 {ignoring
Black's queenside counterplay. Indeed, after} a5 27. Rbf1 Ra8 28. Ng4 Ne8 29.
h4 a4 30. h5 axb3 31. axb3 {It seems that White prevails since his kingside
threats are very dangerous while Black could hardly create something
interesting on the other side of the board. Nevertheless, I would like to make
an important practical consideration. For a strong engine is not difficult to
decide exactly how "insufficient" are the resources of our opponent. During
the game, however, even the slightest counterplay could cause us practical
problems. That is why it is better to prevent our opponent from creating any
counterplay.}) 26... bxa3 27. Ra1 {[%cal Ga1a3] The pawn structure on the
queenside is highly favourable for White. The a6-pawn will be a permanent
weakness, while the b3-b4 advance should always be considered. This break will
work extremely well when all black pieces are engaged in the defence on the
kingside. Black has no counterplay at all.}) ({After taking into account the
above-mentioned considerations, we could conclude that Black's most flexible
approach is} 25... a5 {Now 26.a4 is not working anymore since Black could play
26...bxc4 27.bxc4 Rb4. Of course, White will proceed with the execution of his
kingside attack. For instance, moves like Ng4, Rf3 followed by Rf1 and h4-h5
always come into consideration.}) 26. bxc4 Rxb1 27. Bxb1 {I am not sure if
this is the most precise move in the position.} ({Maybe White should have
seized the chance to immediately occupy the open b-file by taking with the rook
} 27. Rxb1 {Probably Zhigalko was afraid not to lose the f5-pawn. Nevertheless,
this is an illusion since White could make use of the weakened b1-h7 diagonal.
For example, after} gxf5 $6 28. exf5 Nxf5 $2 {, he is just winning after} 29.
Qd3 $18) 27... Kh8 28. Bd3 Na8 {The knight is going nowhere. Black is doomed
to passivity, while White could play on both wings. Even if we give Black some
extra time, he could improve his position, because his pieces lack good
squares. Such is the nature of the space advantage.} 29. h4 {Very useful move.
White not only prevents his opponent from closing the kingside by means of
g6-g5 but at the same time, in a suitable moment, he could weaken the Black's
kingside by playing fxg6 followed by h4-h5.} Ng8 30. Ng4 Rf7 31. Rb1 {Black
managed to concentrate some forces on the kingside, but White immediately
starts active actions on the other side of the board. Now, Black has to reckon
with a possible invasion on the b-file.} Bf8 32. Rb3 {[%cal Gd2b2,Gb3b8] The
idea of this move is obvious - White wants to follow with 33.Qb2 followed by
Rb8. That is why Black's next move is forced.} Ba4 33. Ra3 {Forcing the bishop
to retreat.} ({In case of} 33. Rb2 {[%cal Gd2c1,Gc1b1] Black would have played}
Rb7 {Nevertheless, as I pointed out in my previous article when having space
advantage we could afford to exchange major pieces, but it is necessary to
keep the minor pieces on the board. That is why in response to Black's last
move, White could go for} 34. Rxb7 Qxb7 35. fxg6 hxg6 36. h5 {with initiative.}
) 33... Be8 34. Qf2 $1 {By this strong prophylactic move, Zhigalko prepares 35.
Rb3. This time, Black couldn't play 35...Rb7 since after the exchange of the
rooks the f6-pawn will be handing. For example, after 36.Rxb7 Qxb7 37.fxg6
hxg6 38.Nxf6 White is winning.} Nb6 35. Rb3 Rb7 {Somehow, Black has found a
way to bring his rook to b7. Moreover, he intends to protect the f6-pawn by
playing 36...Nd7. The drawback of this plan could be explained by the fact
that black rook couldn't participate in the defence on the kingside. That is
the reason why White decides to return on the kingside.} 36. Be2 $1 {
Protecting the g4-knight and threatening to win the f6-pawn. Another idea is
to weaken Black's kingside structure by means of 37.fxg6 followed by h4-h5.}
Nd7 37. fxg6 hxg6 38. h5 $1 {This is the point! Black couldn't keep his
kingside structure flexible anymore. The f5-square will become a terrible
weakness.} Rxb3 39. axb3 g5 ({Another option is} 39... gxh5 {Even in that case,
however, White obtains a huge advantage after} 40. Nxh5 $1 Bxh5 41. Qh4 Qe8 42.
Nf2 $16 {Black has passive pieces, weak light squares, terrible structure and
vulnerable king. He will hardly survive in such a position.}) 40. Bd2 $1 {
Another wonderful positional decision by Zhigalko. In this structure, Black's
only chance to obtain some counterplay is based on the advance a6-a5-a4. With
his last move, White not only prevents this idea but at the same time frees
the e3-square for the knight. Also, in some positions, the bishop could invade
Black's camp via the a5-square.} Qb7 41. Bd1 Be7 42. Nf5 Bf8 43. Nge3 Nb6 44.
Ba5 {We can see the triumph of White's strategy. Black is deprived of the
slightest chance for  counterplay. Besides his tactical ideas on the kingside,
in a suitable moment, White could even consider opening the queenside by means
of b3-b4. In such a difficult position, the defender usually goes wrong rather
quickly. Black lost in just a few moves.} Nc8 45. Qa2 Nge7 46. Bd8 Kg8 $2 {
This is an obvious mistake, but it is already impossible to provide Black with
reasonable advice.} 47. Ng4 Kf7 48. Qf2 Ng8 49. Nxf6 $1 {This is the final
blow. Black resigns in view of 49...Nxf6 50.Nh6 Bxh6 51.Qxf6 Kg8 52.Qxh6.} 1-0

