{Let's take a look at another Spanish position. The diagram position was
reached in the game Nepomniachtchi - Bu Xiangzhi played this year in the
Hainan Danzhou GM tournament. A brief look at the position is sufficient to
understand that something had gone wrong for Black. His pieces are extremely
passive, while the queenside is completely closed. Of course, the thematic
f7-f5 advance is impossible either. It is clear that White must come up with
creative ideas, while Black is going to react accordingly. What is the right
plan for White in this position? Given the fact that the queenside is closed,
his only constructive idea consists in executing the typical f2-f4 advance.
This advance becomes even more obvious when we consider the fact that black
minor pieces couldn't establish firm control over the e5-square. In the game,
the Russian grandmaster managed to find an astonishing idea.} 22. Ra2 $3 {
This wonderful positional move shows a very deep understanding of the position.
A more straightforward way to prepare f2-f4 is 22.Nh2 followed by Rf1 and
f2-f4. What is the idea behind White's last move? Actually, White already
intends to double the rooks along the f-file. For instance, after playing Bb1
on the next move, he is going to prepare f2-f4 by means of Nh2. After playing
f2-f4, he is ready to double the rooks along the f-file. It is astonishing
that Black could do nothing against this plan.} Bg7 23. Bb1 Ne7 $6 {This move
is connected with a wrong idea. Since Black intends to answer 24.Nh2 with 24...
g6-g5, the move 23...Ne7 is designed to cover the weak f5-square. As we are
going to see, however, the move g6-g5 is never acceptable in such a structure.}
({Despite the fact that Black's last move is a mistake, it is already
difficult to find a suitable system of defence. As I have already pointed out,
we should always try to meet f2-f4 by means of exf4 followed by Ne5. That is
why Black must take have a knight on d7. But where to put the queen? A logical
attempt would be} 23... Qe7 {From "c7" the queen doesn't participate in the
defence.} 24. Nh2 Nd7 {Even in this case, however, White could execute his
typical idea. Let's take a look.} 25. Rf1 h5 {This is a typical way to play
against White's g3-knight. Nevertheless, we should know that such an approach
weakens the kingside (when possible, the pawn should stay on h7).} ({After the
passive} 25... Qf8 {White's play is very natural} 26. f4 exf4 27. Bxf4 Ne5 28.
Raf2 {[%cal Gg1h1,Gh2g4] Followed by Kh1 and Ng4. As the reader could see,
Black doesn't have enough resources to support his central knight (with a
knight on d7 instead of c8, the situation would have been different). After
the exchange of the e5-knight, White's pressure is irresistible.}) 26. f4 exf4
27. Bxf4 Bd4+ (27... h4 {[%csl Rg4] This move is rather dubious since the
g4-square is already available for white knights.} 28. Nh1 $1 {Very original
move. The white knight is heading for the g4-square. Black should reckon with
the manoeuvre Nf2-g4. For example, after} Be5 ({Nothing changes} 28... Bd4+ 29.
Nf2 Ne5 {since White could prepare Nfg4 by the simple} 30. Kh1 f6 31. Nfg4 $18
{White is ready to exchange the e5-knight after which Black remains with his
weakened kingside. As the reader already know, in such positions, White's
attack is unstoppable.}) 29. Bxe5 Nxe5 30. Nf2 {[%cal Gf2g4]}) ({As usual, the
move} 27... Ne5 {is very well met by} 28. Raf2 {[%cal Gh2f3] followed by Nf3.})
28. Kh1 Be5 {This is by far the most principled continuation. After exchanging
the bishops, Black wants to install his knight on the weakened e5-square.} ({
In case of} 28... h4 29. Ne2 Be5 {again, White makes use of the weakened
g4-square} 30. Ng4 Bxf4 31. Nxf4 {[%cal Ga2f2] Followed by 32.Raf2 with a
decisive attack.}) 29. Qc1 $1 {[%cal Gh2f3] White protects the bishop and at
the same time intends to play 30. Nf3, thus fighting for the e5-square.} Bxf4
30. Qxf4 Ne5 31. Raf2 {Again, had the other black knight been on d7, Black's
position would have been more or less OK. Now, however, the central e5-knight
could be easily challenged.} Rd7 32. Nf3 Qf8 {And here, instead of immediately
exchanging the knights, White could go for the active} 33. Ng5 {[%csl Gd3]
[%cal Gg3e2,Ge2c1,Gc1d3,Gd3e5] Intending to exchange the black knight by means
of the manoeuvre Ne2-c1-d3. After the exchange, White could make use of the
attacking potential of his pieces.}) 24. Nh2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge1f1,Ga2f2] The
preparation is over. White is ready to play f2-f4 on the next move.} g5 {
[%csl Rf5,Rg7,Rh5] After this move, Black position is positionally lost. The
squares "f5" and "h5" are very weak while almost all black pieces are
extremely passive. In this position, Nepomniachtchi finds an elegant way to
exploit the weaknesses in Black's camp.} 25. Nh5 $1 {White's idea is rather
simple - he wants to bring the queen to h5 while the knight goes to g4.} Bc8 {
Black activates his light-squared bishop but it is already too late. The next
few moves are obvious.} 26. Nxf6+ Bxf6 27. Qh5 Kg7 28. Ng4 Rh8 {This is the
position Black was aiming for. It seems that despite his passive position, he
managed to protect everything while White has run out of attacking resources.
Nepomniachtchi, however, comes up with an amazing idea.} 29. f4 $1 {This move
is designed to open up the kingside. At this point, the pawns are not
important.} gxf4 30. g3 $1 {This is the point. White is going to open the
g-file. Later on, he will just transfer his rook to g2. Once again, we could
see how deep was the idea 22.Ra2. Black couldn't take the pawn because h6 is
hanging.} Ng6 31. gxf4 Qe7 {Despite his difficult position, Black goes for the
most stubborn defence.} ({After} 31... exf4 {White manages to bring all his
pieces into play by means of the energetic} 32. Nxf6 Kxf6 33. e5+ $1 dxe5 ({
After} 33... Nxe5 {White could go for the following forced sequence} 34. Qh4+
Kg7 35. Rg2+ Kf8 36. Qf6 {Black is helpless. For example} Rg8 37. Rxg8+ Kxg8
38. Bxf4 Nf3+ 39. Kf2 Nxe1 40. Bxh6 {With mate to follow.}) 34. Rg2 {White's
idea is to eliminate the e5-pawn after 35.Bxg6 followed by 36.Qxe5.} Rde8 35.
Bxf4 $1 {After this final blow, White is winning. The bishop is untouchable.}
exf4 $2 (35... Nxf4 $2 36. Qh4#) 36. Rxg6+ fxg6 37. Qxg6#) 32. Nxf6 Qxf6 33.
fxe5 dxe5 34. Rg2 Qd6 35. Rf1 {White completed his plan. Now he has a decisive
kingside attack. After putting his king to the safe h1-square, he could play
Be3 followed by Rgf2 and Rf6. Black has no reliable defence against this plan.
That is why I leave the remaining part of the game without comments.} Rde8 36.
Kh1 Re7 37. Be3 Rc7 38. Rgf2 Rh7 39. Rf6 Qxf6 40. Rxf6 Kxf6 41. Bxh6 Rxh6 42.
Qxh6 Re7 43. h4 Re8 44. Qg5+ Kg7 45. h5 Rh8 46. Bc2 Rh6 47. Bd1 f6 48. Qg1 1-0

