{This example shows a typical idea that allows Black to handle White's
kingside play.} 14... Nh5 $1 {[%cal Rf1g3,Rg2g4] An important move for black.
If he allows white to play Ng3 or g2-g4 followed by Ng3, he would likely fall
into the Ruy Lopez grind that was Karpov's bread and butter back in the day.
With Nh5, he discourages both.} 15. Bg5 Qc7 16. Ng3 $5 ({In case of} 16. Qd2 {
black does well with} c4 17. b4 Nb7 {[%cal Ga6a5]} 18. a4 (18. g4 $6 Nf4 19.
Bxf4 exf4 {[%csl Rc3]}) 18... a5 19. axb5 axb4 20. cxb4 Bxb5 21. Qc3 Nf4 $132)
16... Nf4 {Carlsen consciously goes for the risky variation, counting on the
long term compensation on the dark-squares.} ({However, I do not see anything
wrong with} 16... Nxg3 $142 17. fxg3 c4 18. b4 Nb7 19. g4 {White does have the
f-file, but black is very solid.} a5 20. a3 Ra6 21. Rc1 axb4 22. axb4 Rea8 23.
Qd2 f6 24. Be3 Nd8 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Yf7][%cal Gd8f7,Ga5b7,Gb7d8] The well-known
Rubinstein's manoeuvre.} 25. Rf1 Nf7 $11 {[%cal Ga6a3]}) 17. Qd2 c4 18. b4 Nb7
19. Bxf4 exf4 20. Ne2 a5 21. a3 Qd8 22. Qxf4 Qe7 23. Ned4 $14 {[%csl Gg7][%cal
Ga8a1] Black had some compensation for the pawn in Giri,A (2773)-Carlsen,M 
(2876)/Stavanger 2015/1/ 2-1/2} *

