{[%evp 0,87,39,17,17,24,24,15,19,9,9,17,21,-2,5,11,16,-22,-20,-11,-7,3,4,17,30,
-26,53,51,87,80,99,97,76,65,65,71,60,58,58,61,62,56,89,74,71,75,87,60,60,60,96,
98,105,105,101,106,113,101,90,91,86,74,74,34,91,91,108,94,137,141,147,147,150,
160,157,147,160,148,145,150,154,154,173,160,230,231,228,254,335,337] This
example is a perfect illustration of how White can White play in both wings in
the Closed Ruy Lopez.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6.
Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. d5
$5 Nd8 14. a4 Rb8 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 Nb7 17. Nf1 Bd7 18. Be3 {A new move at
that time. By putting pressure on c5 White, complicates Black's fight for the
a-file.} ({An older top-level game went} 18. Bd2 Ra8 19. Ne3 Rfc8 20. Kh2 Rxa1
21. Qxa1 Qd8 22. Qa7 Ra8 23. Qxb7 Rb8 {1/2-1/2 Spassky,B-Kortschnoj,V Kiev 1968
}) 18... Ra8 19. Qd2 Rfc8 {This natural move apparently consolidates c5 and
puts pressure on the c-file. Both aspects are illusory as the game will show.
But as we will see, Black's mistake will come only later.} ({Karpov recommends
} 19... Rfb8 $5 {as the start of a more effective regrouping. However, his
suggested continuation is not the most critical.} 20. Ng3 (20. Bd3 Qc8 $1 {
Leaving the d8-square available for the bishop.} 21. Ng3 c4 22. Bc2 Rxa1 23.
Rxa1 Ra8 {Karpov} 24. Ba7 Bd8 $1 {Now and in the mainline below, this is a key
manoeuvre, aimed at reducing White's queenside pressure, which is possible
only due to the regrouping started with ...Rfb8.} 25. Qc1 Bc7 {, possibly
followed by ...Qd8 and ...Bb6.}) 20... Qc8 21. Rec1 Bd8 $1 22. Bd1 (22. Bd3 c4
23. Bc2 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Ra8 25. Ba7 $2 Bb6 $1) 22... Bb6 23. Be2 {, and now
Black should proceed with} Rxa1 ({There is no favourable way of unpinning the
c5-pawn, for instance:} 23... Qc7 24. Ra2 $1 {, followed by R1a1 or}) (23...
Qd8 24. Bg5 h6 25. Bh4 $1 {, and the pin of the knight is pretty annoying.} g5
$6 {is answered by} 26. Nxg5 {, of course.}) 24. Rxa1 Ra8 25. Qb2 Qb8 26. Ra2
Ra7 {Black has neutralized the pressure along the a-file and has a normal
position.}) 20. Bd3 g6 ({The merits behind Be3 are obvious if Black tries to
neutralise the pressure along the a-file:} 20... Qd8 $2 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. bxc5
$18 {, winning a pawn.}) 21. Ng3 Bf8 22. Ra2 {Simple chess. Disposing over
more space, White finds it easier to fight for the open file.} c4 23. Bb1 {
The way the game goes, this involves a small psychological trap. It may seem
that White has given up the fight for the a-file and that he is going to focus
on the kingside plan based on f2-f4.} (23. Be2 {looks more logical, as it
allows a quick R1a1. But in this case, Unzicker might have switched to
Rubinstein's plan:} Rxa2 24. Qxa2 Nd8 25. Nh2 Ne8 26. f4 exf4 27. Bxf4 f6 28.
Be3 Nf7 {, followed by ...Ng7 and ...Ne5, with a solid position. But even here
Be2 is more useful, as White can play} 29. Bg4 {, retaining some light
pressure.}) 23... Qd8 $2 {Preparing ...Rxa2 followed by ...Ra8, not suspecting
anything...} ({Here, too,} 23... Nd8 {would have kept Black in the game.} 24.
Nh2 Ne8 {[%cal Gf7f6,Ge8g7,Gd8f7]} 25. f4 exf4 26. Bxf4 f6 27. Nf3 Nf7) 24. Ba7
$1 {One of Karpov's most famous moves. Because of Black's queenside piece
congestion (a special mention goes to the knight), the fight for the a-file is
over. Curiously, White will not try to develop his initiative on this wing but
will use his partial success as a warranty against Black's potential activity
along the a-file. The main events will take place on the kingside, and Black
will have to just sit and wait for the execution.} Ne8 ({It is too late to try
to fight against White's domination:} 24... Qc7 25. Qe3 {, planning Bc2 and
R1a1,} Nc5 $5 26. bxc5 dxc5 27. Qg5 $1 Ne8 (27... Bg7 28. d6 $1 Qb7 29. Nxe5
Rxa7 30. Rxa7 Qxa7 31. Nxd7 Nxd7 32. e5 $16) 28. Nh5 $16 Rxa7 29. Rxa7 Qxa7 30.
Nxe5 b4 31. Nxf7 Kxf7 32. e5 $18) 25. Bc2 Nc7 26. Rea1 Qe7 27. Bb1 Be8 28. Ne2
Nd8 29. Nh2 Bg7 30. f4 f6 {Now and in the moment before the next comment,
Black has a difficult choice.} (30... exf4 31. Nxf4 f6 32. Qf2 Nf7 33. Bd4 Ne5
34. Ra7 $16 {With respect to the line above resulting in the same structure,
White's control over the open file makes a big difference.}) 31. f5 $1 {
The start of a beautiful positional attack on the light squares. Due to his
queenside congestion, Black is unable to react.} g5 (31... Nf7 32. Ng3 Bh6 33.
Qf2 Bd7 34. h4 {[%cal Gf5g6,Gh4h5] followed by fxg6 and h4-h5.}) 32. Bc2 Bf7
33. Ng3 Nb7 34. Bd1 h6 {Karpov is right when saying that Black should not play
this move unless White forces it (with h3-h4 I suppose). At a later stage, the
weakness of g6 will help White's intrusion.} (34... Qe8 35. Bf3 h5 $5 (35...
Nd8 36. Qe2 Kh8 37. Bh5 {does not make a big difference with respect to the
game.}) 36. Qe2 h4 37. Ngf1 {White still has to find the optimal way to open
the kingside with g2-g3 and h3-h4.}) 35. Bh5 Qe8 36. Qd1 Nd8 37. Ra3 {Just
playing cat and mouse a bit.} Kf8 38. R1a2 Kg8 39. Ng4 Kf8 (39... Bxh5 40. Nxh5
Qxh5 {loses the queen to} 41. Nxf6+ {But with the king elsewhere than on g8,
White could have transferred his knight to e3 via f1.}) 40. Ne3 Kg8 41. Bxf7+
Nxf7 ({If} 41... Qxf7 {, White can switch to queenside play:} 42. Bb6 Rab8 (
42... Rxa3 43. Rxa3 Rb8 44. Bxc7 Qxc7 45. Qh5 {is no better.}) 43. Bxc7 Rxc7
44. Qh5 Qxh5 45. Nxh5 Kf7 46. Ra7 Rbb7 47. Rxb7 Rxb7 48. Ra8 {Due to Black's
passive and hanging minor pieces, Black loses the pawn on b5.} Rd7 49. Rb8 {
And the pawn on c4 is not too much alive, either.}) 42. Qh5 Nd8 (42... Nh8 {
prevents Qg6 but leaves the knight awfully passive.} 43. Ng4 Qxh5 44. Nxh5 Kf7
45. Bb6 Rxa3 46. Rxa3 Ra8 47. Rxa8 Nxa8 48. Bd8 {, with full Zugzwang. (Karpov)
}) 43. Qg6 Kf8 44. Nh5 (44. Nh5 Qf7 45. Ng4 $18) 1-0

