{[#] Just like in his game against Unzicker, in the following model game,
Karpov combines his play along the a-file with kingside threats. Black's last
move was 14...Ne8, planning ...g7-g6 followed by ...f7-f5. A typical way of
preventing Black's kingside activity is} 14. Nf1 g6 15. Bh6 Ng7 16. Ne3 {
The advance ...f7-f5 is no longer possible. Of course, White could have played
Ng3 as well. From the e3-square, however, besides preventing ...f7-f5, the
knight has some influence on the queenside.} Nf6 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf6g8] Another
idea borrowed from the Classical Benoni. Black is planning to chase the
h6-bishop away with ...Kh8 followed by ...Ng8.} 17. a4 {As usual, this move
allows White to create a queenside weakness.} Kh8 18. b3 {[%csl Rb5][%cal
Gd1e2,Gc2d3] We can already see that the b5-pawn is likely to become a target.
White is ready to put pressure on b5 with simple moves such as Qe2 and Bd3.}
Rb8 {In order to protect the b5-pawn, Black is forced to surrender the a-file.}
19. Qe2 Bc8 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra7 {[%cal Ge1a1] Planning to double the rooks
along the a-file.} Ng8 22. Bxg7+ Kxg7 23. Rea1 Nf6 24. Bd3 Bd7 25. Qa2 {
[%cal Ga2a6] Even though White does not have concrete threats, its difficult
for Black to coordinate his forces. The a7-rook can participate in various
tactical ideas.} Ne8 ({The following line is a good illustration of a play on
both wings by White -} 25... Qb6 26. Ng4 $1 {[%cal Ga7e7] The a7-rook should
always be taken into consideration.} Rfd8 27. Qd2 $1 {[%cal Ga1a6] /\28.R1a6}
Rb7 28. R7a6 Qc7 29. Qh6+ Kg8 30. Nxf6+ Bxf6 31. Ng5 Bxg5 32. Qxg5 $16) 26. Qa6
Rb6 27. Qa5 Nf6 28. Ng4 {Once again, we see the same motif.} Rb8 29. Nxf6 Bxf6
30. Qc7 Qxc7 31. Rxc7 $16 {The endgame is very difficult for Black. The next
move will be Raa7. Karpov managed to convert his advantage in a convincing way.
} Rfd8 32. Raa7 Be8 33. Rab7 Kg8 34. g4 h6 35. h4 Rxb7 36. Rxb7 c4 37. bxc4
bxc4 38. Be2 Ra8 39. Bxc4 Ba4 40. Bb3 Bxb3 41. Rxb3 Rc8 42. Kg2 h5 43. gxh5
gxh5 44. Rb6 Rxc3 45. Rxd6 Kg7 46. Rc6 Rd3 47. Rc7 Kg6 48. Rc8 Bg7 49. Rc6+ Kh7
50. Ng5+ Kg8 51. Rc8+ Bf8 52. Rc7 f6 53. Ne6 Bh6 54. Rd7 Rd2 55. Kf1 Rd1+ 56.
Ke2 Rd2+ 57. Ke1 Rc2 58. d6 Rc1+ 59. Ke2 Rc2+ 60. Kf1 Rc6 61. Kg2 Rb6 62. Nc7
Rb7 63. Nd5 1-0

