{[%evp 0,79,19,38,25,16,14,23,25,0,4,0,9,2,19,14,20,-4,-5,-4,7,3,5,-26,17,18,
13,15,18,22,50,24,52,49,37,36,42,12,27,0,51,41,46,34,45,19,8,14,38,41,33,39,56,
49,22,20,102,38,31,21,86,66,89,54,193,193,187,215,255,255,325,359,343,360,375,
374,374,339,339,358,525,527] The current game is a beautiful example of a
queenside play by the rising star Alireza Firouzja. By applying a subtle pawn
play on the queenside, he manages to create a weak pawn on c4.} 1. e4 {I had
made two draws until this round, so I really wanted to push for the win in
this game.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 {
[%cal Gc6a5] By protecting the e5-pawn, Black creates the positional threat ...
Na5.} 8. c3 $5 {This rare line is underestimated. White wants to enter a
familiar type of position without having to study a huge amount of theoretical
lines.} (8. a3 {is by far White's most popular option in this position.}) 8...
O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 {We have a Chigorin position with a tempo down
for White. Since White is planning to close the centre with d4-d5, however,
Black's extra tempo is not a crucial factor.} Qc7 12. d5 $1 {And now White
should close the centre because there is no time anymore for the Nbd2/Re1/Nf1
manoeuvre.} Nc4 $5 {Making use of the extra tempo. Had the white knight been
on d2, this option would have been impossible. Nevertheless, we will see that
in some cases White can benefit from keeping the knight on b1.} 13. b3 Nb6 14.
a4 $1 {Black should be careful now since White is ready to close the queenside
by means of a4-a5.} c4 $1 {Now we can see that Black cannot really play the
old 14...bxa4 15.bxa4 a5 plan because the knight is sitting on b1 and can go
to the b5 square via a3!} (14... bxa4 $2 15. bxa4 a5 16. Na3 Ba6 17. Nb5 $16)
15. axb5 axb5 $2 {It's really hard to believe that such a move can be a
mistake. But if you go deeper into the position you understand that Black
should not really care about the pawns, and he has some great square like c5
for his knight and can get excellent counterplay!} (15... cxb3 $1 16. Bd3 (16.
Bxb3 $2 Nxe4) 16... Nfd7 $1 {Probably the move that Pentala missed during the
game.} 17. Qxb3 Nc5 18. Qc2 f5 $13 {with a very double-edged position!}) 16.
Rxa8 Nxa8 17. bxc4 bxc4 (17... Qxc4 {Of course now this looks really ugly for
Black.} 18. Ba3 Re8 19. Bd3 Qc7 20. Bxb5 $18) 18. Ba3 $1 {So here I found a
very nice setup for my pieces which you can see in the game!} Nd7 {19.Nxe5 was
the threat.} 19. Bb4 Nc5 20. Qe2 Nb6 21. Nbd2 {This was the setup that I had
in mind when I played 18.Ba3.} f5 $1 {The right move. Otherwise Black will
slowly lose the battle on the queenside.} 22. Rd1 {The logic behind this move
is simple of course: after ...fxe4/Nxe4 the pawn on d5 will be well protected.}
g6 23. Qe3 $1 {Very nice move.} f4 $2 {This move just really questions the
move 21...f5! The idea was to open up things on the kingside and fight for
some counterplay, but for some reason probably he thought he was just worse
after the exchanges in the centre. But anyway Black had to go for it!} (23...
fxe4 24. Nxe4 Nxe4 25. Bxe4 Nd7 $14 {with idea knight f6. White is still
better, but Black is fighting.}) 24. Qe2 $16 {From here I thought I was just
winning because it's clear that White will win the battle on the queenside.}
Ba6 25. Ra1 Ra8 26. Qf1 $1 {Playing for the A file} Qc8 ({Of course I was not
scared of} 26... Nd3 {because the knight on d2 will be well blocking the pawn
on d3!} 27. Bxd3 cxd3 28. Ra5 Nc4 29. Nxc4 Qxc4 30. Qa1 $18) 27. Ra5 Ncd7 (
27... Nb3 28. Ra3 {and Black has to either go back or exchange on d3 which
does not improve his position at all.}) 28. Qa1 Bb5 29. Nb1 g5 30. Rxa8 Nxa8 (
30... Qxa8 {The endgame is of course completely winning for White:} 31. Qxa8+
Nxa8 32. Na3 Ba6 33. Ba4 Nab6 34. Bb5 Bxb5 35. Nxb5 $18) 31. Qa7 {and the rest
is just a matter of time. Black's pieces are all very passive and he has lots
of weaknesses.} Nc7 32. Na3 Ba6 33. Ba4 Nf6 34. Nxg5 Nfxd5 35. exd5 Bxg5 36.
Bxd6 Nxd5 37. Bd7 $1 Qb7 38. Be6+ Kg7 39. Bxe5+ Bf6 40. Qd4 {A very strong
game from start to finish!} 1-0

