{Sometimes, however, the c4-pawn can be an important asset. In the position on
the diagram, Wesely So played} 18... c4 $1 {Black needs to make use of his
slight advance in development (a direct consequence of having saved on the
regrouping ...Bb7-c8-d7) to get some queenside play before White's kingside
attack becomes too strong. In general, the advance ...c5-c4 works very well
when Black has an active dark-squared bishop.} 19. bxc4 (19. b4 a5 $36) 19...
Ba5 $1 (19... bxc4 20. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d2] would force Black to exchange on e3
in order to save the c4-pawn.}) 20. Bd2 bxc4 {This capture is safe now that
the d2-square is not available anymore.} 21. Nhg4 Nxg4 22. hxg4 Rab8 23. Ra3 $5
{At this point, Black should have played} Bb6 $1 ({The game saw} 23... Qc5 $6 {
which is basically a waste of time.}) 24. Ra2 (24. Qf3 Bxe3 25. Bxe3 Rb2 $36)
24... Qc8 25. g3 (25. g5 $2 Bd8) (25. Nf5 g6 {White does not have any way to
justify a knight sacrifice on f5 while after} 26. Nh6+ Kg7 27. g5 Bd8 {the
g5-pawn is doomed.}) 25... Nd3 26. Rf1 Bxe3 27. Bxe3 Bxg4 *

