{[#] The next example features very important aspects of the queenside pawn
play. In the position on the diagram, Harikrishna played} 13... c4 {When White
has a pawn on a2, this advance is not so desirable. The reason is that White
can undermine Black's queenside structure by means of b2-b3. Of course, we are
speaking strictly from a structural point of view. Sometimes, the advance ...
c5-c4 just works tactically.} 14. b3 cxb3 15. axb3 Qc7 16. Bb2 {[%cal Gb3b4,
Gd1e2,Gc3c4] White's queenside structure is very flexible. After fixing the
b5-pawn with b3-b4, his next idea would be to prepare the advance c3-c4. Even
if all queenside pawns get exchanged, White will keep an advantage due to his
extra space. Additionally, the b7-bishop is a very problematic piece in such
structures.} a5 $6 {Preventing b3-b4 but weakening the b5-pawn.} ({Black
should have taken care of the passive light-squared bishop -} 16... Rfb8 17. b4
Nb6 18. Bb3 Bc8 19. Qe2 Bd7 20. Rec1 Qb7 {½-½ (47) Sadhwani, R (2555)-Perez
Candelario, M (2607) Peniche 2021 It turns out that the advance c3-c4 is not
that one-sided since Black has managed to coordinate his pieces.}) 17. b4 $1 ({
The game saw} 17. Bd3 $6 {Caruana wants to secure the c4-square for the knight
by provoking the advance ...b5-b4.} b4 18. Nc4 Nc5 19. cxb4 axb4 20. Bc2 {
[%csl Rb4] with a balanced position.}) 17... axb4 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19. cxb4 {
[%cal Gc2d3] White is planning to follow with Bd3. In this structure, the
pressure on b5 is very annoying.} 1-0

