{[%evp 0,120,17,24,24,24,24,-2,25,9,10,5,19,5,11,0,6,-22,-16,-13,19,-1,-15,-9,
-7,11,16,15,26,24,33,31,33,35,27,2,42,30,116,85,81,76,62,63,66,74,87,69,90,47,
46,33,70,77,73,45,46,71,94,90,79,-4,72,70,72,67,69,68,69,37,37,37,42,45,57,49,
59,59,65,36,31,37,48,18,18,17,6,2,35,30,41,32,49,58,50,43,1,1,-1,2,21,24,30,36,
28,31,29,2,32,23,17,9,4,28,31,37,44,26,36,32,32,32,32] The next game shows
that the advance ...c5-c4 is reliable when White's a-pawn is not on a2 or a4.} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15.
a4 c5 16. d5 c4 17. Bg5 {In those years the theory of the Breyer system was in
its beginnings. The way Karpov treated it with Black shows a deep positional
understanding.} Rb8 {To understand Karpov's play in the next phase, we should
mention the tasks on Black's agenda. 1) The bishop on c8 needs to be
reactivated. 2) The queen's knight should be placed on c5 3) Black should
leave the square d7 free if possible, as several of his pieces are competing
for it. 4) The rooks should communicate. Just that simple.} ({For unknown
reasons, modern games automatically continue with} 17... h6 18. Be3 Nc5 19. Qd2
h5 {, offering White certain kingside attacking chances.}) 18. Qd2 Bc8 19. axb5
({The aggressive} 19. Nh2 {can be met with} Be7 {, threatening ...Nxd5.}) 19...
axb5 20. Ra2 Bg7 {In view of the next two moves, this is absolutely necessary.}
21. Rea1 Nc5 {In the systems with ...h7-h6, Be3, the plan based on Bxc5 has
become popular and is not without poison. But in this game there is no chance
to implement it successfully.} 22. Qe3 Re7 23. Nd2 Rc7 {Black has achieved 
perfect regrouping and can optimistically look into the future.} 24. b3 $5 cxb3
25. Nxb3 Bd7 26. Nxc5 Rxc5 {/\...b4} 27. Qd2 Qc8 28. Ne2 Ne8 29. Bd3 f5 30. Be3
Rc7 {Black has normal kingside counterplay, while on the queenside everything
is safe. The game ended in a draw 30 moves later.} 31. f3 f4 32. Ba7 Rbb7 33.
Qe1 Qd8 34. Qf2 Rc8 35. Ra6 Bf6 36. Bb6 Qe7 37. Ra7 Rcb8 (37... Bh4 38. Rxb7
Bxf2+ 39. Kxf2 Qh4+ 40. Kf1 {Botvinnik} Nf6 {/\...Bxh3 <=>}) 38. Rxb7 Rxb7 39.
Kf1 Bh4 40. Qg1 Kg7 41. Ra7 Rxa7 42. Bxa7 Qd8 43. Qb6 Qc7 44. Qxc7 Nxc7 45. Bb8
Ne8 46. Nc1 Bd8 47. Ba7 Ba5 48. c4 bxc4 49. Bxc4 Kf7 50. Nb3 Bc7 51. Bf2 g5 52.
Be1 h5 53. Nc1 Nf6 54. Nd3 Kg6 55. Ba6 g4 56. hxg4 hxg4 57. Nb2 Nh7 58. Nc4 Ng5
59. Kf2 Kf6 60. Bb4 Nf7 1/2-1/2

