{[%evp 0,75,18,10,43,65,86,59,79,56,60,20,32,-14,18,2,-12,-26,4,-20,6,-33,12,
10,37,42,2,12,40,41,69,64,64,88,97,85,88,88,81,75,75,75,98,99,104,103,106,107,
107,107,105,110,123,113,120,115,131,122,102,113,109,84,104,87,142,155,129,110,
126,129,132,128,128,128,269,298,284,276] The next game is a beautiful
illustration of White's light square strategy on the queenside.} 1. e4 c5 2.
Nf3 d6 3. Bb5+ {The Moscow Variation often leads to Ruy Lopez structures. In
general, we can get Ruy Lopez type of position out of many openings. Therefore,
you can often hear that Ruy Lopez is the cornerstone of the chess strategy.}
Nd7 4. O-O a6 5. Bd3 Ngf6 6. Re1 e5 7. c3 Be7 8. Bf1 O-O 9. d4 Qc7 10. h3 Re8
11. d5 Rb8 12. a4 b5 {The opening is over and it's time to draw some
conclusions. In comparison to the normal Ruy Lopez positions, instead of on c2,
White's bishop is on the diagonal f1-a6. Therefore, the pressure on b5 is very
annoying. Sooner or later, Black will be forced to play either ...b5-b4 or ...
c5-c4, creating queenside weaknesses.} 13. Na3 $1 {Now, Black can no longer
keep the queenside tension. He played} b4 {when White gets the excellent
c4-square for his knight.} ({In case of} 13... c4 {White will follow with} 14.
axb5 axb5 15. b3 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4] when Black's queenside structure is falling
apart.}) 14. Nc4 Bf8 15. Qc2 h6 16. Bd2 $1 {By putting pressure on b4, Bassem
Amin is trying to provoke ...a6-a5. The idea is to weaken the entire white
square complex on the queenside.} a5 17. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Gf1b5,Ge3c4] Another
subtle move. White immediately makes use of the newly weakened b5-square. The
idea is Bb5 followed by Nc4.} Qa7 18. Bb5 Ba6 19. Qd3 Bxb5 20. axb5 {[%cal
Ge3c4]} Qb6 21. Nc4 Qxb5 22. Rxa5 Qb7 23. cxb4 cxb4 24. Be3 $18 {White is
strategically winning. Now, he is ready to start bringing all his pieces to
the queenside.} Rec8 25. Nfd2 Rc7 26. Rea1 Qc8 27. Ra6 Ne8 28. Kh2 Nc5 29. Bxc5
Rxc5 30. Na5 Nc7 31. Rc6 Rcb5 32. Qc2 Rc5 33. Ndc4 Rbb5 34. Rxc5 Rxc5 35. Nb3
Rb5 36. Nca5 Qb8 37. Nc6 Qb6 38. Na7 1-0

