{[#] This position was reached in the game Karpov,A - Torre, E, 1983. Karpov
played} 18. a4 $1 $16 {Due to the bishop's poor placement on b7, this counter
break is very effective. It also solves White's only problem, his delay in
development. Suddenly, new horizons open for the rook on a1 and the knight on
b1.} bxa4 (18... axb4 {leads to similar play as in the game:} 19. cxb4 bxa4 20.
Bxa4 Qc7 21. Nc3 $16) ({The attempt to use the passive bishop to maintain the
tension ends in a fiasco:} 18... Ba6 $2 19. axb5 Bxb5 20. Na3 Ba6 21. bxa5 Nc8
22. Ba4 {Planning the crushing Bc6.} Nb8 23. Nc2 $18 {White has an extra pawn
and is ready for a queenside invasion.}) 19. Bxa4 Qc7 (19... Be7 20. Bb5 $1 {
does not make a difference with respect to the game.} ({Karpov gives} 20. Bc6 {
followed by b4-b5, overlooking} Qc7 (20... axb4 $3 {, which allows Black to
solve all his problems:} 21. Rxa8 Qxa8 22. Bxb7 Qxb7 23. cxb4 f5 {, with
decent counterplay.}) 21. b5 $16) 20... axb4 21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. cxb4 f5 23. exf5
Nxd5 24. Bxc4 N7f6 25. Nc3) (19... axb4 20. cxb4 Nxa4 21. Rxa4 Rxa4 22. Qxa4
Qc7 23. Nc3 $16) 20. Bb5 $1 {With the current black piece configuration, the
bishop is invulnerable here. The last move attacks a5, forcing Black to help
White clear the c3-square for his knight.} axb4 21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. cxb4 Be7 ({
Karpov gives the following line in which White is just in time to stop Black's
kingside counterplay:} 22... Ra1 23. Qd2 Bd8 24. Nc3 Rxe1+ 25. Nxe1 $1 f5 (
25... g6 {offers White a tempo for his regrouping:} 26. Nc2 f5 27. f3 {,
followed by Na3, winning the pawn on c4 soon. The b7-bishop's uselessness is
pathetic. (Marin)}) 26. f3 $16 ({In fact} 26. exf5 $1 {is even stronger:} Nf6
27. Bxb6 Qxb6 28. Nc2 {, followed by Ne3.})) 23. Nc3 Ra3 ({Or if} 23... f5 24.
Bxd7 (24. exf5 Nf6 25. Bxb6 Qxb6 $14) 24... Nxd7 25. exf5 $16 {(Karpov)}) 24.
Qc1 $1 Rb3 $2 {Self-trapping the rook.} ({But if} 24... Ra8 25. Nd2 g6 26. Qc2
Kg7 27. Rc1 $16 {, followed by Qb1 and Nd1, White would sooner or later win
the pawn on c4 anyway.}) 25. Nd2 $18 f5 (25... Rxb4 26. Qa3 {traps the rook.}
Rxb5 27. Nxb5 $18 {Karpov}) 26. Nxb3 cxb3 27. exf5 {The rest is easy.} Nf6 28.
Bc6 b2 29. Qxb2 Nbxd5 30. Nxd5 Nxd5 31. Bxb7 *

