{We will start with a few examples in which Black will carry out ...d7-d5 at
an early stage. The early move order in the first game is not typical for the
early d2-d3 issue, but things will soon transpose.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. h3 (8. d3 {would be the
typical move order for our theme, transposing to the game after} Bb7 9. h3 d5
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. c3) 8... Bb7 9. c3 d5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. d3 {The 15-year-old
Fischer was not ready to go for the Marshall attack main line against his
outstanding tactical opponent. Now is the moment to say that, even though this
game was played more than 60 years ago, it remains to a certain extent
relevant for modern theory. See the games quoted below. I should also mention
a small paradox featured by this and similar positions. Black has more space
and has an advance in development, at least if we count it mathematically.
However, things are not that simple. White's position is both solid and
flexible, exactly like a Sicilian Hedgehog. The bishop on b3 exerts
unchallenged pressure and the pawn on e5 is hanging. Moreover, Black's
queenside weaknesses may count, too. In order to give an accurate evaluation
of such positions, one needs to examine them concretely, rather than counting
the developing tempi. In other words, development counts in terms of quality
and not only  quantity.} Qd6 $6 {This is the second most popular move.} (11...
Bf6 $6 {is the most frequent continuation. As strange as it may seem,
defending the pawn is not the best idea for Black, since it exposes one of his
pieces to White's queen's knight. Here is a modern example:} 12. Nbd2 Nf4 13.
Ne4 Nxd3 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Re4 (15. Bh6 $5 Nxe1 16. Qxe1 {may be even more
dangerous for Black.}) 15... Nxc1 16. Rg4+ Kh8 17. Qxc1 $36 {with excellent
compensation for the pawn, Grischuk, A (2726)-Aronian, L (2750) Mexico City
2007 (½-½, 31)}) (11... Qd7 $5 {is more in the spirit of the Marshall Attack.
True, White can take the pawn, leading to interesting play.} 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13.
Rxe5 Rad8 14. Qg4 f5 15. Qg3 {Black has good compensation for the pawn, but
the play is on, Topalov,V (2780)-Leko,P (2753) Morelia/Linares 2008 (1-0, 48)})
12. Nbd2 Rad8 13. Ne4 Qg6 {Apparently the most logical move, reaching an
optically overwhelming degree of activity. However, the queen will soon be
exposed on g6, illustrating what I meant by "the quality of development."} (
13... Qd7 {looks like a waste of time and does not solve Black's opening
problems, either.} 14. a4 {Preparing to open the a-file, in order to discard ..
.Na5 and create chances to intrude with the rook.} Kh8 (14... f5 15. axb5 axb5
16. Ng3 $5 {The knight was not really attacked, due to the pin along the a2-g8
diagonal, but by retreating it, White immediately attacks e5.} Bf6 17. Nh5 $16)
(14... b4 15. a5 $5) 15. axb5 axb5 16. d4 exd4 (16... f5 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. dxc5
e4 19. Bxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxd5 Rxd5 21. Nd4 Nxd4 22. cxd4 {[%cal Ga1a7,Gc1f4] Quite
a paradoxical position. It may seem that Black has the better structure (he
can actually take a pawn), but the combined threats of Bf4 and Ra7 make
Black's position difficult.} Rxd4 (22... Ra8 23. Rxa8+ Bxa8 24. Bf4 Rxd4 25.
Ra1 Bd5 26. Ra7 Rc4 27. Rxc7 Kg8 28. Be5 $16) 23. Ra7 Rb8 24. Bf4 Rd7 $2 25.
Rxb7 Rxb7 26. c6) 17. cxd4 f6 18. Nc3 {Suddenly, Black cannot maintain the
blockade under favourable circumstances. His bishops are either passive or
hanging.} Ncb4 19. Qe2 Bd6 20. Qxb5 Nxc3 21. Qxd7 Rxd7 22. bxc3 Nd3 23. Rd1
Nxc1 24. Raxc1 Bxf3 25. gxf3 $14 {White has more winning chances than it may
seem, and actually won in Kamsky, G (2705)-Bacrot, E (2709) Elista 2007 (1-0,
36).}) 14. Ng3 Bc5 $2 {[%cal Gg6g3] A natural move and a heavy mistake at the
same time. The threat ...Qxg3 can be parried easily and leaving h4 undefended
should have led to problems.} (14... Rfe8 {looks like the most constructive
move, preparing for the eventuality that White takes the pawn. However,} 15.
Re4 $1 {puts the queen in a bad situation.} h6 16. d4 exd4 17. Rg4 Qh7 18. cxd4
$36 {With reasonable attacking chances.}) (14... Nf4 15. d4 Nxg2 16. Kxg2 exd4
17. Qe2 dxc3 18. bxc3) 15. d4 $1 exd4 16. cxd4 $2 {Fischer misses his chance.}
(16. Nh4 $1 {would have put the queen in a critical situation.} Qf6 (16... Qd6
17. Ne4 Qe7 18. Nf5 Qe5 19. Nxc5 Qxf5 20. Nxb7 {wins material}) 17. Ne4 $1 {
Possibly the move missed by both players.} Qxh4 18. Bg5 $18 {trapping the
queen.}) 16... Ndb4 $6 (16... Nxd4 $1 17. Nxd4 Nb4 18. Be3 Bxd4 19. Bxd4 c5 {
transposes to the game}) 17. Be3 $6 {Missing the second chance.} (17. Nh4 $1
Qf6 18. Ne4 Qxd4 19. Qh5 Rde8 20. Be3 (20. Nf3 Rxe4 21. Be3 g6 22. Bxd4 Rxe1+
23. Nxe1 gxh5 24. Bxc5) 20... Qxe4 21. Bxc5 Qxe1+ 22. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 23. Kh2 Re5
24. Nf5 Rxc5 25. Nh6+ gxh6 26. Qxc5 Nd3 27. Qh5 $14) 17... Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Bxd4
19. Bxd4 c5 20. Bxc5 $1 {Obviously forced, the same as the entire following
sequence.} Rxd1 21. Raxd1 Nd3 22. Bxf8 Nxe1 23. Rd8 {Apparently winning...
Maybe Fischer overestimated this position when heading for it.} h5 $1 {Not
only preparing the king's escape to h7 but also neutralising the threat of
Bb4+ followed by Bxe1, which would run into ...h5-h4.} 24. Bb4+ Kh7 25. Rd6 Qb1
26. Rd1 Qg6 27. Rd6 Qb1 {Black should not avoid the move repetition.} (27...
Qg5 $2 28. Bxe1 h4 29. Rd7 Bc6 30. Bc2+ $1 {The point, With the queen on g6
none of these would happen.} g6 31. Bd2 $5 $18) 28. Rd1 Qg6 29. Rxe1 $5 h4 30.
Re3 hxg3 31. Rxg3 Qb1+ 32. Kh2 Qf5 33. Kg1 1/2-1/2

