{In this game we will see a completely different Fischer. He was more mature
than in the previous game, of course, but had not played any single tournament
game over the previous 20 years! Still, he could produce perfect games, at
least once in 3-4 games.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. d3 ({Deviating from the previous games,
continuing} 9. h3 Nb8 {, with varying results.}) 9... Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. Nbd2
Re8 12. h3 Bf8 13. Nf1 Bb7 14. Ng3 {Black has almost completed his development
and enjoys a space advantage. A familiar situation after all. However, all the
space he has gained so far implies certain obligations. Should he play only
neutral moves, White could prepare either d3-d4 or b2-b4.} g6 {By far the most
popular continuation.} (14... d5 $5 15. exd5 Qxd5 {may run into} 16. Bg5 {
, which is not entirely clear, though.} Nd7 (16... Qc6 17. a3 Rac8 18. Bxf6 (
18. b4 $2 cxb4 19. axb4 Qxc3 $1) 18... Qxf6 19. Ne4 Qd8 20. b4 {with certain
initiatives. We can notice that the square on c5 is weak.}) 17. Qe2 (17. Bd2 $1
{threatening c3-c4 is stronger, practically forcing the weakening move} b4)
17... h6 18. Bd2 Qd6 19. Ne4 Qc7 20. Nh4 Re6 21. Rac1 Qd8 22. Nf5 Nf6 $10 {
Tal-Conquest Tbilisi 1988}) 15. Bg5 $5 {Inducing the slight weakening of the
kingside.} (15. a4 d5 {had been played in Teichmann,R-Przepiorka,D Munich 1909
(1-0, 26), examined later.}) 15... h6 16. Bd2 {One should pay attention to
White's regrouping. Both his bishops and his knights are perfectly coordinated,
controlling a series of complementary squares and yielding White's position
hidden dynamic resources.} d5 $6 (16... Nc6 {followed by ...d6-d5 was
recommended by Seirawan, who apparently did not know that it had been played.}
17. Nh2 d5 18. exd5 $1 (18. Ng4 Nxg4 19. hxg4 d4 {offers Black a lot of space,
Campora,D (2485)-Hazai,L (2480) Nis 1985 (1-0, 40)}) 18... Qxd5 (18... Nxd5 $6
19. Ng4 $16 h5 (19... Kh7 20. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3d5] attacking f7 and threatening
Qxd5 wins.}) 20. Nh6+ $16 Kg7 $2 (20... Bxh6 21. Bxh6 $16) 21. Nxh5+ gxh5 22.
Qxh5 $18) 19. Ne4 Nxe4 20. dxe4 Qd6 21. Qe2 Rad8 22. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rh6]
[%cal Gh2g4,Gg4e3] The black kingside is a bit exposed to Ng4 and the square
on d5 is weak.}) 17. exd5 {A fierce tactical battle starts now.} c4 $1 (17...
Qxd5 $2 18. Qc1 $1 (18. c4 Qd8 (18... bxc4 19. Bxa5 cxd3 20. Qxd3 (20. Bxd3 e4
21. Bc3 $18 {Seirawan} exf3 22. Rxe8 Nxe8) 20... Qxd3 21. Bxd3 e4 22. Bc3 $18 {
Marin}) 19. Nxe5 $18 {Seirawan. Actually +/=}) 18... Kh7 19. c4 Qd8 20. Nxe5
Qc7 21. Bxa5 Qxa5 22. d4 cxd4 23. Qf4 $16 {Marin Suddenly, WHite has excellent
attacking chances.}) 18. b4 $1 (18. Nxe5 Qxd5 $132 19. Nf3 cxd3 20. Bb3 Nc4 $19
{Marin}) (18. d4 $5 {Marin} exd4 19. Rxe8 Nxe8 (19... Qxe8 20. cxd4 b4 (20...
Qd8 21. Bxg6 fxg6 22. Qc2 $18) 21. d6 Bxd6 22. Bxh6) 20. Nxd4 Nf6 21. Ne4 Nxd5
22. Qg4 $14) 18... cxd3 (18... cxb3 19. axb3 Bxd5 20. c4 Bxf3 21. Qxf3 {
[%csl Ga5]} b4 22. Rxa5 Qxa5 23. Qxf6 $18 {Hansen}) 19. Bxd3 Qxd5 $2 {Missing
or under-evaluating White's answer.} (19... Nc4 $1 20. Bxc4 bxc4 21. Nxe5 Qxd5
22. Nf3 $16 {Actually the best chance for Black. Still, in the following
correspondence game, he could not reach a draw.} a5 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. a3 Bg7
25. Qf1 Kh7 26. Rd1 Qb5 27. Nd4 Qa4 28. Ra1 Ba6 29. Qb1 Qd7 30. b5 Bb7 31. Qf1
Rd8 32. Qxc4 Rc8 33. Qd3 a4 34. Re1 Qd5 35. Qf3 Qd7 36. Qe2 Rc7 37. Nc2 Qd5 38.
Ne3 Qc5 39. c4 Qxa3 40. Ba5 Rc8 41. Qd2 Ra8 42. Bc3 Kg8 43. Be5 Re8 44. Ra1 Qe7
45. Bd6 Qe6 46. Rxa4 Rd8 47. c5 Ne8 48. Nc4 Bf8 49. Qa5 Nxd6 50. Qxd8 Nxc4 51.
c6 Bxc6 52. bxc6 Qxc6 53. Ra8 Qd6 54. Qe8 Kg7 55. Ne4 Qe7 56. Qc6 Ne5 57. Qc3
f6 58. Rc8 Nf7 59. Nxf6 Qxf6 60. Qxf6+ {1-0 Conterno,D-Beckett,P (2139) ICCF
email 2006}) 20. Be4 $18 (20. Ne4 $2 Nh5 (20... Nd7 {Seirawan} 21. Bxh6 Bxh6
22. bxa5) 21. Bxh6 Bxh6 22. bxa5 (22. g4 Red8) 22... Rad8 $17) 20... Nxe4 (
20... Qc4 21. Qb1 $1 {Indicated by Fischer} (21. Qc2 Nc6 22. Bxg6 Rad8 23. Ne4
Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Nxb4 25. cxb4 Qxc2 26. Bxc2 Bxf3 $14 {Marin}) 21... Nc6 22. Bxg6
fxg6 (22... Rad8 23. Ne4 $18) 23. Qxg6+ Bg7 24. Nf5 $18) 21. Nxe4 {/\22.Nf6+/
22.bxa5 White wins a piece and Black will not have enough compensation for it.}
Bg7 (21... Be7 22. bxa5 f5 23. c4 $1 bxc4 24. Nc3 $16) (21... Re6 22. bxa5 f5
23. Ng3 e4 24. Nd4 e3 25. f3 $18) 22. bxa5 f5 23. Ng3 {From practical point of
view, the simplest.} (23. c4 $5 bxc4 (23... Qd8 24. Nc5 Bxf3 25. gxf3 $18) 24.
Nc3 {suggested by Gligoric and Velimirovic is also preferred by the engines,
but optically things do not seem entirely clear.} Qf7 $5 (24... Qxa5 $6 $16 25.
Rb1) (24... Qc6 $1 $132 {Hansen} 25. Rb1 Rad8 26. Qc1 {[%csl Gg6,Gh6][%cal
Gb1b6] Marin}) 25. Nh2 (25. Be3 Rad8 26. Qc1 e4 27. Nh2 Rd3 $44 {Seirawan})
25... Rad8 26. Rb1 Rd3 27. Qc1 Kh7 28. Rb6 Red8 29. Nf1 $18 {Marin}) 23... e4
24. Nh4 (24. Nh2 $2 e3) 24... Bf6 $2 (24... Rad8 25. Be3 (25. Re2 Bxc3 26. Nxg6
Bxd2 $1 $13) (25. Bxh6 Bxh6 26. Nxg6 f4 $40) 25... Qf7 $1 26. Qc1 Rd3 27. Bd4 (
27. Ne2 g5) (27. Bxh6 $14) 27... f4 28. Ngf5 gxf5 29. Qxf4 {Marin}) (24... Kh7
25. Nxg6 (25. Be3 {Marin}) 25... Kxg6 26. Qh5+ Kh7 27. Bxh6 Bxh6 28. Nxf5 Qe6
29. Rad1 $40) 25. Nxg6 e3 26. Nf4 Qxd2 27. Rxe3 Qxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Rxe3 29. fxe3 {
The endgame is won despite Black's two bishops. Fischer plays the final part
perfectly.} Rd8 (29... Bxc3 30. Nxf5 Bxa5 31. Rd7 Be4 32. Nxh6+ $18) 30. Rxd8+
Bxd8 31. Nxf5 Bxa5 32. Nd5 (32. Nxh6+ Kh7 33. Nf5 Bxc3 $17) (32. Ne7+ Kf7 33.
Ned5 $18) 32... Kf8 (32... Bxd5 33. Ne7+ Kf7 34. Nxd5 Ke6 35. Nb4 $1 Bxb4 36.
cxb4 Kd5 37. Kf2 Kc4 38. a3 Kb3 39. e4 $18) 33. e4 Bxd5 34. exd5 h5 35. Kf2
Bxc3 36. Ke3 Kf7 37. Kd3 Bb2 38. g4 hxg4 39. hxg4 Kf6 40. d6 Ke6 41. g5 $1 a5 (
41... Kxf5 42. d7) 42. g6 Bf6 43. g7 Kf7 44. d7 (44. d7 Bd8 (44... a4 45. Nd6+
Kg8 (45... Kxg7 46. Ne8+ $18) 46. Nxb5 Kxg7 47. Na7 Kf7 48. Nc6 Ke6 49. d8=Q
Bxd8 50. Nxd8+ $18) 45. Nd6+ Kxg7 46. Nb7 Bf6 47. d8=Q Bxd8 48. Nxd8 $18) 1-0

