{Due to time limitations, I had to skip this game during the webinar. I
include it in the database, though, with just brief comments. The game shows
that some of the things were known by the classical players, too.} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 Na5 9. Bc2 c5
10. d3 O-O 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. Nf1 Bf8 13. h3 g6 14. Ng3 Bb7 15. a4 d5 $2 (15...
b4 {Alapin}) 16. exd5 Qxd5 (16... Qc7 $5 17. h4 {It is probably better to
prepare this way the knight jump to e4.} (17. Ne4 Nxd5 18. c4 bxc4 19. dxc4 Nb4
20. Nf6+ Kg7 21. Nxe8+ Rxe8 {yields Black reasonable compensation for the
exchange.} 22. b3 $2 Bxf3 23. gxf3 Nac6 $17) 17... h5 (17... Nxd5 18. h5) 18.
Ne4 Nxd5 19. c4 bxc4 20. dxc4 Nb4 21. Nf6+ Kg7 22. Nxe8+ Rxe8 23. Be4 Bxe4 24.
Rxe4 $16 {[%csl Gg5] Things have changed to White's favour with respect to the
line above since in case of Black's kingside expansion, the knight will have
the excellent square on g5.}) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Bg5 Bg7 19. d4 $1 {With his
knight hanging on a5, Black cannot hold his over the expanded position.} cxd4
20. cxd4 Nc6 (20... e4 21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Bxe4 Qd7 23. Bxb7 Rxe1+ 24. Qxe1 {
attacking the knight on a5.}) (20... exd4 21. Bxf6 Rxe1+ 22. Qxe1 Bxf6 23. Rxa5
$18) 21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. Bb3 $1 Qd7 23. dxe5 Qxd1 (23... Nxe5 24. Nxe5 Qxd1 25.
Bxd1 Nd7 26. Nd3 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Bxb2 {was more stubborn according to Alapin})
24. Rxd1 Nh5 (24... Nxe5 25. Nxe5 Rxe5 26. Rd8+ Re8 27. Bxf6 {Alapin}) 25. Nxh5
gxh5 26. Rd7 1-0

[Event "Candidates Tournament"]
[Site "Curacao"]
[Date "1962.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Kortschnoj"]
[Black "Petrosian"]
