{[%evp 0,58,19,31,34,19,13,4,13,-2,-9,0,7,-5,4,10,3,-22,-13,-26,17,-30,1,-4,22,
17,34,29,32,17,26,4,-14,-14,-14,-17,-14,-14,16,-21,27,4,17,-13,-17,-7,-7,-10,
-15,-28,-15,-21,-16,-35,-61,-42,-61,-42,-36,-36,-33] We will now start dealing
with White's delayed opening of the centre with d3-d4. In the first game, it
will prove a bit premature.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O
Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. d3 Nd7 $5 {Typical for Petrosian.
Anticipating a possible kingside attack long before the second white knight
reaches g3, he will keep both his bishops open to control a series of
important squares.} 10. Nbd2 Nb6 11. Nf1 Na5 12. Bc2 c5 13. Ne3 {The main
difference compared with the normal lines based on h3 and d4 consists of the
fact that both sides have more freedom of manoeuvring at this stage of the
game. The outcome of the opening largely depends on each player's ability to
make use of this freedom. Up to this moment, there is nothing to be reproached
to any of the players.} Nc6 14. h3 {This move is useful in those cases when
White plays an early d4 because it prevents ...Bg4 with pressure against the
d4-square. However, what could be the point of this move in a position where
the g4-square is under control? Kortschnoj probably intended it as a
half-waiting move, tending a small trap into which Petrosian will willingly
fall.} (14. d4 cxd4 15. cxd4 Bf6 $1 16. d5 Nd4 $1 {with counterplay.}) 14...
Be6 $1 {I would make the same comment as in the game Fischer-Spassky,
referring to the coordination of Black's minor pieces.} 15. d4 $6 {Now that
White threatens to win a piece with d4-d5, the reaction indicated in the line
above is not possible anymore. However, Petrosian's play in the next phase of
the game proves that his advance in development is real. He has reached a
genuine "quality coordination" of his pieces.} ({`} 15. Bb3 $5 {.}) 15... cxd4
$1 16. cxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 exd4 18. Qxd4 Rc8 19. Qd3 g6 20. Bb3 Nc4 21. Nd5 Bxd5
22. Qxd5 {With a better development, the control of this square would have
offered White a stable advantage, but the queen is well known to be a bad
blocking piece. However,} (22. exd5 Bf6 {would have left Black with a dream
Benoni position.}) 22... Bf6 23. Rb1 Re8 24. Rd1 Qe7 {Black has completed the
mobilization of his forces while White is playing with only a part of his
pieces.} 25. Bxc4 Rxc4 26. Qxd6 Qxe4 27. Be3 {Getting close to completing the
development, but not absolving White of problems, since Black's pieces remain
more active.} (27. Qxf6 Qxb1 28. Bh6 {was not possible because of} Qxd1+ 29.
Kh2 Qd4) 27... Re6 28. Qb8+ Kg7 29. b3 Rc2 $15 {White cannot neutralise
Black's pressure easily. Petrosian went on winning a fine game.} 30. Rbc1 Rec6
31. Rxc2 Rxc2 32. a3 Rc3 33. Qd6 Be5 34. Qd2 h5 35. Re1 Qf5 36. Qd1 Rd3 37. Qb1
Qd7 38. Qc1 Bc3 39. Rf1 Qd5 40. b4 Qb3 41. Bc5 Bf6 42. Qf4 Qe6 43. Qc1 Rc3 44.
Qd2 Rxa3 45. Re1 Qxe1+ 46. Qxe1 Ra1 47. Kf1 Rxe1+ 48. Kxe1 a5 49. bxa5 Bc3+ 50.
Kd1 Bxa5 51. Bd4+ Kf8 52. Kc2 Ke7 53. f3 Kd6 54. Be3 Kd5 55. Kb3 Kc6 56. Bd4
Bb6 57. Bf6 Bc5 58. Bb2 Kd5 59. Bc3 Ke6 60. g4 Kd5 61. Bf6 Bd6 62. Bb2 f5 63.
gxf5 gxf5 64. Bc3 f4 65. Bb2 b4 66. Bf6 Be5 67. Bg5 Kd4 68. Kxb4 Ke3 69. Kc4
Kxf3 0-1

