1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 Bd7 7. Nbd2 g6 8. Nf1
Nh5 9. Ng3 (9. d4 Bg7 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Ne3 Nf4 12. O-O O-O 13. Nd5 Ne6 14. b4
f5 15. Bb3 Kh8 16. Qe2 f4 17. Rd1 Qe8 18. Ne1 g5 19. h3 Ne7 {0-1 (31) Simon
Padros,E-Marin,M (2515) Manresa 1993}) 9... Nf4 10. O-O Bg7 {Black seems to be
very active and if allowed to complete his development properly, he could
prove this feeling right.} 11. d4 $1 {A strong novelty, forcing me to abandon
my pet line. Black is not able to maintain all his outposts.} (11. Be3 O-O 12.
d4 (12. Qd2 Qf6 13. d4 Rad8 14. Ne1 h5 15. Nd3 Bh6 16. d5 Ne7 17. Bxd7 Rxd7 {
with excellent play, Stefanov,P (2495)-Marin,M (2480) Predeal 1988 (0-1, 47)})
12... b5 13. Bc2 h5 14. d5 Na5 15. b3 Qf6 (15... c6 $5) 16. Ne1 c5 (16... c6 $1
{is more restrictive}) 17. dxc6 (17. Qd2 Qe7 18. c4 Qd8 19. Nd3 h4 20. Nh1 bxc4
21. Nxf4 exf4 22. Bxf4 c3 {Not really necessary.} 23. Qc1 Qb6 {with a complex
fight, Milu,R (2410)-Marin,M (2515) Bucharest 1993 (0-1, 35)}) 17... Nxc6 18.
b4 a5 19. bxa5 Nxa5 {with overwhemling advantage in my first game with this
line, Reyes Larena,J (2400)-Marin,M (2480) Thessaloniki 1988 (0-1, 27)}) 11...
b5 12. Bb3 O-O (12... h5 {runs into} 13. dxe5 dxe5 $6 14. Bxf4 exf4 15. Ne2 g5
16. Qd5 $18) 13. Be3 Qf6 {Black would need just one tempo to play ...Rad8,
defending the bishop, but White is quicker.} 14. dxe5 $1 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16.
Qd2 Bh6 (16... Nh5 17. f4 Qe7 18. Nxh5 gxh5 19. f5 $5 $18) 17. Rad1 Be6 18. Kh1
$1 {Preparing the next move.} Rad8 19. Ne2 g5 {Sad necesity.} 20. Ng3 {With
his kingside weak and some of his minor pieces missplaced, Black will go down
quickly.} c5 21. f3 a5 22. Bc2 b4 23. Nf5 Bxf5 24. exf5 Rfe8 25. Rfe1 g4 26. g3
Ng2 27. Bxh6 Nxe1 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. f4 1-0

