{[%evp 0,76,30,36,38,38,30,8,13,8,8,-4,-2,-30,-19,-27,-22,-43,10,13,16,23,40,
34,37,22,23,11,11,-15,-7,-7,-7,-7,-7,-37,-36,-23,-21,-6,-11,-32,-27,-31,-17,
-45,-42,-82,-82,-58,-79,-85,-68,-127,-99,-113,-85,-130,-217,-263,-273,-309,
-309,-309,-286,-503,-395,-414,-455,-636,-413,-354,-323,-306,-306,-311,-265,
-330,-301] We will move now to the thematic breaks on the f-file. In the first
game, a veteran will crush one of the most promising elite players.} 1. e4 e5
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 d6 6. c3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Nd7 $5 9.
Be3 {A somewhat clumsy move. When playing it, Caruana may have anticipated ...
Kh8 and ...f5, but most probably not ...g5!} (9. d4 $1 {as in the next game is
better.}) 9... Nb6 {This is one of the cases when huge experience allows
breaking the rules. Allowing the exchange on b6 looks like an important
strategic concession because it takes a pawn away from the centre and weakens
the d5-square. Since Caruana delayed the capture for a few moves, we will
discuss the deeper aspects of this operation at that moment.} 10. Bb3 Kh8 $1 {
Quite straightforward. Although less exotic than Ke1-d1 in the game against
Plakhetka, this has the same abstract purpose: preparing the marching in of
the f-pawn. Also, less unexpected than g2-g4 as against Gashimov, but
certainly a change of rhythm. It suddenly appears that Black's whole previous
play had just one main purpose: launching a kingside attack!} 11. Nbd2 ({
After the opening of the h3-c8 diagonal,} 11. d4 {would not be effective
because of} Bg4 {with comfortable development for Black.}) 11... f5 12. Bxb6 {
White probably thought that Black has nothing better than play ...f4 on the
next move, in the spirit of the King's Indian Defence. therefore, he decides
to keep his knight on d2, in order to react with d3-d4 and Nc4.} ({One
important alternative was} 12. Nf1 f4 (12... fxe4 13. dxe4 Bg4 {releases the
tension for nothing, in view of the calm} 14. N1d2 $14) 13. Bxb6 cxb6 14. d4 {
A necessary move, anticipating the attack based on ...g5. The straightforward
King's Indian attack starting with} Bg4 (14... g5 {may be unsound by just one
tempo now, for instance:} 15. h3 h5 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Bd5 Bf6 18. N3h2 Qe8 19.
Nd2 Qg6 20. Nc4 {and the c8-bishop, which is an important attacking piece will
be exchanged. 19...b5 does not solve the problem because of 20.a4. However,
Black can do better with 14...Bg4! immediately putting pressure on the enemy
centre.})) 12... cxb6 13. Bd5 g5 $3 {Probably the move Caruana had not
anticipated. Suddenly, White has acute problems of space and faces the threat
of losing a piece to ...g4.} ({He may have hoped for} 13... f4 $6 14. d4 {
followed by Nc4, when Black may well not be able to sustain his e5-outpost.})
14. h3 {Caruana also breaks a rule: "Do not move pawns on the wing where you
are attacked!"} ({The alternative did not look too rosy:} 14. Nc4 g4 15. Nfd2
f4 $1 (15... b5 $6 {is premature in view of} 16. Ne3 {and Black's pawns become
vulnerable.}) 16. a4 {Otherwise, Black would get rid of the weak b6-pawn with .
..b5, freeing his queen for the attack.} Qc7 17. Qb3 Bd8 {Black has solidly
defended his queenside and can think about regrouping for his attack. For
instance,} 18. Qa3 {can be met by} Rf6 {, defending d6 and preparing ...Rh6
followed by ...Qe7-h4.}) 14... g4 {The start of a forced sequence, allowing
Black to activate his play and retain some kingside pressure.} 15. hxg4 fxg4
16. Nh2 Bg5 17. Nc4 b5 18. Ne3 Bxe3 19. Rxe3 Qf6 20. Qe1 Ne7 {With a double
purpose: transferring the knight to g6 or capturing on d5. I assume the former
is the main threat, while the latter should be carried out only under special
circumstances.} 21. f3 $6 {This second break of the same rule will have almost
decisive consequences. To be compared with Plakhetka's ...f7-f5.} ({He should
have organized some defensive regrouping with} 21. Nf1 {or 21. Rd1.}) 21...
Nxd5 $1 {ince the g-file is going to be open, Black needs the g8-square for
his rook. Therefore, he executes his secondary threat.} 22. exd5 Rg8 {Suddenly,
the white king is in danger. Exchanges on g4 would just allow Black to
complete his development, but the solution was chosen by Caruana also allows
the rapid mobilization of Black's forces. ***We have seen this situation
before: the opening has not been completed yet and Kortschnoj's opponent is in
trouble.} 23. Qg3 gxf3 24. Qxf3 Bf5 {Correctly evaluating that this
self-pinning move is not dangerous.} 25. Rf1 Rg5 {Combining defence with an
attack. Rooks will be doubled at the maximum speed.} 26. Kh1 Qh6 27. Rf2 Rag8 {
Black is in deep trouble already. The hidden threat is 28...Bh3, when the back
rank weakness forces White answer with 29.Qxh3 when after 29...Rh5 he would
have to give up the queen for insufficient compensation.} 28. Re1 Qg6 $1 {
Spotting a small combination.} 29. Re3 Bxd3 $1 {The pawn is taboo because of
the fork with ... e4.} 30. Kg1 e4 31. Qh3 Rxd5 {Being two pawns down and
having a miserable position, Caruana could have well resigned already. He
would have had one possible reason to continue if Kortschnoj were in time
trouble, but this was not the case. In fact, Kortshcnoj had played quickly and
confidently and had loads of time left...} 32. Qd7 Rg5 33. g4 Qh6 34. Rf7 R5g7
({Computers suggest} 34... Rh5 $1 {as strongest, but Kortschnoj's will never
leave any doubt regarding the final result.}) 35. Rxg7 Rxg7 36. Qd8+ Rg8 37.
Qb6 Qf6 38. Qxb7 Rf8 39. Qa7 b4 $5 {Well, if ...g4 worked out well, the
similar move on the opposite wing may be just as good. White loses his last
hopes for stability on dark squares.} 40. Rh3 Qg7 41. Qe3 ({The ending is
hopeless:} 41. Qxg7+ Kxg7 42. Re3 ({The only way to temporarily maintain some
stability;} 42. Rh5 e3 {or}) (42. cxb4 d5 {are a disaster.}) 42... bxc3 43.
bxc3 Rc8 {followed by ...Rxc3.}) 41... bxc3 42. bxc3 Qxc3 43. Rh5 d5 44. g5
Qa1+ {The start of the final attack. White's poorly coordinated army cannot
provide an adequate defence to the exposed king.} 45. Kg2 Bf1+ 46. Kg3 Qe5+ (
46... Qe5+ {After} 47. Kg4 {there is no immediate win by checks, but the simple
} d4 {forces the queen to give up the control of one of the e2- and f4-squares,
which would lead to mate. Therefore, White finally resigned. Black's resolute
attack has been made viable in this game mainly because of White's refraining
from occupying the centre. Later, it took decisive proportions when White
kindly helped his opponent open the g-file. What followed was a display of
energy and inspiration from the arguably most longevity player in the whole
history. Apart from rendering an image to Kortschnoj on his 80th birthday, the
technical purpose of this article has been to reveal some typical aspects of a
pawn kingside attack. In order to evaluate whether such an operation is viable,
advantageous, premature or double-edged, one should permanently relate to the
situation in the centre and the stage of development of each side.}) 0-1

