{In the last two examples, it will be White who will open the f-file by means
of f2-f4. Both games feature interesting tactical variations, both on the
board and behind the scene.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
6. Bb3 Bb7 7. d3 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bd2 d6 10. Nd5 Re8 $2 (10... Nxd5 {was
played in Salov,V-Yudasin,L (2405) Ivano Frankivsk 1982 (1-0, 38), examined
below.}) 11. a4 $5 {Now and later, the ever solid Kholmov (the central
defender, as he was surnamed by Tal), will try to play on the whole board.} ({
The brutal} 11. Ng5 $1 {was much stronger, though.} Rf8 (11... Nxd5 $2 {
, apparently winning a piece, runs into} 12. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 13. Bxd5+ Kg6 (13...
Kf8 14. Qh5 g6 15. Bh6#) 14. Qg4+ Bg5 15. f4 exf4 16. Qf5+ Kh6 17. Rf3 g6 18.
Rh3+ Bh4 19. Qxf4+ g5 20. Rxh4+) 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Qh5 Bxg5 14. Bxg5 Qd7 15.
c3 $1 {is more convincing.} (15. f4 {is a bit premature, but nevertheless
interesting.} Nd4 16. f5 Nxb3 17. axb3 f6 18. Be3 d5 19. Rf3 dxe4 20. Rh3 h6
21. Rg3 Kh8 22. d4 $3 {Either stabilising the bishop, or weakening the
f4-square. Black should now play a normal developing move, since} exd4 $2 {
runs into} 23. Bxh6 gxh6 24. Rf1 $1 {The square on f4 is available now.} Rad8 (
24... Qh7 25. Rg6 $18) (24... Rf7 25. Qxh6+ Rh7 26. Qxf6+ Rg7 27. Rf4 Qf7 28.
Rh4+ Kg8 29. Rxg7+ Qxg7 30. Qe6+ Kf8 31. f6 $18) 25. Qxh6+ Qh7 26. Qxh7+ Kxh7
27. Rf4 $18) 15... Kh8 16. Be3 Na5 17. Bc2 f6 (17... f5 18. Qh3 {[%cal Gf2f4]
threatening f2-f4.} Qf7 19. exf5 Qxf5 20. Qxf5 Rxf5 21. d4 $16) 18. f4 exf4 19.
Bxf4 $16) 11... Nb8 $6 (11... Nxd5 12. Bxd5 $14) 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Bxa8
14. Nxf6+ (14. Nxe7+ $5 Qxe7 15. Nh4 g6 16. f4 {yields White a strong attack,
too.} exf4 (16... Nxe4 17. dxe4 Qxh4 18. fxe5 $18) 17. Qf3 Nxe4 (17... Nh5 18.
Nf5 Qf8 19. Ng3 $5 fxg3 20. Qxf7+ Qxf7 21. Bxf7+ Kf8 22. Bh6+ Ke7 23. Bxe8 Kxe8
24. Rf8+ {wins}) 18. dxe4 Qxh4 19. Bxf4 {with an overwhelming attack.}) 14...
Bxf6 15. Qa1 Nd7 16. Qa2 {More of playing on both wings.} Qe7 (16... Rf8 17.
Ra1 Bb7 18. Qa5 $16) 17. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 (17... Rf8 $2 18. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 19. Qxa8+)
18. Bxg5 Qf8 (18... Qxg5 19. Bxf7+ $1 Kf8 20. Bxe8 Kxe8 21. Qxa8+) 19. f4 ({
Preparing this attack with} 19. Qa5 {[%csl Gb5,Gc7] , attacking b5 and c6, was
even stronger.} c6 (19... Nc5 20. Ba2 h6 21. Be3 c6 22. f4 $18) 20. f4 $18)
19... Nc5 20. fxe5 Nxb3 21. exd6 $1 {The move Kholmov was relying on.} (21.
Qxb3 h6 22. Be3 Rxe5 $11) 21... Qxd6 $6 (21... Nc5 $2 22. Be7 Rxe7 23. dxe7 Qe8
24. Rxf7 Qxf7 25. Qxa8+) (21... cxd6 $1 22. Qxb3 d5 $14 {offers better chances
for survival, because it activates the bishop on a8.}) 22. Qxb3 Qc5+ 23. Kh1
Re6 (23... Qxg5 24. Qxf7+ {wins}) 24. Bh4 {Starting with this moment, Kholmov
plays inaccurately, probably found himself in time trouble.} (24. Bd2 $1 Qh5
25. Rf3 {Now and later, White will have effective ways of parrying the threats
on the back rank.} Bc6 (25... Rf6 26. Qa3 Bc6 27. Qa7 h6 28. Rxf6 $1 Qd1+ 29.
Qg1 $18) 26. Qc3 Rf6 27. Rxf6 Qd1+ 28. Be1 gxf6 29. Kg1 $18) 24... Qh5 25. Bg3
Rf6 26. Rg1 h6 27. Bxc7 Kh7 28. Qa3 Bc6 29. Bb6 Qe2 (29... Bxe4 $1 {attacking
the bishop on b6 would have equalised.}) 30. Bd4 Rg6 31. Qa1 Qxc2 32. Qd1 Qxd1
33. Rxd1 f5 34. Re1 fxe4 35. dxe4 Rg4 36. h3 Rxe4 37. Rxe4 Bxe4 38. Bc3 1/2-1/2

