{[%evp 0,45,42,20,34,24,26,25,16,-3,6,-2,19,11,11,11,23,23,23,20,23,27,35,34,
37,-8,-1,-23,0,-3,17,17,17,25,27,27,47,13,72,44,44,41,46,45,56,60,56,0]} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7 7. d3 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9.
Bd2 d6 10. Nd5 Nxd5 ({Obviously better than} 10... Re8) 11. Bxd5 Qc8 12. Ng5 {
A bit premature.} (12. a4 $5) 12... h6 $2 {This helps the knight to evacuate
the exposed square and reach one offering better perspectives in view of f2-f4,
...exf4, Nxf4.} (12... Nd4 $1 13. Bxb7 Qxb7 14. c3 Bxg5 $1 15. Bxg5 Ne6 16. Be3
c5 {Black has stabilised the position and has little to fear.}) 13. Nh3 $16 Bf6
(13... Nd4 14. Bxb7 Qxb7 15. f4 exf4 16. Nxf4 $16) 14. c3 Ne7 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16.
f4 Qb6+ 17. Kh1 exf4 18. Bxf4 (18. Nxf4 $1 {was stronger.}) 18... Kh7 (18...
Be5 $1 {would have reduced White's attacking potential.} 19. Qd2 Bxf4 20. Nxf4
Rae8) 19. d4 {This offers Black a hidden chance.} (19. Qd2 $1 {threatening
Bxh6 was stronger.} Be5 20. Be3 c5 21. d4 cxd4 (21... Bf6 22. Bxh6 cxd4 23.
Rxf6 gxf6 24. Bxf8 Rxf8 25. cxd4 $5 $18) 22. cxd4 Bf6 23. e5 $1 $18) 19... Ng6
(19... Qc6 $1 {would have somewhat spoiled White's attacking mechanism.} 20.
Qd3 Ng6) 20. Qh5 {[%cal Gf4h6] Freed of the task of defending e4, the queen
has reached the optimal square. The threat is Bxh6.} Be7 ({AFter} 20... Nxf4
21. Nxf4 {[%csl Gf6,Gf7][%cal Gf4d5] the threat Nd5 is hard to meet since the
bishop and the pawn on f7 are hanging.} g6 (21... c6 22. Qg4 {threatening Nh5
does not improve Black's position.} g6 23. Nh5 $1 Bg7 (23... gxh5 24. Qf5+ $1)
24. Nf6+ Bxf6 25. Rxf6 Qc7 26. Raf1 Qe7 27. h4 {WHite will soon have a
decisive attack.}) 22. Nd5 gxh5 23. Nxb6 cxb6 24. Rxf6 Rae8 25. Re1 Re6 26. Rf4
$16) 21. Be3 Rae8 22. Nf2 {Regrouping systematically.} Qb7 {It is too late for
attacking e4.} 23. Ng4 $1 Qxe4 24. Bxh6 $1 {White has a decisive attack
already, but certain accuracy is needed.} gxh6 25. Rae1 Qd3 26. Nxh6 Kg7 27.
Nf5+ Kg8 28. Nh6+ Kg7 29. Nf5+ Kg8 30. Rf3 $6 {The rook lift weakens the back
rank, so White should have prepared it.} (30. Rd1 $1 Qc2 (30... Qe4 31. Rf3 Bf6
32. Rdf1) 31. Kg1 $3 {[%cal Gf1f2,Gd1f1,Rf2f3] The point. The kning not only
prepares Rf2, but also defends the square on f1 in advance.} Bf6 32. Rf2 Qe4
33. Rf3 Qe2 {The same defensive idea as suggested below, but with the king on
g1 already.} 34. Rdf1 Qd2 35. Rh3 Bh4 36. Nxh4 Re1 37. Rhf3 Qe2 {With the rook
on f1 well defended, White can unpin himself with} 38. Qh6 $18 {[%cal Ge2h5]})
30... Bg5 $2 {Exposing the bishop without any reason.} (30... Bf6 $1 {was the
correct defence.} 31. Ref1 (31. Rg1 Qe2 {pins the rook.}) 31... Qd2 32. Nh6+ (
32. Rh3 Bh4 33. Nxh4 Re1 34. Rhf3 Qe2 $19) 32... Kg7 $11 {White does not have
more than a perpetual since} 33. Rxf6 {loses to} Qxh6 {and if} 34. Rxf7+ Rxf7
35. Rxf7+ Kxf7 36. Qxh6 Re1# {Things that can happen with the king on h1...})
31. Ref1 Re3 32. R3f2 (32. Nxe3 Bxe3 33. Re1 Re8 34. Qh3 Qd2 35. Qg3 $18) 32...
Bf4 33. g3 Qe4+ 34. Kg1 Re1 35. gxf4 Rxf1+ 36. Rxf1 c5 37. Qg5 cxd4 38. Qf6 1-0

