-42,-21,11,16,-8,-36,16,-24,89,74,64]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6
5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12.
Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. Bg5 {This natural developing move is
introduced in the middle of the 1950'es. The main idea behind it is provoking
the somewhat weakening h7-h6. In this way, White would have better attacking
prospects.} h6 ({Too passive is} 15... Bg7 16. Qd2 Qe7 17. b3 c6 18. Rad1 Qf8
19. a4 Rad8 20. Qc1 h6 21. Be3 Kh7 22. b4 {White had a big space advantage and
eventually won in Karjakin, S - Kamsky, G Nice 2009}) 16. Bd2 {This isn't a
perfect spot for the bishop, but the pressure on e4 leaves no better choice.} (
{Dubious is} 16. Be3 $6 exd4 17. Bxd4 (17. cxd4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxe4 {leaves
White with no adequate compensation.}) 17... c5 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. a4 b4 {
Black was better due to his powerful dark-squared bishop in Ameir, M - Amin, B,
Cairo 2015.}) 16... Bg7 17. Qc1 (17. a4 {As usual, the b5-pawn is a target.
However, in this case, it's difficult for White to extend initiative on the
queenside in view of the awkward location of his pieces.} Nb6 $1 {It makes
sense to provoke White to release the tension or create weak spots in his camp.
} 18. b3 {This is the most common response.} (18. axb5 axb5 19. b3 (19. Bd3 {
, as was tried in Hou Yifan - Vitiugov, N Belokurikha 2018 can be naturally
met by} Nc4 $146 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. Bc1 exd4 22. Nxd4 c6 $132) 19... c5 {
Now, when the a-file is open, Black doesn't mind letting White lock the
b7-bishop.} 20. d5 Qc7 21. Qe2 c4 22. b4 {This was Pichot, A - Cheparinov, I
Doha 2016. At this moment, it made sense to swap all the rooks:} Rxa1 $146 23.
Rxa1 Ra8 24. Qd1 Qb8 $11) (18. Qc1 Kh7 {transposes to 17.Qc1.}) (18. a5 Nc4 19.
Bc1 d5 $1 20. Nxe5 Nxe5 21. dxe5 Nxe4 22. Bf4 g5 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Bg3 Bxe5 25.
Bxe4 Bxe4 26. Rxe4 Qxd1+ 27. Rxd1 Bxg3 28. Rxe8+ Rxe8 29. fxg3 Re2 30. Rd8+ Kg7
31. Ra8 Rxb2 32. Rxa6 Rc2 33. Rc6 b4 34. Rxc7 Rxc3 35. Rb7 Ra3 {1/2 (35) Mista,
A (2616) -Almasi,Z (2695) Germany 2014}) 18... bxa4 19. bxa4 Nc4 20. Bc1 {
Naturally, White prefers to deviate from exchanging his dark-squared bishop.
On the flip side, now half of his pieces are placed on their initial spots, so
Black feels free to challenge the centre.} (20. Rb1 Bc6 (20... Nxd2 21. Qxd2
Rb8 22. Bd3 Bc6 23. Rxb8 Qxb8 24. Qa2 exd4 25. cxd4 Qa8 26. Bc4 Re7 27. Nh4 d5
28. Bb3 Nxe4 29. Nxe4 Kf8 30. Re2 dxe4 31. Bxf7 Rxf7 32. Nxg6+ Kg8 33. Ne7+ Kf8
34. Ng6+ Kg8 35. Ne7+ {1/2 (35) Ter Sahakyan,S (2615)-Boruchovsky,A (2542)
Terme Catez 2021}) 21. Bd3 (21. Bc1 d5 22. Nxe5 ({The more interesting try
would be} 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Qd3 {, but even then after} Ndb6 $1 24. a5 Nxa5 25.
Nxe5 Bxe5 26. dxe5 Qxd3 27. Bxd3 Nac4 {the a-passer offers Black a comfortable
play.}) 22... Nxe5 23. dxe5 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 dxe4 {Black was fine in Balogh,C -
Banusz,T Slovakia 2016}) 21... Nxd2 22. Nxd2 {This position took place in
Saurabh, A - Ghosh, D Mumbai 2016.} Qd7 {At this point, Black could have
exploited the lack of dark-squared bishop in opponent's camp by means of} 23.
a5 d5 $1 {,forcing favorable simplifications:} 24. dxe5 Nxe4 25. Ndxe4 dxe4 26.
Bxe4 Qxd1 27. Rbxd1 Bxe4 28. Rxe4 Rxe5 {White has to struggle for a draw.})
20... d5 $1 {This thematic break comes on time.} 21. Bd3 ({More accurate seems
} 21. dxe5 Nxe4 22. Bf4 ({Bad is} 22. Nxe4 $2 dxe4 23. Qxd8 Raxd8 24. Bxe4 Bxe4
25. Rxe4 Rd1+ 26. Re1 Rxe1+ 27. Nxe1 Rxe5 $17) 22... Nxe5 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24.
Bxe4 Bxe4 25. Rxe4 Qxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 Rxe4 28. fxe4 Bxc3 29. Bxc7
Re8 $11 {, and the draw is the most probable result.}) 21... dxe4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4
23. Bxc4 Nd6 24. Ba2 exd4 25. Rxe8+ Qxe8 26. cxd4 {We have been following the
correspondence game Klausner, H - Laurent, C ICCF email 2011. At this moment
