Qxf2 30. Qxf2 Bxf2 31. Bxh6 Re8 $15 {White's bishops don't offer a full
compensation here.}) (17. Nh2) 17... Kh7 18. a4 (18. h4 {The most aggressive
attempt to fight for the initiative.} exd4 $1 {This committing move is
justified by the fact that g4 belongs to Black's knight now.} 19. cxd4 c5 20.
e5 {The most consistent - White opens the diagonal b1-h7, so g6 is vulnerable
now. On the other hand, Black's pieces are getting activated as well.} ({
Inferior is} 20. d5 Ng4 21. h5 Nde5 $36 {The weakness of g4 tells and White's
king is in bigger danger.Tunyik, V - Andriuschenko,N ICCF email 2011}) 20...
dxe5 21. dxe5 Ng4 22. e6 {This position was reached in Smirin, I - Eljanov, P
Ashdod 2015. At this point, Black could have damaged the opponent's pawn
structure by means of} Bxf3 23. gxf3 Nge5 24. Be4 Rxe6 25. f4 Nc6 26. h5 {
White's light-squared bishop is so powerful that it is worths a rook!} Rxe4 27.
Nxe4 Nd4 28. Qd1 Nf8 29. hxg6+ fxg6 $44 {In this unbalanced position, Black's
chances are by no means worse.}) ({White has also tried} 18. Nh2 $6 {The
knight's manoeuvre seems slow and makes it possible for Black to seize the
initiative with} d5 $1 19. dxe5 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Nxe5
$15 {Murawski,G - Janocha,W Lubniewice 1994}) ({The prophylactic} 18. b3 {
exposes the long diagonal, so it makes sense to play} exd4 ({Instead,} 18...
Rc8 19. Rb1 c6 20. a4 Qc7 21. Bd3 $14 {was passive for Black in Salem,A -
Flores Rios,M Tromso 2014}) 19. cxd4 c5 20. d5 a5 21. Rb1 (21. Bc3 b4 22. Bb2
Ba6 23. Qf4 Qe7 $132 {also offers Black plenty of play on the queenside.}) ({
Pointless is} 21. Bd3 Ba6 22. a4 b4 23. Bxa6 Rxa6 24. Qc4 Ra8 $15 {the poor
location of the d2-bishop doesn't allow White to set-up a blockade.}) 21... b4
22. Bd3 a4 23. a3 axb3 24. axb4 Rc8 $1 {[%eval -32767,0] Black had excellent
counter-play along the c-file in the correspondence game Popov, V - Harabor,
