11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {This is White's second
most popular choice according to statistics. At some point, this move even
became the main preference of the top players. In comparison to 15.a4, White
isn't focused on attacking the b5-pawn. He mainly aims to seize more space in
the centre by advancing d4-d5 and c3-c4.} a5 $5 {This move was introduced in
2007 by one of the leading Breyer experts Gata Kamsky. Black leaves the
dark-squared bishop on its initial spot for a while, so the d6-pawn remains
protected. Moreover, the potential b5-b4 advance might undermine White's
control of d4 and offer Black good prospects on the queenside.} ({In my
opinion, the following high-level game illustrates the strategic danger of
Black's position if he lets White to lock the centre:} 15... Bg7 16. d5 Qe7 {
Black connects the rooks and makes c7-c6 possible.} (16... c6 $6 17. dxc6 Bxc6
18. Qxd6 {leaves Black with no adequate compensation for the pawn.}) (16... Nb6
$5 {is another common response. Even here, however, Peter managed to claim
superiority after} 17. Rb1 $1 c6 18. c4 Qc7 19. Bd3 Nfd7 20. Be3 $14 {Leko,P -
Beliavsky, A Bled 2002}) 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rec8 19. Rc1 a5 {The same approach
worked well for Black in similar positions that arise after 15.a4. However, in
this situation, White can interrupt Black's plan.} 20. Qd2 bxc4 21. bxc4 cxd5 (
{In particular, the typical counterattacking move} 21... Ba6 {is now well met
by} 22. Ba4 $1 cxd5 23. cxd5 {, and White is firmly in control.}) 22. cxd5 Nc5
23. Bd3 {Black is left with a passive bishop on b7 and was eventually
outplayed in Leko, P - Short, N Wijk aan Zee 2005.}) 16. Rb1 $5 {New move,
played by Kasimfzhanov} ({The prophylactic} 16. a3 d5 $1 {is well met by} 17.
Bg5 {The only way to fight for the initiative.} ({The timid} 17. dxe5 $6 dxe4
18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4 Nxe5 $15 {allows Black to seize the
initiative.}) 17... h6 {This move forces the favourable exchange of the
opponent's dark-squared bishop.} 18. Bxf6 ({Over-optimistic is} 18. Bh4 $6 g5
19. Nxg5 hxg5 20. Bxg5 exd4 21. e5 (21. cxd4 dxe4 22. Nxe4 Bg7 $17) 21... Rxe5
22. Rxe5 Nxe5 23. cxd4 Ng6 24. Qf3 Ra6 {leaves White no sufficient play for
the piece.}) 18... Qxf6 19. exd5 exd4 20. Rxe8 (20. Nxd4 Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Bxd5
22. Nxb5 Qb6 23. c4 Bb7 $44 {also provides Black with full compensation for
the pawn due to the powerful dark-squared bishop.}) (20. Ne4 $2 Rxe4 21. Bxe4
dxc3 $17 {is bad for White who is paralyzed by the strong c3-pawn.}) 20... Rxe8
21. Nxd4 b4 22. axb4 axb4 {Black took full control over the dark squares.
White doesn't pretend on claiming superiority. Anand,V - Amin,B Batumi GEO 2018
}) (16. Bd2 {isnot a successful attempt to stop b5-b4:} b4 $1 17. cxb4 (17. Bd3
{is traditionally met by} d5 $1 {when Black successfully solves his space
problems:} 18. Qc2 c5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Rxe5 21. Bf4 Re6 $11 {Unander,M -
