18... Bh6 {The bishop is perfectly placed on c1-h6 diagonal and makes it more
difficult for White to connect his rooks.} (18... exd4 19. Nxd4 d5 20. exd5
Nxd5 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Nb5 c6 23. Be4 cxb5 24. Bxd5 Bxd5 25. Qxd5 bxa4 26. Qd4
f6 27. bxa4 Qe6 (27... Ra6) 28. Ne4 Be7 29. Ng5 Qb3 30. Qxd7 Qxb2 31. Re1 fxg5
32. Qd5+ {1-0 (32) Saric,I (2637)-Roiz,M (2618) Sibenik 2012}) (18... c5 $5 19.
dxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 (20. Nxe5 dxe5 21. Bd3 Ba6 22. Bxa6 Qxd1 23. Raxd1 Rxa6 24.
Rc1 Ra7 25. Nf1 Rd7) 20... dxe5 21. Bd3 Ba6 22. Bxa6 Qxd1 23. Raxd1 Rxa6 24.
Nd2 Nd7 25. Ngf1 Bh6 26. Nc4 Nb6 27. Rd6 Re6) 19. dxe5 {Eventually, White
finds nothing better than simplifying the matters.} (19. Bd3 exd4 20. Nxd4 {
, as in Ganguly, S - Stefanova, A Caleta 2017 can be met by} c5 21. Nb5 Bf4 22.
Qf3 Be5 23. Bxe5 Nxe5 24. Qe3 Nxd3 25. Qxd3 Re6 $132) 19... dxe5 20. Qe2 {
is hardly an improvement, as was illustrated in the following fresh encounter:}
(20. Bd3 {The most natural continuation - transferring the bishop on c4 would
