{[%evp 0,52,29,32,32,32,28,12,4,1,9,9,23,8,8,8,17,-11,-11,-11,-18,-1,-14,0,-4,
-4,-15,0,3,10,19,15,3,-32,-40,-34,-20,-20,5,-26,2,4,14,22,22,6,3,-3,3,0,-6,2,
14,11,4]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3
d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Nd7 {In my game vs Lettieri I tried first 10...
Re8 and only after repetition Ng5-Rf8-Nf3 played this} 11. Nbd2 {Now there are
two main options: to release the pressure and attack d4-pawn or try to put the
pressure without exchanging on d4. To conclude in both cases White has a
pleasant game since there are not enough forces to attack White's centre.} ({
Another option is} 11. a4 Na5 12. Bc2 c5 13. d5 {when White is slightly better.
}) 11... exd4 (11... Bf6 12. Nf1 g6 {Now White is flexible to choose slightly
different setups. Since I'm preparing Bg7 and covered in advance h5-f5 squares,
it makes sense to consider slightly different options to develop the knight
from f1.} (12... Re8 13. Ng3 g6 14. d5 Na5 15. Bc2 $14) 13. Ne3 {makes sense
since e4-square is not under pressure} (13. Bh6 $5 {It is very logical to put
more pressure on the kingside and try to develop some initiative around the
king.} Re8 14. N1h2 Na5 15. Bc2 Bg7 (15... c5 16. Ng4 Bh8 17. d5 $1 $16 {
It's always risky to allow this with such pieces like Na5 and Bb7. Furthermore,
White already improved a lot his position on the kingside so it looks like an
inferior Chigorin-style position.} Bc8 18. Bg5 f6 19. Nh6+ Kf8 20. Bc1 Bg7 21.
Nh2) 16. Ng4 Bxh6 17. Nxh6+ Kg7 18. Qc1 $14 {with very pleasant and long-term
edge}) (13. N1h2 $5 Bg7 (13... exd4 $2 14. cxd4 Na5 15. Ng4 Bg7 16. Bg5 Qe8 17.
Bc2 $18 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gg5h6]}) 14. Ng4 Kh8 15. a4 f5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Bg5 $1
Qe8 18. Ne3 $36 {This is a quite typical King's Indian style structure. It
looks double-edged from first sight but in fact, Black can hardly develop any
attack and at the same time it's not easy at all to hold f5-e5-b5 pawns and in
the same time to defend from numerous threats like Nd5, d5 and even Nh4.}) (13.
Ng3 Na5 14. Bc2 exd4 15. cxd4 c5 $132) 13... Bg7 14. a4 Nb6 (14... Na5 $5 15.
Bd5 $14) 15. a5 Nd7 16. Nd5 (16. h4 $5 {would be very very typical and also
unpleasant.}) 16... h6 17. Be3 $2 {probably blunder} ({It was a proper moment
to release the tension} 17. dxe5 $5 {maybe here White can't pretend for a big
advantage but still it's more pleasant everywhere} Ndxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. f4
Nd7 20. Be3 Nf6 21. f5 $5 Nxd5 22. Bxd5 Bxd5 23. Qxd5 g5 24. Qc6 $14) 17...
Nxa5 $1 {now I can transform to favourable structure} 18. Rxa5 c6 19. Ra1 cxd5
20. exd5 (20. Bxd5 Bxd5 21. exd5 e4 22. Nd2 f5 $15) 20... e4 21. Nd2 f5 22. Bf4
Nb6 23. c4 $2 {Now he is quickly collapsing} ({it was the last moment to
undermine while I'm not yet fully coordinated} 23. f3 $1 g5 24. Bh2 exf3 25.
Qxf3 Qd7 26. Re6 $1 Qxe6 27. dxe6 Bxf3 28. gxf3 d5 29. Bc7 Nc4 30. Nxc4 dxc4
31. Bc2 $44) 23... Kh7 24. c5 dxc5 25. dxc5 Nxd5 26. Bd6 Nb4 27. Nf1 Nd3 $19 {
0-1 (36) Lettieri,G  (2435) -Eljanov,P (2672) Chess. com INT 2020 CBM 196
Extra [Home]}) 12. cxd4 Bf6 13. Nf1 Na5 14. Bc2 Re8 15. Ng3 g6 16. b3 $6 {
Too soft though White has at least two good options} (16. Bh6 $5 Nc4 17. a4 $5
{I like a lot this sacrifice.} (17. b3 $5 {is more routine but also fine} Na3
18. Bd3 c5 19. Rc1 Rc8 (19... cxd4 20. Qd2 a5 21. Bf1 b4 22. Nxd4 $14) 20. Qd2
b4 21. Bf4 $16 a5 $2 22. Bxd6 $18 {1-0 (36) Van Foreest,J (2621)-Perez
Candelario,M (2621) Batumi 2019}) 17... bxa4 (17... Nxb2 18. Qb1 Nc4 19. axb5
axb5 20. Qxb5 $14) 18. b3 $1 axb3 19. Bxb3 Ncb6 20. Qd2 c5 21. Ng5 c4 22. Bc2
$44 {With a huge compensation. For a practical game Black is in deep trouble.})
(16. Rb1 $5 {A sound profilactic move. White is moving the rook in advance and
preparing b3. The idea is to meet ...c7-c5 with d4-d5.} c5 17. d5 Nc4 18. b3 (
18. Nh2 $5) 18... Nce5 (18... Ncb6 19. Nh2 Bg7 20. Ng4 Ne5 21. Ne3 a5 22. f4
Ned7 23. Nef5 $5 {not neccesary but typical and spectacular} (23. Kh2 $5) 23...
gxf5 24. Nxf5 $16 {with a huge attack}) 19. Nh2 $1 $16 {A typical retreat.
Having in mind Black is cramped it's logical to keep both knights on the board.
Ne5 and Nd7 - typical 'superfluous" piece.}) 16... c5 $1 17. Be3 Nc6 18. Rc1 h5
$2 {I wanted to get things as complicated as possible but it's a bit too much}
({Better would have been} 18... cxd4 $1 {transforming to another typical
structure. Having in mind Bc2 is a bit misplaced and Ng3 is restricted Black
has enough counterplay} 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Rc8 21. Qd2 Bxd4 22. Qxd4 Qg5 $1
$132 23. Qxd6 Ne5 24. Qa3 $2 (24. Red1 Red8 25. Qb6 $8 Rxd1+ 26. Rxd1 Rxc2 27.
Qxb7 h5 $44) 24... h5 25. Kh1 Qf4 26. Kg1 Qg5 27. Kh1 Rc3 28. Bb1 Nc4 {0-1 (28)
Can,I (2173)-Kovalev,V (2598) Lisbon 2017}) 19. Bb1 $2 (19. d5 $1 {of course
it was much better to play with this structure} Nce5 20. Nh2 $1 (20. Nxe5 Bxe5
21. f4 Bb2 $5 22. Rb1 Bc3 $132) 20... Nf8 21. f4 Ned7 22. Nf3 $16) 19... h4 20.
Ne2 cxd4 21. Nexd4 Nxd4 22. Bxd4 Ne5 23. Nh2 $1 Bg5 24. Be3 Bxe3 25. Rxe3 Qf6
26. Ng4 (26. Qd2 $5 {with some pressure}) 26... Qg5 $11 1/2-1/2

