{[%evp 0,43,21,37,9,8,25,8,-2,-10,3,0,23,5,8,8,14,-15,-11,-11,-8,-8,-1,0,27,-5,
-5,13,1,-7,-7,-32,-19,-26,-20,27,28,9,41,-7,5,-2,8,-1,38,-15]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10.
d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a3 ({Another possible option is} 12. Bc2 {White is
aiming at getting a Breyer type of position.} g6 13. d5 Nb8 14. b3 c6 15. c4
Nbd7 16. Nf1 Nc5 17. Ng3 a5 $5 {I like this plan} 18. Be3 (18. Bg5 Bg7 19. Nd2
Ba6 20. Rc1 Rc8 $132) 18... Ba6 19. cxb5 Bxb5 20. dxc6 Qc7 21. Rc1 Bxc6 {
A very typical Sicilian looking structure. Here and in many similar occasions
Black is doing OK since Ng3 is restricted and it's not that easy for White to
fight for the centre.} 22. Bxc5 (22. Nd2 Rab8 23. Qf3 Nfd7 $132) 22... dxc5 23.
Bd3 Qb7 24. Qc2 a4 25. Rcd1 axb3 26. axb3 Rad8 $11 27. Bc4 Rxd1 28. Qxd1 h6 $6
(28... Bb5 $5 29. Nd2 Bxc4 30. Nxc4 h5 $132) 29. Qe2 ({After one inaccuracy it
was possible to pose some problems after the typical} 29. h4 $5 h5 30. Ng5 Re7
31. Qf3 $14) 29... Bd7 30. Qb2 Be6 31. Qc2 Bxc4 32. bxc4 h5 {here White lost
the thread at some point and collapsed} 33. Rb1 Qc6 34. Rb5 Bh6 35. Qb1 Kg7 36.
Rb6 Qa4 37. Qb5 $2 (37. Qd3) 37... Qd1+ 38. Kh2 Qd8 39. Rb7 Bf4 $19 {0-1 (46)
Ter Sahakyan,S (2617)-Gharibyan,M (2381) Yerevan 2020}) 12... h6 13. d5 {
A rare line nowadays but not without venom.} Nb8 14. Nh2 Nbd7 ({The main idea
in this setup. White is preparing for} 14... c6 {and trying to play on the
light squares.} 15. dxc6 Nxc6 (15... Bxc6 {probably better}) 16. Ng4 $1 Nxg4
17. hxg4 Na5 18. Bd5 Qc8 19. a4 Bxd5 20. exd5 Nc4 21. Ne4 $14 {I was suffering
in another game vs Vladimir and lost .1-0 (41) Malakhov,V (2706)-Eljanov,P 
(2729) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009}) 15. Qf3 Be7 $5 {Looking a bit strange but makes
sense: I'm preparing in advance for Ng4 and my idea is to activate and trade
my passive bishop.} (15... c6 {also possible but a bit premature to my taste}
16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Ng4 Nc5 $5 {It seems like with some strong measures Black
can hope to get a normal play.} (17... Qe7 {Black made a draw in
correspondence game but I really dislike the trend of the game here} 18. Nf1
Nxg4 19. hxg4 Nc5 20. Ba2 g6 21. Ng3 Bg7 22. Be3 Qb7 (22... Ne6 23. Red1 $14)
23. Bxc5 dxc5 24. Bd5 Rad8 25. Rad1 c4 26. Nf1 (26. Bxc6 Qxc6 27. Nf1 Rxd1 28.
Rxd1 Bf8 29. Ne3 $14) 26... Bxd5 27. Rxd5 Rxd5 28. exd5 Qd7 29. Qe4 {1/2-1/2 
(29) Borwell,A (2182) -Alderisio,P (2434) ICCF email 2010} (29. Ng3 {[#]} e4 $1
(29... Rd8 30. Rd1 $16) 30. Rxe4 (30. Nxe4 f5) 30... Rd8 $1 $11)) 18. Nxf6+
Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. Bc2 Rad8 (20... Red8 $5) 21. b4 Na4 22. c4 Nb6 $132 {
And despite his weaknesses, Black is active and should equalise}) (15... a5 $5
{I like this. Before undermining the centre I'm trying to improve my position
on the queenside.} 16. Ndf1 (16. Ng4 Nxg4 17. hxg4 a4 18. Bc2 c6 $132) (16. a4
b4 17. cxb4 axb4 18. Ng4 c6 $5 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Qxf6 gxf6 $132) 16... Nc5 17.
Ba2 a4 $132) 16. Ndf1 (16. Ng4 Nxg4 17. Qxg4 Bg5 $132) 16... Nh7 $6 {This is a
bit too much. Instead, I had some flank pawn moves with similar ideas to grab
some space. Although it's more pleasant to play with White in my opinion} (
16... h5 $5 17. Ba2 g6 18. c4 Nb6 $132) (16... a5 $5 17. Ng3 (17. a4 Nc5) 17...
a4 18. Bc2 Bf8 19. Nf5 c6 20. dxc6 Bxc6 21. Be3 $14 {/=}) 17. Ng3 Bg5 18. Nf5 {
After this move, I managed to equalise} (18. c4 $1 {was better} Bc8 19. Qc3 $14
) 18... h5 (18... Bc8 $5) 19. Bc2 Bxc1 20. Raxc1 g6 21. Ne3 c5 22. Qe2 {
1/2-1/2 (22) Malakhov,V (2706)-Eljanov,P (2729) Khanty-Mansiysk 2009} 1/2-1/2

