{[%evp 0,52,19,32,28,24,16,23,23,5,9,9,27,8,8,10,10,-11,-18,-18,0,-10,0,-9,20,
17,27,20,20,-29,-16,-30,-33,-39,-37,-37,-34,-43,-6,-70,-45,-41,-41,-60,-59,-60,
-53,-49,-43,-104,-75,-52,-66,-70,-65]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6
5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12.
d5 {This continuation was quite popular about 10-15 years ago but now is out
of fashion.} Nb8 13. Nf1 Nbd7 14. N3h2 Nc5 15. Bc2 c6 16. b4 Ncd7 17. dxc6 Bxc6
18. Bg5 Qc7 19. Bxf6 Nxf6 20. Ng4 Nxg4 21. hxg4 {This position very much
reminds me of Sveshnikov. Seems like the best idea is exactly as in Sveshnikov
to activate dark-squared bishop.} a5 ({In my opinion the easiest is} 21... Be7
$5 {Typically, Black's bishop will cover a lot of important squares on h6-c1
diagonal} 22. Bb3 (22. Ne3 Bg5 23. Qd3 Qb7 24. Rad1 g6 25. Nd5 Kg7 26. g3 Rad8
27. Bb3 Qd7 28. Qf3 Rh8 $132) 22... Bg5 23. Qf3 Qb7 24. Rad1 Red8 25. Bd5 Bxd5
26. Rxd5 Rac8 $132) 22. bxa5 ({The best try probably is} 22. Ne3 $5 Qb7 (22...
Rec8 $5 23. Qd3 Qb7 $132) 23. g5 (23. a4 $5) 23... axb4 24. cxb4 Ra3 25. Rc1
Rxa2 $2 {Exemplary game which is covering Black's dangers in this line} (25...
Rc8 26. Bb3 Bxe4 27. Rxc8 Qxc8 28. Nd5 $44 {still it's much easier to play
with White}) 26. Bb3 Rb2 27. Bd5 Bxd5 28. Nxd5 {Now it's clear that despite
the extra pawn Blackis strategically lost as Nd5 is simply dominating} Rc8 29.
Re3 (29. Qf3 $1 Rbc2 30. Rxc2 Rxc2 31. Ra1 $16) 29... Rxc1 30. Qxc1 {1-0 (39)
Naiditsch,A (2700) -Efimenko, Z (2682) Poikovsky 2009}) 22... Qb7 23. Ne3 (23.
Qf3 $5) 23... Rxa5 24. Bb3 Bxe4 25. Nd5 Bxd5 26. Bxd5 Qc7 $11 {1/2 (39)-1/2 
(39) Bacrot,E (2728) -Eljanov,P (2693) Nalchik 2009} 1/2-1/2

