{[%evp 0,43,32,28,18,18,18,-4,13,6,9,9,26,-1,10,7,16,-18,-10,-10,-6,0,-6,-5,17,
17,-1,10,21,26,23,39,46,39,35,44,55,40,56,41,42,41,17,34,23,2]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3
Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10.
d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a3 h6 13. Bc2 {The most popular line nowadays.White
wants to transform to some kind of Breyer but with inclusion of h6 and a3
moves. Since White normally plays a3-a4 anyway, it means that Black has an
extra h6 move which is normally useful.} Nb8 14. b3 Nbd7 15. Bb2 ({A bit
premature is} 15. a4 {although it's strange that nobody played} d5 $1 $146 {
it's very typical idea here to play d5 and smash everything in the centre} 16.
dxe5 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Bxe4 Bxe4 19. Rxe4 {[#]} Nxe5 $11) 15... Nb6 $6 {
This idea I explored in Breyer but it seems like it only makes sense against
a4 and the problem is that White is not forced to play it. Besides that I can
suggest two options} ({A modern try. Black is trying to fortify the b5-pawn in
advance} 15... Rb8 $5 16. Rb1 $5 {following the waiting strategy as well} ({
Seems like White can't count on advantage in case of straightforward play} 16.
a4 Ba8 17. axb5 (17. b4 Nb6 18. axb5 axb5 $132) 17... axb5 18. Bd3 d5 $1 19.
exd5 exd4 20. Rxe8 Qxe8 $11) 16... g6 17. Bd3 c6 $6 {Too passive. Such a move
makes sense against a4 but now I don't see any reason to play it in advance.} (
17... Bg7 $5 18. dxe5 $5 {and again it's the best try to fight for an advantage
} (18. Qc2 d5 $1 {it works as in many similar occasions} 19. dxe5 Nxe4 20. Nxe4
dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Nxe5 $11) 18... dxe5 19. Qc2 c5 20. c4 {but with
precise play Black can get a decent position} b4 $1 21. Nf1 Nh7 22. Ne3 Nhf8
23. Nd5 a5 $132 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ge6d4] Black is also about to transfer the knight
to d4 with complicated play}) (17... d5 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. dxe5) 18. Qc2 Nh5 19.
Bf1 Ng7 20. dxe5 $1 {Very typical and in style. White is well prepared for
central actions. He easily gets an advantage.} dxe5 21. c4 Rc8 22. Rbd1 Qe7 23.
c5 Nxc5 24. Nxe5 $16 {1-0 (63) Firouzja,A (2770) -Predke,A (2666) Riga 2021}) (
15... g6 $5 16. a4 (16. Bd3 Bg7 17. dxe5 dxe5 18. c4 Nc5 19. Bc2 Nh5 20. b4 Nd3
21. Bxd3 Qxd3 22. Re3 Qd7 $132) (16. b4 $5 Bg7 17. dxe5 dxe5 (17... Nxe5 18.
Nxe5 Rxe5 (18... dxe5 19. Nb3 $14) 19. c4 Re8 20. Rc1 c5 21. bxc5 dxc5 22. e5
Nd7 23. f4 $36 {1/2 (46)-1/2 (46) Merrheim,X (2404) -Bobel,P (2284) ICCF email
2015}) 18. a4 Bf8 $1 {It's important to increase the influence on the queenside
} 19. Qe2 c6 20. Red1 Qb6 (20... Qc7 $5 21. Bb3 bxa4 22. Bxa4 c5 $132) 21. Bd3
Nh5 (21... Rab8 {1/2-1/2 (35) Romm,M (2463)-Ghysens, D (2419) ICCF email 2019})
22. a5 Qc7 23. Qe3 c5 $132) 16... Bg7 17. dxe5 (17. Bd3 bxa4 $1 (17... d5 {
not precise immediately} 18. axb5 axb5 19. exd5 Rxa1 20. Qxa1 Nxd5 21. Bxb5
exd4 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23. cxd4 Qc8 24. Bf1 (24. Qa7 $5 $14) 24... N7b6 25. Qc1
Qf5 $6 26. Ne5 $14 {1/2 (33)-1/2 (55) Bologan,V (2610) -Drygalov,S (2418)
Sochi 2018}) 18. Rxa4 d5 $1 19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Nxe4 21. Nf3 c5 $132) 17...
Nxe5 $5 {It makes sense to exchange a pair of knights here} ({but also not bad
} 17... dxe5) 18. Nxe5 dxe5 19. b4 Bf8 20. Qe2 Nh5 $1 21. Nf3 Nf4 22. Qf1 c6 (
